{"title_page": "Natalie Chou", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Natalie Chou\n| image = \n| caption = \n| number = 23\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb =\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = UCLA Bruins\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West]] ([[Plano, Texas]])\n| college =\n*[[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA]] (2018\u2013present)\n| highlights =\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] (2016)\n}}\n'''Natalie Chou''' (born December 22, 1997<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Chou|website=FIBA.basketball|url= https://www.fiba.basketball/world/u17women/2014/player/Natalie-Chou|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>) is an American [[college basketball]] player for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA Bruins]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Growing up in [[Texas]], she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] as a high school senior in 2016.  Chou played two seasons of college ball for the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor Lady Bears]] before transferring to UCLA.\n\n==Early life==\nChou was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], to Quanli Li and Joseph Chou.<ref>{{cite news|title=WBB Signs Impressive Recruiting Class|date=November 11, 2015|publisher=Baylor University|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2015/11/11/WBB_Signs_Impressive_Recruiting_Class.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Her mother played basketball for the [[China women's national basketball team|Chinese national team]] before playing professionally in China. She moved to the United States in the mid-1990's with her husband when he received the opportunity to study abroad at [[Lamar University]] in [[Beaumont, Texas]].<ref name=fuchs>{{cite news|last=Fuchs|first=Jeremy|title=Impressive Lineage|year=2017|website=Time.com|url=https://time.com/collection/american-voices-2017/5028327/american-voices-natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=horn_01212016>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=Barry|title=Nothing comes easy|date=January 21, 2016|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=http://interactives.dallasnews.com/2016/natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> When Chou was one week old, she stopped breathing and was rushed to a hospital, where she was revived. She was diagnosed with [[human respiratory syncytial virus]] (RSV), a condition she no longer has.<ref name=villa_07032014>{{cite news|last=Villa|first=Walter|title=A healthy appetite for life, basketball|date=July 3, 2014|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/11171844/hoopgurlz-hungry-natalie-chou-representing-team-usa-fiba-u17-world-championships|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his master's degree, Joseph moved the family to [[Plano, Texas|Plano]] for his work.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Li became a basketball instructor for kids. Chou's parents' relationship deteriorated, and they eventually separated.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Raised in Plano,<ref name=chou_03262020/> Chou grew up with her older sister Tingting, who was trained in basketball by their mom. As Chou grew older, she became the more talented player, while her sister took after their father and was more into academics.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Chou continued training under Li, but also played on then-[[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Jason Terry]]'s girl's [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) team from sixth through ninth grade.{{efn|Terry played 19 seasons (1999\u20132018) in the NBA, earning the [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award]] in 2009 and winning an NBA championship with the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Mike|title=Mavs fave Jason Terry joining G-League Legends as assistant GM|date=September 18, 2019|website=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/mavericks/news/mavs-fave-jason-terry-joining-g-league-legends-as-assistant-gm|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=fuchs/><ref name=villa_07032014/> Terry first noticed Chou while preparing his daughter and her sixth-grade basketball team.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Judging by her skills, he estimated that Chou was in high school.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Terry was surprised to learn that she was only in sixth grade, and he was curious how her mom learned the NBA drills.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\nChou attended [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West High]], where she was a three-time all-state player.<ref name=waco_06162018>{{cite news|title=Lady Bears\u2019 Chou transferring to UCLA|date=June 16, 2018|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/lady-bears-chou-transferring-to-ucla/article_c59f0207-6876-5cdf-9bef-a7398d5c303b.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] and was one of five finalist for the [[Morgan Wootten National Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=fuchs/><ref>{{cite news|title=McDonald's All American Game names boys and girls finalists for Morgan Wootten award|date=March 3, 2016|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/mcdonalds-all-american-game-names-boys-and-girls-finalists-for-morgan-wootten-award|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Chou was a five-star recruit, and [[ESPN]]'s HoopGurlz ranked her No. 8 in the nation in the class of 2016.<ref name=riddle_04082020>{{cite news|last=Riddle|first=Greg|title=Natalie Chou, a former 5-star basketball recruit from Plano West, is granted release from Baylor and will transfer|date=April 8, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-a-former-5-star-basketball-recruit-from-plano-west-is-granted-release-from-baylor-and-will-transfer/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Some Chinese media outlets called her \"the female [[Jeremy Lin]]\", likely more related to her ethnicity.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Why Jeremy Lin and Jason Terry are rooting for Natalie Chou|date=December 4, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18188723/why-jeremy-lin-jason-terry-rooting-baylor-natalie-chou-women-college-basketball|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=riddle_04082020/> Terry said her play was \"not as flashy as Jeremy\", but praised her fundamentals.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\n==College basketball==\nChou committed to attend [[Baylor University]], where she and her high school rival, [[Lauren Cox]], helped form one of the top recruiting classes in the country.<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Will hyped Baylor freshmen go from local rivals to perfect pair?|date=November 18, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com.sg/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18058478/baylor-natalie-chou-lauren-cox-go-rivals-teammates-college-basketball|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in [[2016\u201317 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2016\u201317]], Chou played in all 37 games as a [[reserve (sport)|reserve]] and averaged 4.7 points, 2.1 rebounds and 1.6 assists per game as the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Lady Bears]] reached the [[Elite Eight]] of the [[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2017 NCAA Tournament]]. She led Baylor with a 42.3 [[three-point field goal percentage]], which ranked sixth in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref name=waco_06162018/>\n\nThe following season in [[2017\u201318 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2017\u201318]], Chou was a [[starting lineup|starter]] in the first 21 games before undergoing surgery for a broken bone in her non-shooting wrist.<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=ap_05072018>{{cite news|title=Natalie Chou will transfer from Big 12 champion Baylor|date=May 7, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|agency=AP|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaw/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-will-transfer-from-big-12-champion-baylor/34665327/|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> She returned for the final six games as Baylor advanced to the Sweet Sixteen in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]], but she was scoreless after her return, totaling 35 minutes and shooting 0-for-8 with all but one shot from three-point range.<ref name=ap_05072018/> She averaged 6.7 points, 3.3 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.1 steals for the season.<ref name=waco_06162018/> Needing a change of scenery,<ref name=dsouza_01302020>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Dylan|title=Natalie Chou carries on basketball tradition passed on from her mother|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Daily Bruin|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-carries-on-basketball-tradition-passed-on-from-her-mother/|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Chou decided after the season to transfer to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> \"[The injury] kind of changed the dynamics of a lot of the relationships, and I didn\u2019t like that kind of pressure,\" she said.<ref name=dsouza_01302020/>\n\nDue to [[NCAA]] transfer rules, Chou sat out a season as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] and served on the [[practice squad]] for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|Bruins]] in [[2018\u201319 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2018\u201319]].<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=nguyen_11042019>{{cite news|last=Nguyen|first=Thuc Nhi|title=UCLA, USC women\u2019s basketball teams will get a boost from youngsters|date=November 4, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-11-04/ucla-usc-womens-basketball-teams-will-get-a-boost-from-youngsters|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Eligible to play in [[2019\u201320 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2019\u201320]], she was expected to boost UCLA's outside shooting after they ranked next-to-last in three-point percentage in the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] (30.6%) and last in three-pointers made per game (5).<ref name=nguyen_11042019/> On January 24, 2020, Chou made a season-high four 3-pointers and scored 18 points in career-high 33 minutes in an 85\u201380 overtime win over [[Washington Huskies women's basketball|Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Vanoni|first=Maggie|title=Natalie Chou raising her game as UCLA women\u2019s basketball team enters toughest stretch|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-raising-her-game-as-ucla-womens-basketball-team-enters-toughest-stretch/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She was a part-time starter during the season and averaged 7.6 points and 3.6 rebounds while making 31.1% of her three-pointers for UCLA, who finished 26\u20135 and ranked No. 10 nationally.<ref name=bolch_03222020/> Their season ended prematurely, however, when the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]] was cancelled due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=chou_03262020/>\n\n==National team career==\nChou helped the [[United States women's national under-17 basketball team|United States under-17 team]] win a gold medal at the [[2014 FIBA Under-17 World Championship for Women|2014 FIBA U-17 World Championship]].<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016/> She also won a silver medal playing [[3x3 basketball]] with the [[United States women's national 3x3 team#2015 U18|2015 U.S U-18 3x3 team]] at the [[FIBA 3x3 U-18 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plano West's Natalie Chou, Team USA win silver in 3-on-3 FIBA tourney|date=June 9, 2015|newspaper=Plano Star Courier|url=https://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/plano-west-s-natalie-chou-team-usa-win-silver-in/article_9a31667a-0ed1-11e5-a839-ef4fb3e21b61.html|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Chou spoke out against the rise in animosity towards [[Asian Americans]] since the spread of the virus which originated in China.<ref name=sherrington_04042020>{{cite news|last=Sherrington|first=Kevin|title=Ex-Plano West star Natalie Chou speaks out against anti-Asian racism fueled by coronavirus pandemic|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2020/04/04/ex-plano-west-star-natalie-chou-speaks-out-against-anti-asian-racism-fueled-by-coronavirus-pandemic/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After flying home following the the 2019\u201320 season, she was afraid to leave her [[Dallas]]-area home.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=bolch_03222020/> Although she had been used to being stared at for being a {{convert|6|ft|1|in|adj=on}} Asian female, Chou said the looks were now hateful.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> She felt safer going out wearing clothes with ''UCLA'' on it,<ref name=bolch_03222020/><ref name=sherrington_04042020/> as she hoped to ease people's fears by showing that she was a basketball player and \"not just a Chinese person [that others] need to stay away from.\"<ref name=sherrington_04042020/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=NatalieChou1|author=Natalie Chou|number=1246201661124685826|date=April 4, 2020|title=Thank you for referencing me in your article ...|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Later that month, Chou posted on [[Twitter]] about her experience, which was followed by a story in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and later her first-person account on [[ESPN.com]]. She attributed the growing resentment towards Asian Americans to the use of the slang term ''Chinese virus'', which she stated was \"disrespectful and ultimately racist\" and created \"unnecessary [[xenophobia]]\".<ref name=bolch_03222020>{{cite news|last=Bolch|first=Ben|title=UCLA\u2019s Natalie Chou talks about racism and being associated with 'the Chinese virus'|date=March 22, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/story/2020-03-22/ucla-natalie-chou-talks-racism-the-chinese-virus|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sherrington_04042020/>  Since 2015, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has recommended to not name infectious diseases after geographic locations due to the negative impact on countries, economies and people.<ref name=chou_03262020>{{cite news|last=Chou|first=Natalie|editor-last=Gobson|editor-first=Charlotte|title=UCLA's Natalie Chou won't stand for anti-Asian racism related to coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/story/_/id/28955666/20|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=chow_03302020>{{cite news|last=Chow|first=Cary|title=Why it is NOT the 'Chinese virus'|date=March 30, 2020|website=The Undefeated|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/why-it-is-not-the-chinese-virus/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> According to Chou, \"It takes literally no effort to call it by its correct name {{bracket|, [[COVID-19]]}}.\"<ref name=chow_03302020/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://uclabruins.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/natalie-chou/8969 UCLA Bruins bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chou, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor Lady Bears basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plano, Texas\u200e]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Natalie Chou\n| image = \n| caption = \n| number = 23\n| position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6 \n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb =\n| league = [[Pac-12 Conference]]\n| team = UCLA Bruins\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|12|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Beaumont, Texas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West]] ([[Plano, Texas]])\n| college =\n*[[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA]] (2018\u2013present)\n| highlights =\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] (2016)\n}}\n'''Natalie Chou''' (born December 22, 1997<ref>{{cite web|title=Natalie Chou|website=FIBA.basketball|url= https://www.fiba.basketball/world/u17women/2014/player/Natalie-Chou|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>) is an American [[college basketball]] player for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|UCLA Bruins]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Growing up in [[Texas]], she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] as a high school senior in 2016.  Chou played two seasons of college ball for the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Baylor Lady Bears]] before transferring to UCLA.\n\n==Early life==\nChou was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]], to Quanli Li and Joseph Chou.<ref>{{cite news|title=WBB Signs Impressive Recruiting Class|date=November 11, 2015|publisher=Baylor University|url=https://baylorbears.com/news/2015/11/11/WBB_Signs_Impressive_Recruiting_Class.aspx|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Her mother played basketball for the [[China women's national basketball team|Chinese national team]] before playing professionally in China. She moved to the United States in the mid-1990's with her husband when he received the opportunity to study abroad at [[Lamar University]] in [[Beaumont, Texas]].<ref name=fuchs>{{cite news|last=Fuchs|first=Jeremy|title=Impressive Lineage|year=2017|website=Time.com|url=https://time.com/collection/american-voices-2017/5028327/american-voices-natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=horn_01212016>{{cite news|last=Horn|first=Barry|title=Nothing comes easy|date=January 21, 2016|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=http://interactives.dallasnews.com/2016/natalie-chou/|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> When Chou was one week old, she stopped breathing and was rushed to a hospital, where she was revived. She was diagnosed with [[human respiratory syncytial virus]] (RSV), a condition she no longer has.<ref name=villa_07032014>{{cite news|last=Villa|first=Walter|title=A healthy appetite for life, basketball|date=July 3, 2014|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/11171844/hoopgurlz-hungry-natalie-chou-representing-team-usa-fiba-u17-world-championships|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter earning his master's degree, Joseph moved the family to [[Plano, Texas|Plano]] for his work.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Li became a basketball instructor for kids. Chou's parents' relationship deteriorated, and they eventually separated.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Raised in Plano,<ref name=chou_03262020/> Chou grew up with her older sister Tingting, who was trained in basketball by their mom. As Chou grew older, she became the more talented player, while her sister took after their father and was more into academics.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Chou continued training under Li, but also played on then-[[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) player [[Jason Terry]]'s girl's [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) team from sixth through ninth grade.{{efn|Terry played 19 seasons (1999\u20132018) in the NBA, earning the [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award]] in 2009 and winning an NBA championship with the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Mike|title=Mavs fave Jason Terry joining G-League Legends as assistant GM|date=September 18, 2019|website=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/mavericks/news/mavs-fave-jason-terry-joining-g-league-legends-as-assistant-gm|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=fuchs/><ref name=villa_07032014/> Terry first noticed Chou while preparing his daughter and her sixth-grade basketball team.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> Judging by her skills, he estimated that Chou was in high school.<ref name=horn_01212016/> Terry was surprised to learn that she was only in sixth grade, and he was curious how her mom learned the NBA drills.<ref name=horn_01212016/><ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/> \n\nChou attended [[Plano West Senior High School|Plano West High]], where she was a three-time all-state player.<ref name=waco_06162018>{{cite news|title=Lady Bears\u2019 Chou transferring to UCLA|date=June 16, 2018|newspaper=Waco Tribune-Herald|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/sports/college/baylor/lady-bears-chou-transferring-to-ucla/article_c59f0207-6876-5cdf-9bef-a7398d5c303b.html|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a senior in 2016, she was named a [[McDonald\u2019s All-American]] and was one of five finalist for the [[Morgan Wootten National Player of the Year]] award.<ref name=fuchs/><ref>{{cite news|title=McDonald's All American Game names boys and girls finalists for Morgan Wootten award|date=March 3, 2016|newspaper=USA Today|url=https://usatodayhss.com/2016/mcdonalds-all-american-game-names-boys-and-girls-finalists-for-morgan-wootten-award|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Chou was a five-star recruit, and [[ESPN]]'s HoopGurlz ranked her No. 8 in the nation in the class of 2016.<ref name=riddle_04082020>{{cite news|last=Riddle|first=Greg|title=Natalie Chou, a former 5-star basketball recruit from Plano West, is granted release from Baylor and will transfer|date=April 8, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-a-former-5-star-basketball-recruit-from-plano-west-is-granted-release-from-baylor-and-will-transfer/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Some Chinese media outlets called her \"the female [[Jeremy Lin]]\", likely more related to her ethnicity.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Why Jeremy Lin and Jason Terry are rooting for Natalie Chou|date=December 4, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18188723/why-jeremy-lin-jason-terry-rooting-baylor-natalie-chou-women-college-basketball|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=riddle_04082020/> Terry said her play was \"not as flashy as Jeremy\", but praised her fundamentals.<ref name=youngmisuk_12042016/>\n\n==College basketball==\nChou committed to attend [[Baylor University]], where she and her high school rival, [[Lauren Cox]], helped form one of the top recruiting classes in the country.<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016>{{cite news|last=Youngmisuk|first=Ohm|title=Will hyped Baylor freshmen go from local rivals to perfect pair?|date=November 18, 2016|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com.sg/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/18058478/baylor-natalie-chou-lauren-cox-go-rivals-teammates-college-basketball|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> As a freshman in [[2016\u201317 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2016\u201317]], Chou played in all 37 games as a [[reserve (sport)|reserve]] and averaged 4.7 points, 2.1 rebounds and 1.6 assists per game as the [[Baylor Lady Bears basketball|Lady Bears]] reached the [[Elite Eight]] of the [[2017 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2017 NCAA Tournament]]. She led Baylor with a 42.3 [[three-point field goal percentage]], which ranked sixth in the [[Big 12 Conference]].<ref name=waco_06162018/>\n\nThe following season in [[2017\u201318 Baylor Lady Bears basketball team|2017\u201318]], Chou was a [[starting lineup|starter]] in the first 21 games before undergoing surgery for a broken bone in her non-shooting wrist.<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=ap_05072018>{{cite news|title=Natalie Chou will transfer from Big 12 champion Baylor|date=May 7, 2018|newspaper=USA Today|agency=AP|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaw/2018/05/07/natalie-chou-will-transfer-from-big-12-champion-baylor/34665327/|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref> She returned for the final six games as Baylor advanced to the Sweet Sixteen in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]], but she was scoreless after her return, totaling 35 minutes and shooting 0-for-8 with all but one shot from three-point range.<ref name=ap_05072018/> She averaged 6.7 points, 3.3 rebounds, 2.3 assists and 1.1 steals for the season.<ref name=waco_06162018/> Needing a change of scenery,<ref name=dsouza_01302020>{{cite news|last=D'Souza|first=Dylan|title=Natalie Chou carries on basketball tradition passed on from her mother|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Daily Bruin|url=https://dailybruin.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-carries-on-basketball-tradition-passed-on-from-her-mother/|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> Chou decided after the season to transfer to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=waco_06162018/> \"[The injury] kind of changed the dynamics of a lot of the relationships, and I didn\u2019t like that kind of pressure,\" she said.<ref name=dsouza_01302020/>\n\nDue to [[NCAA]] transfer rules, Chou sat out a season as a [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] and served on the [[practice squad]] for the [[UCLA Bruins women's basketball|Bruins]] in [[2018\u201319 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2018\u201319]].<ref name=waco_06162018/><ref name=nguyen_11042019>{{cite news|last=Nguyen|first=Thuc Nhi|title=UCLA, USC women\u2019s basketball teams will get a boost from youngsters|date=November 4, 2019|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2019-11-04/ucla-usc-womens-basketball-teams-will-get-a-boost-from-youngsters|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Eligible to play in [[2019\u201320 UCLA Bruins women's basketball team|2019\u201320]], she was expected to boost UCLA's outside shooting after they ranked next-to-last in three-point percentage in the [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] (30.6%) and last in three-pointers made per game (5).<ref name=nguyen_11042019/> On January 24, 2020, Chou made a season-high four 3-pointers and scored 18 points in career-high 33 minutes in an 85\u201380 overtime win over [[Washington Huskies women's basketball|Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Vanoni|first=Maggie|title=Natalie Chou raising her game as UCLA women\u2019s basketball team enters toughest stretch|date=January 30, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=https://www.dailynews.com/2020/01/30/natalie-chou-raising-her-game-as-ucla-womens-basketball-team-enters-toughest-stretch/|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She was a part-time starter during the season and averaged 7.6 points and 3.6 rebounds while making 31.1% of her three-pointers for UCLA, who finished 26\u20135 and ranked No. 10 nationally.<ref name=bolch_03222020/> Their season ended prematurely, however, when the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]] was cancelled due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=chou_03262020/>\n\n==National team career==\nChou helped the [[United States women's national under-17 basketball team|United States under-17 team]] win a gold medal at the [[2014 FIBA Under-17 World Championship for Women|2014 FIBA U-17 World Championship]].<ref name=youngmisuk_11182016/> She also won a silver medal playing [[3x3 basketball]] with the [[United States women's national 3x3 team#2015 U18|2015 U.S U-18 3x3 team]] at the [[FIBA 3x3 U-18 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plano West's Natalie Chou, Team USA win silver in 3-on-3 FIBA tourney|date=June 9, 2015|newspaper=Plano Star Courier|url=https://starlocalmedia.com/planocourier/sports/plano-west-s-natalie-chou-team-usa-win-silver-in/article_9a31667a-0ed1-11e5-a839-ef4fb3e21b61.html|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nDuring the coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Chou spoke out against the rise in animosity towards [[Asian Americans]] since the spread of the virus which originated in China.<ref name=sherrington_04042020>{{cite news|last=Sherrington|first=Kevin|title=Ex-Plano West star Natalie Chou speaks out against anti-Asian racism fueled by coronavirus pandemic|date=April 4, 2020|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/high-school-sports/2020/04/04/ex-plano-west-star-natalie-chou-speaks-out-against-anti-asian-racism-fueled-by-coronavirus-pandemic/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> After flying home following the the 2019\u201320 season, she was afraid to leave her [[Dallas]]-area home.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=bolch_03222020/> Although she had been used to being stared at for being a {{convert|6|ft|1|in|adj=on}} Asian female, Chou said the looks were now hateful.<ref name=chou_03262020/><ref name=<ref name=sherrington_04042020/> She felt safer going out wearing clothes with ''UCLA'' on it,<ref name=bolch_03222020/><ref name=<ref name=sherrington_04042020/> as she hoped to ease people's fears by showing that she was a basketball player and \"not just a Chinese person [that others] need to stay away from.\"<ref name=<ref name=sherrington_04042020/><ref>{{cite tweet|user=NatalieChou1|author=Natalie Chou|number=1246201661124685826|date=April 4, 2020|title=Thank you for referencing me in your article ...|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Later that month, Chou posted on [[Twitter]] about her experience, which was followed by a story in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' and later her first-person account on [[ESPN.com]]. She attributed the growing resentment towards Asian Americans to the use of the slang term ''Chinese virus'', which she stated was \"disrespectful and ultimately racist\" and created \"unnecessary [[xenophobia]]\".<ref name=bolch_03222020>{{cite news|last=Bolch|first=Ben|title=UCLA\u2019s Natalie Chou talks about racism and being associated with 'the Chinese virus'|date=March 22, 2020|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/story/2020-03-22/ucla-natalie-chou-talks-racism-the-chinese-virus|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=<ref name=sherrington_04042020/>  Since 2015, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has recommended to not name infectious diseases after geographic locations due to the negative impact on countries, economies and people.<ref name=chou_03262020>{{cite news|last=Chou|first=Natalie|editor-last=Gobson|editor-first=Charlotte|title=UCLA's Natalie Chou won't stand for anti-Asian racism related to coronavirus|date=March 26, 2020|website=ESPN.com|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/voices/story/_/id/28955666/20|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=chow_03302020>{{cite news|last=Chow|first=Cary|title=Why it is NOT the 'Chinese virus'|date=March 30, 2020|website=The Undefeated|url=https://theundefeated.com/features/why-it-is-not-the-chinese-virus/|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> According to Chou, \"It takes literally no effort to call it by its correct name {{bracket|, [[COVID-19]]}}.\"<ref name=chow_03302020/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://uclabruins.com/sports/womens-basketball/roster/natalie-chou/8969 UCLA Bruins bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chou, Natalie}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American women's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Texas]]\n[[Category:Baylor Lady Bears basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Plano, Texas\u200e]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins women's basketball players]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref tags fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_Chou"}
{"title_page": "Suggestopedia", "text_new": "\n\n{{POV check|date=October 2010}}\n\n'''Suggestopedia''' is a teaching method developed by the Bulgarian psychotherapist [[Georgi Lozanov]]. It is used mostly to learn foreign languages.\n\nThe theory applied positive [[suggestion]] in teaching when it was developed in the 1970s. However, as the method improved, it has focused more on \"desuggestive learning\" and now is often called \"desuggestopedia\".<ref name=\"one\">Lozanov, Georgi. ''Suggestology and Suggestopedy''. http://lozanov.hit.bg/ 4/30/2006</ref> Suggestopedia is a [[portmanteau]] of the words \"suggestion\" and \"[[pedagogy]]\". A common misconception is to link \"suggestion\" to \"hypnosis\". However, Lozanov intended it in the sense of offering or proposing, emphasising student choice.\n\n==In practice==\nPhysical surroundings and atmosphere in classroom are the vital factors to make sure that \"the students feel comfortable and confident\",<ref name=\"three\">Harmer, Jeremy. ''The Practice of English Language Teaching. 3rd Edition.'' Person Education Limited, 2001</ref> and various techniques, including art and music, are used by the trained teachers.\nThe lesson of Suggestopedia consisted of three phases at first: deciphering, concert session (memorization s\u00e9ance), and elaboration.<ref name=\"one\"/><ref name=\"two\">Lozanov, Georgi. ''Suggestopaedia - Desuggestive Teaching Communicative Method on the Level of the Hidden Reserves of the Human Mind''. http://dr-lozanov.dir.bg/book/start_book.htm 4/30/2006</ref>\n\n'''Deciphering:''' The teacher introduces the grammar and lexis of the content. In most materials the foreign language text is on the left half of the page with a translation on the right half, i.e. meanings are conveyed via the mother tongue not unlike the [[bilingual method]].\n\n'''Concert session (active and passive):''' In the active session, the teacher reads the text at a normal speed, sometimes intoning some words, and the students follow. In the passive session, the students relax and listen to the teacher reading the text calmly. Baroque music is played in the background.\n\n'''Elaboration:'''\nThe students finish off what they have learned with dramas, songs, and games.\n\nThen it has developed into four phases as lots of experiments were done: introduction, concert session, elaboration, and production.<ref name=\"one\"/><ref name=\"two\"/>\n\n'''Introduction:''' The teacher teaches the material in \"a playful manner\" instead of analyzing lexis and grammar of the text in a directive manner.\n\n'''Concert session (active and passive):''' In the active session, the teacher reads with intoning as [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Musical_Selections_for_Suggestopedia_Concert_Sessions.pdf selected music] is played. Occasionally, the students read the text together with the teacher, and listen only to the music as the teacher pauses in particular moments. The passive session is done more calmly.\n\n'''Elaboration:''' The students sing classical songs and play games while \"the teacher acts more like a consultant\".<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n'''Production:''' The students spontaneously speak and interact in the target language without interruption or correction.\n\n==Teachers==\nTeachers should not act in a directive way, although this method is teacher-controlled and not student-controlled. For example, they should act as a real partner to the students, participating in the activities such as games and songs \"naturally\" and \"genuinely.\" <ref name=\"one\"/> In the concert session, they should fully include classical art in their behaviors. Although there are many techniques that the teachers use, factors such as \"communication in the spirit of love, respect for man as a human being, the specific humanitarian way of applying their 'techniques'\" etc. are crucial.<ref name=\"two\"/> The teachers not only need to know the techniques and to acquire the practical [[methodology]] completely, but also to fully understand the theory, because, if they implement those techniques without complete understanding, they will not be able to lead their learners to successful results, or they could even cause a negative impact on their learning. Therefore, the teacher has to be trained in a course taught by certified trainers.\n\nHere are the most important factors for teachers to acquire, described by Lozanov.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n# Covering a huge bulk of learning material.\n# Structuring the material in the suggestopaedic way: global-partial \u2013 partial-global, and global in the part \u2013 part in the global, related to the golden proportion.\n# As a professional, on one hand, and a personality, on the other hand, the teacher should be a highly regarded professional, reliable and credible.\n# The teacher should have, not play, a hundred percent expectation of positive results (because the teacher is already experienced even from the time of the teacher training course).\n# The teacher should love his/her students (of course, not sentimentally but as human beings) and teach them with personal participation through games, songs, classical arts, and pleasure.\n\n==Method for children (preventive Suggestopedia)==\nThe method for Adults includes long sessions without movement,<ref name=\"one\"/> and materials that are appropriate for adults. Children, however, get impacts from \"the social suggestive norms\" differently, and their brains are more delicate than those of adults. Therefore, another method with different materials should be applied to children, which better matches their characteristics. Lessons for children are more incidental and short, preventing the children from the negative pedagogical suggestions of Society. It is important to tell the parents about the method and their roles \u2013 because they could influence children both negatively and positively, depending on how they support the kids.<ref name=\"two\"/>\n\n==Side effects==\nLozanov claims that the effect of the method is not only in language learning, but also in producing favorable side effects on health, the social and psychological relations, and the subsequent success in other subjects.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nSuggestopedia has been called a \"pseudo-science\".<ref name=\"richards\">Richards, J.C. and Rodgers, T.S. (2001). Approaches and Methods in Language Teaching (2nd ed.). Cambridge: Cambridge University Press</ref> It depends, in a sense, on the trust that students develop towards the method. Lozanov never admitted that Suggestopedia can be compared to a placebo. He argues, however, that placebos are indeed effective. Another point of criticism is brought forward by Baur, who claims that the students only receive input by listening, reading and musical-emotional backing, while other important factors of language acquisition are being neglected.<ref>Baur, R.S. (1984). Die Psychop\u00e4dische Variante der Suggestop\u00e4die (Psychop\u00e4die). In Bauer, H.L. (Ed.), Unterrichtspraxis und theoretische Fundierung in Deutsch als Fremdsprache. (pp. 291-326 ). M\u00fcnchen: Goethe-Institut.</ref> Furthermore, several other features of the method \u2013 like the 'nonconscious' acquisition of language, or bringing the learner into a childlike state \u2013 are questioned by critics.\n\nLukesch claims that Suggestopedia lacks scientific backing and is criticized by psychologists as being based on pseudoscience.<ref>Lukesch, H. (2000): Lernen ohne Anstrengung? Der Sirenengesang der geheimen Verf\u00fchrer. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr P\u00e4dagogische Psychologie/German Journal of Educational Psychology, 14, 59-62.</ref>\n\n==Later variations==\n\nSuggestopedia yielded four main offshoots. The first \u2013 still called Suggestopedia, and  developed in eastern Europe \u2013 used different techniques from Lozanov's original version. The other three are named ''[[Superlearning]]'', ''Suggestive Accelerated Learning and Teaching'' (SALT), and ''Psychop\u00e4die''.<ref name=\"Felix1989\">{{cite book | url=http://users.monash.edu.au/~ufelix/thesis2-7.htm | title=An Investigation of the Effects of Music, Relaxation and Suggestion in Second Language Acquisition in Schools | publisher=[[Flinders University]], Adelaide | type=PhD thesis | year=1989 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Felix, Uschi | pages=Chapter 2.7}}</ref> Superlearning and SALT originated in North America, while Psychop\u00e4die was developed in [[West Germany]].<ref name=\"Felix1989\" /> While all four are slightly different from the original Suggestopedia and from each other, they still share the common traits of music, relaxation, and suggestion.<ref name=\"Felix1989\" />\n\nThose variants of Suggestopedia mentioned above are too far from the original concept, and are based on the early experiments, which were left behind during the new improvements of the method.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*Idiomos Aprendizagem Acelerada = http://www.idiomos.com\n*Edelmann, Walter, Suggestgop\u00e4die/Superlearning, Heidelberg: Ansanger, 1998.\n*Lozanov, Georgi, Suggestology and Outlines of Suggestopedy, New York: Gordon & Breach 1978 (Translation of: {{cite book |last=Lozanov |first=Georgi |date=1971 |title=Sugestologia |language=Bulgarian |location=Sofia |publisher=Nauka i izkustvo}}).\n*Meier, Josef, Mehr Freude und Erfolg beim Englischlernen mit innovativen Lern- und Mentaltechniken, M\u00fcnchen:IBS, 1999.\n*Riedel, Katja, Pers\u00f6nlichkeitsentfaltung durch Suggestop\u00e4die, Hohengehren: Schneider, 1995.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Suggestop\u00e4die und Superlearning - empirisch gepr\u00fcft. Einf\u00fchrung und Weiterentwicklung f\u00fcr Schule und Erwachsenenbildung, Frankfurt am Main: Diesterweg, 1989.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, La Suggestop\u00e9die et le Superlearning - Mise \u00e0 l'\u00e9preuve statistique, Paris: Didier Erudition, 1991.\n*Schiffler, Ludger: \"Suggestopedic Methods and Applications\", Philadelphia, Tokyo, Paris etc.: Gordon & Breach Science Publisher, 1992.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Effektiver Fremdsprachen lehren und lernen - Beide Gehirnh\u00e4lften aktivieren, Donauw\u00f6rth: Auer, 2002.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Interhemispheric Foreign Language Learning - Activating Both Sides of the Brain, online 2003 (732KB )(download available: http://www.ludger-schiffler.de).\n*Sergio, Paulo, Accelerating the Foreign Language Teaching Through Suggestopedia/Neuropedia, online 2010(download available: http://www.lozanov.com.br and www.idiomos.com).\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite book | url=http://users.monash.edu.au/~ufelix/accel.htm | title=An Investigation of the Effects of Music, Relaxation and Suggestion in Second Language Acquisition in Schools | publisher=[[Flinders University]], Adelaide | type=PhD thesis | year=1989 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Felix, Uschi}} No longer online.\n\n{{Language teaching methods}}\n\n[[Category:Language-teaching methodology]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{POV check|date=October 2010}}\n\n'''Suggestopedia''' is a teaching method developed by the Bulgarian psychotherapist [[Georgi Lozanov]]. It is used mostly to learn foreign languages.\n\nThe theory applied positive [[suggestion]] in teaching when it was developed in the 1970s. However, as the method improved, it has focused more on \"desuggestive learning\" and now is often called \"desuggestopedia\".<ref name=\"one\">Lozanov, Georgi. ''Suggestology and Suggestopedy''. http://lozanov.hit.bg/ 4/30/2006</ref> Suggestopedia is a [[portmanteau]] of the words \"suggestion\" and \"[[pedagogy]]\". A common misconception is to link \"suggestion\" to \"hypnosis\". However, Lozanov intended it in the sense of offering or proposing, emphasising student choice.\n\n==In practice==\nPhysical surroundings and atmosphere in classroom are the vital factors to make sure that \"the students feel comfortable and confident\",<ref name=\"three\">Harmer, Jeremy. ''The Practice of English Language Teaching. 3rd Edition.'' Person Education Limited, 2001</ref> and various techniques, including art and music, are used by the trained teachers.\nThe lesson of Suggestopedia consisted of three phases at first: deciphering, concert session (memorization s\u00e9ance), and elaboration.<ref name=\"one\"/><ref name=\"two\">Lozanov, Georgi. ''Suggestopaedia - Desuggestive Teaching Communicative Method on the Level of the Hidden Reserves of the Human Mind''. http://dr-lozanov.dir.bg/book/start_book.htm 4/30/2006</ref>\n\n'''Deciphering:''' The teacher introduces the grammar and lexis of the content. In most materials the foreign language text is on the left half of the page with a translation on the right half, i.e. meanings are conveyed via the mother tongue not unlike the [[bilingual method]].\n\n'''Concert session (active and passive):''' In the active session, the teacher reads the text at a normal speed, sometimes intoning some words, and the students follow. In the passive session, the students relax and listen to the teacher reading the text calmly. Baroque music is played in the background.\n\n'''Elaboration:'''\nThe students finish off what they have learned with dramas, songs, and games.\n\nThen it has developed into four phases as lots of experiments were done: introduction, concert session, elaboration, and production.<ref name=\"one\"/><ref name=\"two\"/>\n\n'''Introduction:''' The teacher teaches the material in \"a playful manner\" instead of analyzing lexis and grammar of the text in a directive manner.\n\n'''Concert session (active and passive):''' In the active session, the teacher reads with intoning as selected music is played. Occasionally, the students read the text together with the teacher, and listen only to the music as the teacher pauses in particular moments. The passive session is done more calmly.\n\n'''Elaboration:''' The students sing classical songs and play games while \"the teacher acts more like a consultant\".<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n'''Production:''' The students spontaneously speak and interact in the target language without interruption or correction.\n\n==Teachers==\nTeachers should not act in a directive way, although this method is teacher-controlled and not student-controlled. For example, they should act as a real partner to the students, participating in the activities such as games and songs \"naturally\" and \"genuinely.\" <ref name=\"one\"/> In the concert session, they should fully include classical art in their behaviors. Although there are many techniques that the teachers use, factors such as \"communication in the spirit of love, respect for man as a human being, the specific humanitarian way of applying their 'techniques'\" etc. are crucial.<ref name=\"two\"/> The teachers not only need to know the techniques and to acquire the practical [[methodology]] completely, but also to fully understand the theory, because, if they implement those techniques without complete understanding, they will not be able to lead their learners to successful results, or they could even cause a negative impact on their learning. Therefore, the teacher has to be trained in a course taught by certified trainers.\n\nHere are the most important factors for teachers to acquire, described by Lozanov.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n# Covering a huge bulk of learning material.\n# Structuring the material in the suggestopaedic way: global-partial \u2013 partial-global, and global in the part \u2013 part in the global, related to the golden proportion.\n# As a professional, on one hand, and a personality, on the other hand, the teacher should be a highly regarded professional, reliable and credible.\n# The teacher should have, not play, a hundred percent expectation of positive results (because the teacher is already experienced even from the time of the teacher training course).\n# The teacher should love his/her students (of course, not sentimentally but as human beings) and teach them with personal participation through games, songs, classical arts, and pleasure.\n\n==Method for children (preventive Suggestopedia)==\nThe method for Adults includes long sessions without movement,<ref name=\"one\"/> and materials that are appropriate for adults. Children, however, get impacts from \"the social suggestive norms\" differently, and their brains are more delicate than those of adults. Therefore, another method with different materials should be applied to children, which better matches their characteristics. Lessons for children are more incidental and short, preventing the children from the negative pedagogical suggestions of Society. It is important to tell the parents about the method and their roles \u2013 because they could influence children both negatively and positively, depending on how they support the kids.<ref name=\"two\"/>\n\n==Side effects==\nLozanov claims that the effect of the method is not only in language learning, but also in producing favorable side effects on health, the social and psychological relations, and the subsequent success in other subjects.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nSuggestopedia has been called a \"pseudo-science\".<ref name=\"richards\">Richards, J.C. and Rodgers, T.S. (2001). Approaches and Methods in Language Teaching (2nd ed.). Cambridge: Cambridge University Press</ref> It depends, in a sense, on the trust that students develop towards the method. Lozanov never admitted that Suggestopedia can be compared to a placebo. He argues, however, that placebos are indeed effective. Another point of criticism is brought forward by Baur, who claims that the students only receive input by listening, reading and musical-emotional backing, while other important factors of language acquisition are being neglected.<ref>Baur, R.S. (1984). Die Psychop\u00e4dische Variante der Suggestop\u00e4die (Psychop\u00e4die). In Bauer, H.L. (Ed.), Unterrichtspraxis und theoretische Fundierung in Deutsch als Fremdsprache. (pp. 291-326 ). M\u00fcnchen: Goethe-Institut.</ref> Furthermore, several other features of the method \u2013 like the 'nonconscious' acquisition of language, or bringing the learner into a childlike state \u2013 are questioned by critics.\n\nLukesch claims that Suggestopedia lacks scientific backing and is criticized by psychologists as being based on pseudoscience.<ref>Lukesch, H. (2000): Lernen ohne Anstrengung? Der Sirenengesang der geheimen Verf\u00fchrer. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr P\u00e4dagogische Psychologie/German Journal of Educational Psychology, 14, 59-62.</ref>\n\n==Later variations==\n\nSuggestopedia yielded four main offshoots. The first \u2013 still called Suggestopedia, and  developed in eastern Europe \u2013 used different techniques from Lozanov's original version. The other three are named ''[[Superlearning]]'', ''Suggestive Accelerated Learning and Teaching'' (SALT), and ''Psychop\u00e4die''.<ref name=\"Felix1989\">{{cite book | url=http://users.monash.edu.au/~ufelix/thesis2-7.htm | title=An Investigation of the Effects of Music, Relaxation and Suggestion in Second Language Acquisition in Schools | publisher=[[Flinders University]], Adelaide | type=PhD thesis | year=1989 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Felix, Uschi | pages=Chapter 2.7}}</ref> Superlearning and SALT originated in North America, while Psychop\u00e4die was developed in [[West Germany]].<ref name=\"Felix1989\" /> While all four are slightly different from the original Suggestopedia and from each other, they still share the common traits of music, relaxation, and suggestion.<ref name=\"Felix1989\" />\n\nThose variants of Suggestopedia mentioned above are too far from the original concept, and are based on the early experiments, which were left behind during the new improvements of the method.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n*Idiomos Aprendizagem Acelerada = http://www.idiomos.com\n*Edelmann, Walter, Suggestgop\u00e4die/Superlearning, Heidelberg: Ansanger, 1998.\n*Lozanov, Georgi, Suggestology and Outlines of Suggestopedy, New York: Gordon & Breach 1978 (Translation of: {{cite book |last=Lozanov |first=Georgi |date=1971 |title=Sugestologia |language=Bulgarian |location=Sofia |publisher=Nauka i izkustvo}}).\n*Meier, Josef, Mehr Freude und Erfolg beim Englischlernen mit innovativen Lern- und Mentaltechniken, M\u00fcnchen:IBS, 1999.\n*Riedel, Katja, Pers\u00f6nlichkeitsentfaltung durch Suggestop\u00e4die, Hohengehren: Schneider, 1995.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Suggestop\u00e4die und Superlearning - empirisch gepr\u00fcft. Einf\u00fchrung und Weiterentwicklung f\u00fcr Schule und Erwachsenenbildung, Frankfurt am Main: Diesterweg, 1989.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, La Suggestop\u00e9die et le Superlearning - Mise \u00e0 l'\u00e9preuve statistique, Paris: Didier Erudition, 1991.\n*Schiffler, Ludger: \"Suggestopedic Methods and Applications\", Philadelphia, Tokyo, Paris etc.: Gordon & Breach Science Publisher, 1992.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Effektiver Fremdsprachen lehren und lernen - Beide Gehirnh\u00e4lften aktivieren, Donauw\u00f6rth: Auer, 2002.\n*Schiffler, Ludger, Interhemispheric Foreign Language Learning - Activating Both Sides of the Brain, online 2003 (732KB )(download available: http://www.ludger-schiffler.de).\n*Sergio, Paulo, Accelerating the Foreign Language Teaching Through Suggestopedia/Neuropedia, online 2010(download available: http://www.lozanov.com.br and www.idiomos.com).\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite book | url=http://users.monash.edu.au/~ufelix/accel.htm | title=An Investigation of the Effects of Music, Relaxation and Suggestion in Second Language Acquisition in Schools | publisher=[[Flinders University]], Adelaide | type=PhD thesis | year=1989 | accessdate=January 12, 2012 | author=Felix, Uschi}} No longer online.\n\n{{Language teaching methods}}\n\n[[Category:Language-teaching methodology]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n", "name_user": "Kazhagiwara", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn practice", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suggestopedia"}
{"title_page": "John Gumley (younger)", "text_new": "'''John Gumley'''  (c. 1696 \u2013 c. 1749) was a British glass manufacturer, East India merchant and Tory politician who sat briefly in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] in 1728.\n\nGumley was the second son of [[John Gumley]] of Isleworth and his wife Susannah White, daughter of Samuel White, merchant of London. He married his cousin Martha Wittewrong, daughter of [[Sir John Wittewrong, 3rd Baronet]], who had married Gumley's mother's sister.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/gumley-john-1695-1749| title=GUMLEY, John (c.1695-bef.1749), of Isleworth, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 14 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGumley was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bramber (UK Parliament constituency)|Bramber]], where his father was steward of the court leet, at a by-election on 2 March 1728. He was unseated  on petition on 4 April 1728 for alleged malpractices by the returning officer, who was his father's nominee. Gumley was the brother-in-law of [[William Pulteney, 1st Earl of Bath|William Pulteney]] who caused a furore when the matter came before the house by pointing out indirectly that Gumley's opponent, John Hoste, was a relation of Robert Walpole.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nGumley inherited his father's share in the Vauxhall glass works when his father died in 1728.  In 1734 he went as head merchant to Bengal, which  entitled him to become a member of Council.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nGumley died without issue before 1749. He was the brother  of [[Samuel Gumley]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  =  [[Richard Gough (1655\u20131728)|Sir Richard Gough]]\n | before2 =  [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bramber (UK Parliament constituency)|Bramber]]\n | years =    1728  \n | with  = [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]    \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  =  [[James Hoste (died 1744)|James Hoste]]\n | after2 =  [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumley, John}}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1740s deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Gumley'''  (c. 1696 \u2013 c. 1749) was a British glass manufacturer, East India merchant and Tory politician who sat briefly in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] in 1728.\n\nGumley was the second son of [[John Gumley]] of Isleworth and his wife Susannah White, daughter of Samuel White, merchant of London. He married his cousin Martha Wittewrong, daughter of [[Sir John Wittewrong, 3rd Baronet]], who had married Gumley\u2019s mother\u2019s sister.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/gumley-john-1695-1749| title=GUMLEY, John (c.1695-bef.1749), of Isleworth, Mdx. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 14 March 2019 }}</ref>\n\nGumley was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bramber (UK Parliament constituency)|Bramber]], where his father was steward of the court leet, at a by-election on 2 March 1728. He was unseated  on petition on 4 April 1728 for alleged malpractices by the returning officer, who was his father\u2019s nominee. Gumley was the brother-in-law of [[William Pulteney, 1st Earl of Bath|William Pulteney]] who caused a furore when the matter came before the house by pointing out indirectly that Gumley\u2019s opponent, John Hoste, was a relation of Robert Walpole.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nGumley inherited his father\u2019s share in the Vauxhall glass works when his father died in 1728.  In 1734 he went as head merchant to Bengal, which  entitled him to become a member of Council.<ref name=HOP/>\n\nGumley died without issue before 1749. He was the brother  of [[Samuel Gumley]].<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  =  [[Richard Gough (1655\u20131728)|Sir Richard Gough]]\n | before2 =  [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bramber (UK Parliament constituency)|Bramber]]\n | years =    1728  \n | with  = [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]    \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  =  [[James Hoste (died 1744)|James Hoste]]\n | after2 =  [[Sir Joseph Danvers, 1st Baronet|Joseph Danvers]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumley, John}}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1740s deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (5)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gumley_(younger)"}
{"title_page": "International student ministry", "text_new": "'''International Student Ministry''' (ISM) refers to [[Evangelicals|evangelical Christian]] ministry among [[international student|international students]] within an academic context, often carried out by [[College religious organizations#Protestant|protestant college religious organizations]], volunteers and churches.<ref name=ChinnAgents>{{cite book | chapter=Agents of Diaspora Missions in and from the Academic World| | first1=Leiton Edward | last1=Chinn | first2=Lisa Espineli | last2=Chinn | |editor1-last=Tira |editor1-first=Sadiri Joy |editor2-last=Yamamori |editor2-first=Tetsunao |title=Scattered and Gathered: A Global Compendium of Diaspora Missiology |date=April 2016 |publisher=Wipf & Stock |isbn=978-1498296670 | pages=228-241 }}</ref> It is considered part of the church\u2019s [[Christian mission|mission]], within the broader framework of diaspora missions.<ref name=\"EnochWan1\">{{cite book\n | last = Wan\n | first = Enoch\n | editor-first = Enoch\n | editor-last = Wan\n | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]]\n | series = Diaspora Series\n | volume = 4\n | date = August 2019\n | page = 10\n | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref>\nThe first two decades of the 21st century have seen sharp growth in the number of international students globally<ref name=\"MigrationDataPortal\">{{cite web\n | url = https://migrationdataportal.org/themes/international-students\n | title = International Students\n | date = 16 October 2019\n | website = Migration Data Portal\n | access-date = 17 October 2019\n}}</ref> with a corresponding development in ISM.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n== History ==\nISM traces its modern roots to [[John Mott|John R. Mott]] who established ''The Committee on Friendly Relations among Foreign Students'' in 1911, which was the first national ISM in the US.<ref name=\"LeitonChinn1\">{{cite book\n | last = Chinn\n | first = Leiton Edward\n | editor-first1 = Chandler H.\n | editor-last1 = Im\n | editor-first2 = Amos\n | editor-last2 = Yong\n | title = Global Diasporas and Mission\n | chapter = Diaspora Missions on Campuses: John R. Mott and a Centennial Overview of the International Student Ministry Movement in North America\n | publisher = Regnum Books International\n | series = Edinburgh Centenary Series\n | volume = 23\n | date = 2014\n | page = 238\n | isbn = 978-1-908355-48-5\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite book\n | last = Thompson\n | first = Mary\n | title = Unofficial Ambassadors: The Story of International Student Service\n | date = 1982\n | publisher = [[International Student Service|World University Service]]\n | location = New York, NY\n | oclc=11196897\n}}</ref>\nSince then, and particularly since the 1950s, there has been a growth of organizations doing this mainly in Western contexts.<ref name=\"LeitonChinn1\"/><ref name=\"Chinn1979\">{{cite web |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=Historical Development of the International Student Ministry Movement In the USA |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/54859d80e4b0fb60932c080f/t/54a43325e4b08424e6957e32/1420047141475/Historical+Development+of+the+International+Student+Ministry+Movement+in+the+USA.pdf |website=Historical Development of the Christian Movement (Ralph Winter) |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=Winter 1979}}</ref>  As of 2016 there were at least 57 organizations engaged in ISM in 22 countries.<ref name=\"ChinnBlindSpot2016\">{{cite web |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Student Ministry: From 'Blind-spot' to Vision (May 2009, Updated June 2016) |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58b70db8d2b85748a0a0bff8/t/591b685e17bffcb364fa29f7/1494968414656/International+Student+Ministry-From+Blind-Spot+to+Vision-Leiton+Chinn.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lausanne_ISM_Issue_Network_Leaders_Forum_2004,_Thailand.jpg|thumb|right|Lausanne ISM Issue Network Leaders Forum, Thailand 2004]]In 2004, after a century of intermittent ISM growth<ref name=ChinnAgents/> Leiton Chinn convened a global gathering in Thailand of ISM leaders, and in 2007 he was appointed the Chair of the Lausanne ISM Issue Network.<ref name=Chinn2019/> The two [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization|Lausanne]] Issue Groups of Diaspora and International Students then published ''Diasporas and International Students: The New People Next Door''.<ref name=\"LOP55\">{{cite book\n | author = Issue Group for Diasporas and International Students\n | title = Diasporas and International Students: The New People Next Door\n | publisher = [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization]]\n | series = Lausanne Occasional Paper\n | volume = 55\n | date = October 2004\n | location = Pattaya, Thailand\n | url = https://www.lausanne.org/content/lop/diasporas-and-international-students-the-new-people-next-door-lop-55\n}}</ref> Recent publications include those by Jack D. Burke<ref name=\"JackBurke1\">{{cite book\n | last = Burke\n | first = Jack D.\n | title = Paradigm Shift: Why International Students Are so Strategic to Global Missions\n | publisher = [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|WestBow Press]]\n | date = 15 March 2019\n | isbn = 978-1973656869\n}}</ref> and Enoch Wan.<ref name=\"EnochWan1\"/> The [[Lausanne_Committee_for_World_Evangelization#Cape_Town_2010|Lausanne 2010 Cape Town Commitment]] (section II-C-5) refers to reaching out to international students.<ref name=\"CapeTown2010\">{{cite web |title=The Cape Town Commitment |url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/ctc/ctcommitment#capetown |website=Lausanne Movement |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=25 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BockBibiographicRefs\">{{cite book |last1=Bock |first1=Darrell |title=The Cape Town Commitment: a Confession of Faith, a Call to Action : Bibliographic Resources. |date=2013 |publisher=Wipf & Stock |isbn=978-1625640031 |pages=77\u201378 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014 the Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Network became a \"docked network\" with the [[World_Evangelical_Alliance|World Evangelical  Alliance]]'s Mission Commission.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n[[File:Lausanne Global ISM Leadership Forum Charlotte 17.jpg|thumb|right|Lausanne Global ISM Leadership Forum in Charlotte, NC, USA in September 2017.]]In September 2017 the Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Network hosted a global ISM forum ''Charlotte '17'' which gathered 100 participants from 25 countries and 70 organizations.<ref name=Chinn2019/><ref name=Charlotte17>{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/gatherings/lausanne-ism-global-leadership-forum-charlotte17 | title=Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Forum: Charlotte \u201917 | website=Lausanne Movement | access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is suggested that ISM is grounded in the ''[[Missio Dei]]'' and is motivated by biblical precedent and trends in migration.<ref name=\"ChrisSneller1\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Sneller | first = Christopher D.\n | chapter = Theological Foundation for the Practice of Diaspora Missions Among International Students | page = 56\u201363\n | editor-first = Enoch | editor-last = Wan | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]] | series = Diaspora Series | volume = 4 | date = August 2019 | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref> Chinn outlines ten reasons why ISM is strategic in relation to the [[Great_Commission|Great Commission]] and nine reasons why it benefits local churches.<ref name=\"ChinnAMA52\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Students: A Strategic Component of Diaspora Missions & The Great Commission |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=June 2016 |volume=52 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/international-students-a-strategic-component-of-diaspora-missions-the-great-commission/ |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Networks and organizations ==\n\nIndividual churches, such as [[Park_Street_Church|Park Street Congregational Church in Boston]], have welcoming ministries reaching international students.<ref name=ChinnAgents/> This [[Modality_(theology)|modality]]-based model of ISM is attractive because every church member can be involved in cross-cultural mission at virtually no expense.<ref name=\"JackBurke1\" /> Miller outlines key qualities leading to successful ISM by local churches.<ref name=Miller2018>{{cite thesis | type=DMin (Global Studies) | last=Miller | first=S. Beau | date=June 2018 | title=Mobilizing Local Churches for International Student Ministry: A Study of How Local Churches Mobilize to Evangelize and Equip Nearby International Students | publisher=Columbia International University | url=https://issuu.com/philjones2510/docs/mobilizing_churches_for_ism__s._beau_miller__ciu_d | access-date=8 March 2020 }}</ref> Perbi and Brewster argue that ISM will be strengthened by the intentional involvement of \"workplace Christians.\"<ref name=PerbiBrewster2019>{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/international-student-ministry-workplace | first1=Yaw | last1=Perbi | first2=Emma | last2=Brewster | title=International Student Ministry and the Workplace | date=June 2019 | access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> Some denominational groups have established an ISM focus such as [[Anglican_Church_in_North_America|Anglican (USA)]],<ref>{{cite web |title=International Student Ministry |url=https://newwineskins.org/ism |website=New Wineskins Missionary Network |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> [[Lutheran_Church\u2013Missouri_Synod|Lutheran Church (Missouri Synod)]], [[Assemblies_of_God_USA|Assemblies of God (USA)]] and the [[Presbyterian_Church_in_America|Presbyterian Church in America]].<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\nChristian campus organizations, which are [[Sodality|sodalities]], have historically focused on domestic university students. These have developed campus-based ministries for international students directly linked to universities or colleges.<ref name=\"WangGreen\">\n{{cite book |last1=Wang |first1=Chin T. (John) |last2=Green |first2=Sam \n |chapter=International Students and Diaspora Missiology |page=43\u201344\n | editor-first = Enoch | editor-last = Wan | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]] | series = Diaspora Series | volume = 4 | date = August 2019 | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}\n</ref>{{rp|55}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Selected ISMs as college ministries<ref name=ChinnAgents/><ref name=\"Chinn2019\">{{cite book\n | last = Chinn\n | first = Leiton Edward\n | editor-first = Enoch\n | editor-last = Wan\n | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | chapter = The Global ISM Movement Emerging from Diaspora Missions on Campuses: From John R. Mott to \"Lausanne\"\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]]\n | series = Diaspora Series\n | volume = 4\n | date = August 2019\n | pages = 119-138\n | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref>\n|-\n! Country !! Organization !! ISM staff !! Other workers !! Campuses !! Churches\n|-\n| USA || [[InterVarsity_Christian_Fellowship|InterVarsity (USA)]]<ref name=\"IVCF_ISM\">{{cite web | url=https://ism.intervarsity.org/home | access-date=19 February 2020 | title=International Student Ministry | website=InterVarsity }}</ref> || 100 || 100 \"engaged with internationals\" || 300 ||\n|-\n| USA || International Students Inc. (ISI)<ref name=\"ISI\">{{cite web | url=https://www.isionline.org/ | title=International Students Inc. (ISI) | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 350 ||  || || \n|-\n| USA || Bridges International<ref name=\"BridgesInternational\">{{cite web | title=Bridges International | url=https://www.bridgesinternational.com | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 315 || 87 \"staff ambassadors (part-time)\" || 200 ||\n|- \n| Canada || ISMC<ref name=\"ISMC\">{{cite web | url=https://ismc.ca/ | title=ISMC | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 110 || 500 volunteers || 52 || 100\n|-\n| Korea || International Students Fellowship || 80 || || 20 ||\n|-\n| Korea || Scientists & Engineers Members, International || 2 || 21 part time, 120 volunteers || 20 ||\n|-\n| Korea || InterVarsity Fellowship || 1 || 3 part time || ||\n|-\n| Singapore || Fellowship of Evangelical Students || 11 || || ||\n|-\n| Malaysia || Fellowship of Evangelical Students || 1 || 1 || ||\n|-\n| Japan || OMF || 2 || || ||\n|-\n| Japan || KGK || 6 || || 6 ||\n|-\n| New Zealand || ISMNZ<ref name=ISMNZ>{{cite web | url=https://www.ismnz.org.nz/| title=ISMNZ | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 40 || || 16 || 20\n|-\n| New Zealand || TSCF || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| New Zealand || OMF || 3 || || ||\n|-\n| UK || Friends International<ref name=\"FriendsInternational\">{{cite web | url=https://friendsinternational.uk/ | title=Friends International | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 75 || 60 affiliated staff || 35 || 250\n|-\n| UK || [[OMF_International|OMF]] || 8 || || ||\n|-\n| UK || Navigators || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| Germany || SMD (IFES) || 3 || || ||\n|-\n| Germany || OMF || 5 || || ||\n|-\n| Switzerland || VBG (IFES) || 2 || 3 || ||\n|-\n| Netherlands || IFES || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| Netherlands || OMF || 1 || || ||\n|-\n| France || Un Coeur Pour le Monde || 11 || || ||\n|-\n| South Africa || Bridge || 4 || 20 volunteers || ||\n|-\n| Philippines || FOCUS || 1 || 10 part time || || 4\n|-\n| Australia || [[Australian_Fellowship_of_Evangelical_Students|AFES]] FOCUS<ref name=\"AFES_FOCUS\">{{cite web | url=https://www.afes.org.au/page/focus | title=AFES FOCUS | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 53 || 18 apprentices || 28 ||\n|-\n| Australia || Navigators || 12 || || ||\n|-\n| Australia || OMF || 3 || || ||\n|-\n|}\n\nAt a global level, the [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization]] has an ISM issue network<ref name=\"LausanneISM\">{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/networks/issues/international-students | title=International Student Ministry (ISM) issue network | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> which connects groups internationally and interdenominationally. This network now includes a North American network on ISM.<ref name=MillerGlobal>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Beau |title=Global Outreach Opportunity: Ministry Among International Students |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/edstetzer/2019/october/global-outreach-opportunity-ministry-international-students.html |website=The Exchange: A Blog by Ed Stetzer |publisher=Christianity Today |accessdate=21 October 2019 |language=en |date=19 October 2019}}</ref> The Association for Christians Ministering Among Internationals (ACMI) is another ISM networking body.<ref name=\"ACMI\">{{cite web | url=https://www.acmi-ism.org/ | title=Association for Christians Ministering Among Internationals | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MillerGlobal\"/> Networking between European ISMs has been identified as a priority.<ref name=\"Tower\">{{cite conference | last1=de Pater | first1 = Francina | last2=Ryan | first2=Clayton | last3=Tower | first3=Alan | url=https://issuu.com/philjones2510/docs/international_students_in_europe_-_de_pater__ryan_ | title=International Students in Europe | conference=Lausanne Global Diaspora Network | location=Liverpool Hope University | date=5-8 June 2019 | access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Trends ==\n\nRecent decades have seen a rapid increase in international student populations<ref name=\"MigrationDataPortal\" /> concurrent with the plateauing of some western markets, most notably the US.<ref name=\"Zong1\">{{cite news |last1=Zong |first1=Jie |last2=Batalova |first2=Jeanne |title=International Students in the United States |url=https://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/international-students-united-states |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=migrationpolicy.org |date=9 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Redden1\">{{cite news |last1=Redden |first1=Elizabeth |title=With international enrollments slowing or declining in some top destination countries, a look at trends across the globe |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/24/international-enrollments-slowing-or-declining-some-top-destination-countries-look |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"FourMegatrends\">{{cite news |title=Four megatrends that are changing the competitive landscape of international education |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2016/11/four-megatrends-changing-competitive-landscape-international-education/ |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor - Market intelligence for international student recruitment |date=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MappingTrends\">{{cite news |title=Mapping the trends that will shape international student mobility |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2017/07/mapping-trends-will-shape-international-student-mobility/ |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor - Market intelligence for international student recruitment |date=18 July 2017}}</ref> Students are turning to non-traditional centers of education, such as Asia.<ref name=\"Ning1\">{{cite web |last1=Luo |first1=Ning |title=Global Student Mobility Trends: Focus on Japan, Malaysia, Taiwan, and South Korea |url=https://wenr.wes.org/2017/08/global-mobility-japan-malaysia-taiwan-and-south-korea-seek-to-shift-student-mobility-by-2025 |website=WENR |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"StudyInternational1\">{{cite web |title=China emerges as the No.1 study abroad destination in Asia |url=https://www.studyinternational.com/news/china-emerges-as-the-no-1-study-abroad-destination-in-asia/ |website=Study International |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ICEF-up-down\">{{cite news |title=Up and down the table: Growth trends across major international study destinations |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2018/08/up-and-down-the-table-growth-trends-across-major-international-study-destinations/ |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor |date=29 August 2018}}</ref> This shift is underpinned by well-formed international [[Education_policy|education policy]] of countries like China,<ref name=\"Atack\">{{cite news |last1=Atack |first1=Patrick |title=China \"opening education to the outside world\" - policy document |url=https://thepienews.com/news/china-opening-education-to-the-outside-world-policy-document/ |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=The PIE News |date=12 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Parr1\">{{cite news |last1=Parr |first1=Chris |title=A two-way street: why China is not just a student departure lounge anymore |url=https://thepienews.com/analysis/international-students-in-china-increasingly-diverse/ |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=The PIE News |date=20 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref name=\"Zulita\">{{cite news |last1=Mustafa |first1=Zulita |title=International students and the Education Malaysia brand |url=https://www.nst.com.my/education/2017/09/284694/international-students-and-education-malaysia-brand |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=New Straits Times |date=27 September 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Singapore and India.<ref name=\"HansdeWit\">{{cite news |last1=de Wit |first1=Hans |title=The new dynamics in international student circulation |url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20180704143553337 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=University World News |date=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe areas of diaspora missiology and its subset, international student ministry, have seen a theological and academic maturing.<ref name=\"Wan2014\">{{cite book |last1=Wan |first1=Enoch |title=Diaspora missiology: theory, methodology, and practice |date=Nov 2014 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1503095502 |edition=2nd }}</ref><ref name=ChinnAgents/><ref name=\"PocockWan2015\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Pocock |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Wan |editor2-first=Enoch |title=Diaspora Missions: Reflections on Reaching the Scattered Peoples of the World |date=August 2015 |publisher=William Carey Library |isbn=978-0878080458 }}</ref> In 2018/2019 two key ISM-specific training resources were launched: the ''Lausanne Global Classroom''<ref name=\"LausanneGlobalClassroom\">{{cite web |title=Lausanne Global Classroom: International Student Ministry |url=https://www.lausanne.org/lausanne-global-classroom/international-student-ministry-episode |website=Lausanne Movement |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=22 July 2019}}</ref> and ''EveryInternational''.<ref name=EveryInternational>{{cite web | title=Every International | url=https://everyinternational.com | accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MillerGlobal\"/> Two ISM training workshops ran at the [[International_Fellowship_of_Evangelical_Students|International Fellowship of Evangelical Students (IFES)]] World Assembly in July 2019.<ref name=IFESWA2019>{{cite web | url=https://ifesworld.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/IFES-WA19-Seminar-summaries-ALL.pdf | title=Messengers of Hope, IFES World Assembly 2019, All Seminars | date=July 2019 | access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> While practical ISM training is offered by a number of ISM organisations, the ''Charlotte '17'' conference considered the need for academic training and research in ISM led by seminaries and graduate schools.<ref name=Chinn2019/> [[Columbia_International_University|Columbia International University]] lists a course called \"Mission to International Students\" in their 2019-2020 Academic Catalog.<ref name=CIU2019>{{cite web | url=http://catalog.ciu.edu/mime/media/view/2/89/1920+Catalog+Complete.pdf | title=Columbia International University, 2019-2020 Academic Catalog | date=1 April 2019 | access-date=8 March 2020 | website=Columbia International University }}</ref>\n\nGlobal mission sending organizations are recognizing the strategic nature and necessity of diaspora missions, and especially ISM.<ref name=\"EddieArthur\">{{cite journal |last1=Eddie |first1=Arthur |title=The Future of Mission Agencies |journal=Mission Round Table |date=January 2017 |volume=12 |issue=1 |page=4\u201312 |url=https://omf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/MRT-12.1-Future-of-Mission-Agencies.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BestGlobalCampus\">{{cite web |last1=Best |first1=Alexander |title=10 Reasons Why the Global Campus Is the Future of Mission |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/edstetzer/2019/july/10-reasons-why-global-campus-is-future-of-mission.html |website=The Exchange: A Blog by Ed Stetzer |publisher=Christianity Today |accessdate=21 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ChinnAMA52\"/> Some have refocused ISM efforts in traditional contexts because of the perceived global impact.<ref name=\"ChinnLGA2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=The Mission Field Coming to Our Campuses |journal=Lausanne Global Analysis |date=January 2018 |volume=7 |issue=1 |url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/lga/2018-01/mission-field-coming-campuses |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> Asia has been identified as an emerging region for ISM.<ref name=\"ChinnAMA62\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=Broad Asian Global Mission Opportunity: Increasing Numbers of International Students in Pan-Asia Region |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=Jan 2019 |volume=62 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/broad-asian-global-mission-opportunity-increasing-numbers-of-international-students-in-pan-asia-region/ |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ChinnAMA42\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Student Ministry: A Most Strategic Yet Most Inexpensive Global Mission Opportunity Arises in Asia |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=January 2014 |volume=42 |page=2\u20137 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/ama_42.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> It is beginning to take shape there, for example among international churches in China.<ref name=\"MarkBlair\">{{cite journal |last1=Blair |first1=Mark |title=Looking for Gospel Laborers? Don't Forget the University! |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=January 2019 |volume=62 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/asian-missions-advances/amadvance-52-60/asian-missions-advance-62/ |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Momoh\">{{ cite web | last1=Momoh | first1=Miatta | url=https://www.chinasource.org/resource-library/chinasource-blog-posts/novel-gospel-opportunities | title=Novel Gospel Opportunities: How One International Church in China Is Maximizing New Gospel Opportunities | website=ChinaSource | date=21 February 2020 | access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=PhilJonesEMQ54-2>{{cite journal | last=Jones | first=Phil | date=April 2018 | url=https://www.missiontools.org/resources/emq-v54-i2/ | title=International Students in China: Who Will Reach This Vast and Strategic Yet Invisible Group? | journal=Evangelical Missions Quarterly | volume=54 | issue=2 | pages=46-57  | access-date=22 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=PhilJonesJan2019>{{cite web | title=The Birth of ISM in China: Is This God's Timing? | last1=Jones | first1=Phil | website=ChinaSource | date=25 January 2019 | access-date=22 February 2020 | url=https://www.chinasource.org/resource-library/chinasource-blog-posts/the-birth-of-ism-in-china }}</ref> Nascent ISMs exist in South Africa, Kenya and Ghana.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:International_student_religious_organizations]]\n", "text_old": "'''International Student Ministry''' (ISM) refers to [[Evangelicals|evangelical Christian]] ministry among [[international student|international students]] within an academic context, often carried out by [[College religious organizations#Protestant|protestant college religious organizations]], volunteers and churches.<ref name=ChinnAgents>{{cite book | chapter=Agents of Diaspora Missions in and from the Academic World| | first1=Leiton Edward | last1=Chinn | first2=Lisa Espineli | last2=Chinn | |editor1-last=Tira |editor1-first=Sadiri Joy |editor2-last=Yamamori |editor2-first=Tetsunao |title=Scattered and Gathered: A Global Compendium of Diaspora Missiology |date=April 2016 |publisher=Wipf & Stock |isbn=978-1498296670 | pages=228-241 }}</ref> It is considered part of the church\u2019s [[Christian mission|mission]], within the broader framework of diaspora missions.<ref name=\"EnochWan1\">{{cite book\n | last = Wan\n | first = Enoch\n | editor-first = Enoch\n | editor-last = Wan\n | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]]\n | series = Diaspora Series\n | volume = 4\n | date = August 2019\n | page = 10\n | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref>\nThe first two decades of the 21st century have seen sharp growth in the number of international students globally<ref name=\"MigrationDataPortal\">{{cite web\n | url = https://migrationdataportal.org/themes/international-students\n | title = International Students\n | date = 16 October 2019\n | website = Migration Data Portal\n | access-date = 17 October 2019\n}}</ref> with a corresponding development in ISM.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n== History ==\nISM traces its modern roots to [[John Mott|John R. Mott]] who established ''The Committee on Friendly Relations among Foreign Students'' in 1911, which was the first national ISM in the US.<ref name=\"LeitonChinn1\">{{cite book\n | last = Chinn\n | first = Leiton Edward\n | editor-first1 = Chandler H.\n | editor-last1 = Im\n | editor-first2 = Amos\n | editor-last2 = Yong\n | title = Global Diasporas and Mission\n | chapter = Diaspora Missions on Campuses: John R. Mott and a Centennial Overview of the International Student Ministry Movement in North America\n | publisher = Regnum Books International\n | series = Edinburgh Centenary Series\n | volume = 23\n | date = 2014\n | page = 238\n | isbn = 978-1-908355-48-5\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite book\n | last = Thompson\n | first = Mary\n | title = Unofficial Ambassadors: The Story of International Student Service\n | date = 1982\n | publisher = [[International Student Service|World University Service]]\n | location = New York, NY\n | oclc=11196897\n}}</ref>\nSince then, and particularly since the 1950s, there has been a growth of organizations doing this mainly in Western contexts.<ref name=\"LeitonChinn1\"/><ref name=\"Chinn1979\">{{cite web |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=Historical Development of the International Student Ministry Movement In the USA |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/54859d80e4b0fb60932c080f/t/54a43325e4b08424e6957e32/1420047141475/Historical+Development+of+the+International+Student+Ministry+Movement+in+the+USA.pdf |website=Historical Development of the Christian Movement (Ralph Winter) |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=Winter 1979}}</ref>  As of 2016 there were at least 57 organizations engaged in ISM in 22 countries.<ref name=\"ChinnBlindSpot2016\">{{cite web |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Student Ministry: From 'Blind-spot' to Vision (May 2009, Updated June 2016) |url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/58b70db8d2b85748a0a0bff8/t/591b685e17bffcb364fa29f7/1494968414656/International+Student+Ministry-From+Blind-Spot+to+Vision-Leiton+Chinn.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lausanne_ISM_Issue_Network_Leaders_Forum_2004,_Thailand.jpg|thumb|right|Lausanne ISM Issue Network Leaders Forum, Thailand 2004]]In 2004, after a century of intermittent ISM growth<ref name=ChinnAgents/> Leiton Chinn convened a global gathering in Thailand of ISM leaders, and in 2007 he was appointed the Chair of the Lausanne ISM Issue Network.<ref name=Chinn2019/> The two [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization|Lausanne]] Issue Groups of Diaspora and International Students then published ''Diasporas and International Students: The New People Next Door''.<ref name=\"LOP55\">{{cite book\n | author = Issue Group for Diasporas and International Students\n | title = Diasporas and International Students: The New People Next Door\n | publisher = [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization]]\n | series = Lausanne Occasional Paper\n | volume = 55\n | date = October 2004\n | location = Pattaya, Thailand\n | url = https://www.lausanne.org/content/lop/diasporas-and-international-students-the-new-people-next-door-lop-55\n}}</ref> Recent publications include those by Jack D. Burke<ref name=\"JackBurke1\">{{cite book\n | last = Burke\n | first = Jack D.\n | title = Paradigm Shift: Why International Students Are so Strategic to Global Missions\n | publisher = [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|WestBow Press]]\n | date = 15 March 2019\n | isbn = 978-1973656869\n}}</ref> and Enoch Wan.<ref name=\"EnochWan1\"/> The [[Lausanne_Committee_for_World_Evangelization#Cape_Town_2010|Lausanne 2010 Cape Town Commitment]] (section II-C-5) refers to reaching out to international students.<ref name=\"CapeTown2010\">{{cite web |title=The Cape Town Commitment |url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/ctc/ctcommitment#capetown |website=Lausanne Movement |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=25 January 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BockBibiographicRefs\">{{cite book |last1=Bock |first1=Darrell |title=The Cape Town Commitment: a Confession of Faith, a Call to Action : Bibliographic Resources. |date=2013 |publisher=Wipf & Stock |isbn=978-1625640031 |pages=77\u201378 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014 the Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Network became a \"docked network\" with the [[World_Evangelical_Alliance|World Evangelical  Alliance]]'s Mission Commission.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n[[File:Lausanne Global ISM Leadership Forum Charlotte 17.jpg|thumb|right|Lausanne Global ISM Leadership Forum in Charlotte, NC, USA in September 2017.]]In September 2017 the Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Network hosted a global ISM forum ''Charlotte '17'' which gathered 100 participants from 25 countries and 70 organizations.<ref name=Chinn2019/><ref name=Charlotte17>{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/gatherings/lausanne-ism-global-leadership-forum-charlotte17 | title=Lausanne ISM Global Leadership Forum: Charlotte \u201917 | website=Lausanne Movement | access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is suggested that ISM is grounded in the ''[[Missio Dei]]'' and is motivated by biblical precedent and trends in migration.<ref name=\"ChrisSneller1\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Sneller | first = Christopher D.\n | chapter = Theological Foundation for the Practice of Diaspora Missions Among International Students | page = 56\u201363\n | editor-first = Enoch | editor-last = Wan | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]] | series = Diaspora Series | volume = 4 | date = August 2019 | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref> Chinn outlines ten reasons why ISM is strategic in relation to the [[Great_Commission|Great Commission]] and nine reasons why it benefits local churches.<ref name=\"ChinnAMA52\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Students: A Strategic Component of Diaspora Missions & The Great Commission |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=June 2016 |volume=52 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/international-students-a-strategic-component-of-diaspora-missions-the-great-commission/ |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Networks and organizations ==\n\nIndividual churches, such as [[Park_Street_Church|Park Street Congregational Church in Boston]], have welcoming ministries reaching international students.<ref name=ChinnAgents/> This [[Modality_(theology)|modality]]-based model of ISM is attractive because every church member can be involved in cross-cultural mission at virtually no expense.<ref name=\"JackBurke1\" /> Miller outlines key qualities leading to successful ISM by local churches.<ref name=Miller2018>{{cite thesis | type=DMin (Global Studies) | last=Miller | first=S. Beau | date=June 2018 | title=Mobilizing Local Churches for International Student Ministry: A Study of How Local Churches Mobilize to Evangelize and Equip Nearby International Students | publisher=Columbia International University | url=https://issuu.com/philjones2510/docs/mobilizing_churches_for_ism__s._beau_miller__ciu_d | access-date=8 March 2020 }}</ref> Perbi and Brewster argue that ISM will be strengthened by the intentional involvement of \"workplace Christians.\"<ref name=PerbiBrewster2019>{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/international-student-ministry-workplace | first1=Yaw | last1=Perbi | first2=Emma | last2=Brewster | title=International Student Ministry and the Workplace | date=June 2019 | access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> Some denominational groups have established an ISM focus such as [[Anglican_Church_in_North_America|Anglican (USA)]],<ref>{{cite web |title=International Student Ministry |url=https://newwineskins.org/ism |website=New Wineskins Missionary Network |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> [[Lutheran_Church\u2013Missouri_Synod|Lutheran Church (Missouri Synod)]], [[Assemblies_of_God_USA|Assemblies of God (USA)]] and the [[Presbyterian_Church_in_America|Presbyterian Church in America]].<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\nChristian campus organizations, which are [[Sodality|sodalities]], have historically focused on domestic university students. These have developed campus-based ministries for international students directly linked to universities or colleges.<ref name=\"WangGreen\">\n{{cite book |last1=Wang |first1=Chin T. (John) |last2=Green |first2=Sam \n |chapter=International Students and Diaspora Missiology |page=43\u201344\n | editor-first = Enoch | editor-last = Wan | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]] | series = Diaspora Series | volume = 4 | date = August 2019 | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}\n</ref>{{rp|55}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Selected ISMs as college ministries<ref name=ChinnAgents/><ref name=\"Chinn2019\">{{cite book\n | last = Chinn\n | first = Leiton Edward\n | editor-first = Enoch\n | editor-last = Wan\n | title = Diaspora Missions to International Students\n | chapter = The Global ISM Movement Emerging from Diaspora Missions on Campuses: From John R. Mott to \"Lausanne\"\n | publisher = [[Western Seminary]]\n | series = Diaspora Series\n | volume = 4\n | date = August 2019\n | pages = 119-138\n | isbn = 978-1949201178\n}}</ref>\n|-\n! Country !! Organization !! ISM staff !! Other workers !! Campuses !! Churches\n|-\n| USA || [[InterVarsity_Christian_Fellowship|InterVarsity (USA)]]<ref name=\"IVCF_ISM\">{{cite web | url=https://ism.intervarsity.org/home | access-date=19 February 2020 | title=International Student Ministry | website=InterVarsity }}</ref> || 100 || 100 \"engaged with internationals\" || 300 ||\n|-\n| USA || International Students Inc. (ISI)<ref name=\"ISI\">{{cite web | url=https://www.isionline.org/ | title=International Students Inc. (ISI) | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 350 ||  || || \n|-\n| USA || Bridges International<ref name=\"BridgesInternational\">{{cite web | title=Bridges International | url=https://www.bridgesinternational.com | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 315 || 87 \"staff ambassadors (part-time)\" || 200 ||\n|- \n| Canada || ISMC<ref name=\"ISMC\">{{cite web | url=https://ismc.ca/ | title=ISMC | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 110 || 500 volunteers || 52 || 100\n|-\n| Korea || International Students Fellowship || 80 || || 20 ||\n|-\n| Korea || Scientists & Engineers Members, International || 2 || 21 part time, 120 volunteers || 20 ||\n|-\n| Korea || InterVarsity Fellowship || 1 || 3 part time || ||\n|-\n| Singapore || Fellowship of Evangelical Students || 11 || || ||\n|-\n| Malaysia || Fellowship of Evangelical Students || 1 || 1 || ||\n|-\n| Japan || OMF || 2 || || ||\n|-\n| Japan || KGK || 6 || || 6 ||\n|-\n| New Zealand || ISMNZ<ref name=ISMNZ>{{cite web | url=https://www.ismnz.org.nz/| title=ISMNZ | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 40 || || 16 || 20\n|-\n| New Zealand || TSCF || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| New Zealand || OMF || 3 || || ||\n|-\n| UK || Friends International<ref name=\"FriendsInternational\">{{cite web | url=https://friendsinternational.uk/ | title=Friends International | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 75 || 60 affiliated staff || 35 || 250\n|-\n| UK || [[OMF_International|OMF]] || 8 || || ||\n|-\n| UK || Navigators || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| Germany || SMD (IFES) || 3 || || ||\n|-\n| Germany || OMF || 5 || || ||\n|-\n| Switzerland || VBG (IFES) || 2 || 3 || ||\n|-\n| Netherlands || IFES || 10 || || ||\n|-\n| Netherlands || OMF || 1 || || ||\n|-\n| France || Un Coeur Pour le Monde || 11 || || ||\n|-\n| South Africa || Bridge || 4 || 20 volunteers || ||\n|-\n| Philippines || FOCUS || 1 || 10 part time || || 4\n|-\n| Australia || [[Australian_Fellowship_of_Evangelical_Students|AFES]] FOCUS<ref name=\"AFES_FOCUS\">{{cite web | url=https://www.afes.org.au/page/focus | title=AFES FOCUS | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> || 53 || 18 apprentices || 28 ||\n|-\n| Australia || Navigators || 12 || || ||\n|-\n| Australia || OMF || 3 || || ||\n|-\n|}\n\nAt a global level, the [[Lausanne Committee for World Evangelization]] has an ISM issue network<ref name=\"LausanneISM\">{{cite web | url=https://www.lausanne.org/networks/issues/international-students | title=International Student Ministry (ISM) issue network | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> which connects groups internationally and interdenominationally. This network now includes a North American network on ISM.<ref name=MillerGlobal>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Beau |title=Global Outreach Opportunity: Ministry Among International Students |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/edstetzer/2019/october/global-outreach-opportunity-ministry-international-students.html |website=The Exchange: A Blog by Ed Stetzer |publisher=Christianity Today |accessdate=21 October 2019 |language=en |date=19 October 2019}}</ref> The Association for Christians Ministering Among Internationals (ACMI) is another ISM networking body.<ref name=\"ACMI\">{{cite web | url=https://www.acmi-ism.org/ | title=Association for Christians Ministering Among Internationals | access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MillerGlobal\"/>\n\n== Trends ==\n\nRecent decades have seen a rapid increase in international student populations<ref name=\"MigrationDataPortal\" /> concurrent with the plateauing of some western markets, most notably the US.<ref name=\"Zong1\">{{cite news |last1=Zong |first1=Jie |last2=Batalova |first2=Jeanne |title=International Students in the United States |url=https://www.migrationpolicy.org/article/international-students-united-states |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=migrationpolicy.org |date=9 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Redden1\">{{cite news |last1=Redden |first1=Elizabeth |title=With international enrollments slowing or declining in some top destination countries, a look at trends across the globe |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/24/international-enrollments-slowing-or-declining-some-top-destination-countries-look |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"FourMegatrends\">{{cite news |title=Four megatrends that are changing the competitive landscape of international education |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2016/11/four-megatrends-changing-competitive-landscape-international-education/ |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor - Market intelligence for international student recruitment |date=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"MappingTrends\">{{cite news |title=Mapping the trends that will shape international student mobility |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2017/07/mapping-trends-will-shape-international-student-mobility/ |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor - Market intelligence for international student recruitment |date=18 July 2017}}</ref> Students are turning to non-traditional centers of education, such as Asia.<ref name=\"Ning1\">{{cite web |last1=Luo |first1=Ning |title=Global Student Mobility Trends: Focus on Japan, Malaysia, Taiwan, and South Korea |url=https://wenr.wes.org/2017/08/global-mobility-japan-malaysia-taiwan-and-south-korea-seek-to-shift-student-mobility-by-2025 |website=WENR |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"StudyInternational1\">{{cite web |title=China emerges as the No.1 study abroad destination in Asia |url=https://www.studyinternational.com/news/china-emerges-as-the-no-1-study-abroad-destination-in-asia/ |website=Study International |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ICEF-up-down\">{{cite news |title=Up and down the table: Growth trends across major international study destinations |url=https://monitor.icef.com/2018/08/up-and-down-the-table-growth-trends-across-major-international-study-destinations/ |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=ICEF Monitor |date=29 August 2018}}</ref> This shift is underpinned by well-formed international [[Education_policy|education policy]] of countries like China,<ref name=\"Atack\">{{cite news |last1=Atack |first1=Patrick |title=China \"opening education to the outside world\" - policy document |url=https://thepienews.com/news/china-opening-education-to-the-outside-world-policy-document/ |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=The PIE News |date=12 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Parr1\">{{cite news |last1=Parr |first1=Chris |title=A two-way street: why China is not just a student departure lounge anymore |url=https://thepienews.com/analysis/international-students-in-china-increasingly-diverse/ |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=The PIE News |date=20 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Malaysia,<ref name=\"Zulita\">{{cite news |last1=Mustafa |first1=Zulita |title=International students and the Education Malaysia brand |url=https://www.nst.com.my/education/2017/09/284694/international-students-and-education-malaysia-brand |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=New Straits Times |date=27 September 2017 |language=en}}</ref> Singapore and India.<ref name=\"HansdeWit\">{{cite news |last1=de Wit |first1=Hans |title=The new dynamics in international student circulation |url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20180704143553337 |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=University World News |date=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe areas of diaspora missiology and its subset, international student ministry, have seen a theological and academic maturing.<ref name=\"Wan2014\">{{cite book |last1=Wan |first1=Enoch |title=Diaspora missiology: theory, methodology, and practice |date=Nov 2014 |publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform |isbn=978-1503095502 |edition=2nd }}</ref><ref name=ChinnAgents/><ref name=\"PocockWan2015\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Pocock |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Wan |editor2-first=Enoch |title=Diaspora Missions: Reflections on Reaching the Scattered Peoples of the World |date=August 2015 |publisher=William Carey Library |isbn=978-0878080458 }}</ref> In 2018/2019 two key ISM-specific training resources were launched: the ''Lausanne Global Classroom''<ref name=\"LausanneGlobalClassroom\">{{cite web |title=Lausanne Global Classroom: International Student Ministry |url=https://www.lausanne.org/lausanne-global-classroom/international-student-ministry-episode |website=Lausanne Movement |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=22 July 2019}}</ref> and ''EveryInternational''.<ref name=EveryInternational>{{cite web | title=Every International | url=https://everyinternational.com | accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MillerGlobal\"/> Two ISM training workshops ran at the [[International_Fellowship_of_Evangelical_Students|International Fellowship of Evangelical Students (IFES)]] World Assembly in July 2019.<ref name=IFESWA2019>{{cite web | url=https://ifesworld.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/IFES-WA19-Seminar-summaries-ALL.pdf | title=Messengers of Hope, IFES World Assembly 2019, All Seminars | date=July 2019 | access-date=4 March 2020 }}</ref> While practical ISM training is offered by a number of ISM organisations, the ''Charlotte '17'' conference considered the need for academic training and research in ISM led by seminaries and graduate schools.<ref name=Chinn2019/> [[Columbia_International_University|Columbia International University]] lists a course called \"Mission to International Students\" in their 2019-2020 Academic Catalog.<ref name=CIU2019>{{cite web | url=http://catalog.ciu.edu/mime/media/view/2/89/1920+Catalog+Complete.pdf | title=Columbia International University, 2019-2020 Academic Catalog | date=1 April 2019 | access-date=8 March 2020 | website=Columbia International University }}</ref>\n\nGlobal mission sending organizations are recognizing the strategic nature and necessity of diaspora missions, and especially ISM.<ref name=\"EddieArthur\">{{cite journal |last1=Eddie |first1=Arthur |title=The Future of Mission Agencies |journal=Mission Round Table |date=January 2017 |volume=12 |issue=1 |page=4\u201312 |url=https://omf.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/MRT-12.1-Future-of-Mission-Agencies.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BestGlobalCampus\">{{cite web |last1=Best |first1=Alexander |title=10 Reasons Why the Global Campus Is the Future of Mission |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/edstetzer/2019/july/10-reasons-why-global-campus-is-future-of-mission.html |website=The Exchange: A Blog by Ed Stetzer |publisher=Christianity Today |accessdate=21 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"ChinnAMA52\"/> Some have refocused ISM efforts in traditional contexts because of the perceived global impact.<ref name=\"ChinnLGA2017\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=The Mission Field Coming to Our Campuses |journal=Lausanne Global Analysis |date=January 2018 |volume=7 |issue=1 |url=https://www.lausanne.org/content/lga/2018-01/mission-field-coming-campuses |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> Asia has been identified as an emerging region for ISM.<ref name=\"ChinnAMA62\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=Broad Asian Global Mission Opportunity: Increasing Numbers of International Students in Pan-Asia Region |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=Jan 2019 |volume=62 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/broad-asian-global-mission-opportunity-increasing-numbers-of-international-students-in-pan-asia-region/ |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ChinnAMA42\">{{cite journal |last1=Chinn |first1=Leiton |title=International Student Ministry: A Most Strategic Yet Most Inexpensive Global Mission Opportunity Arises in Asia |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=January 2014 |volume=42 |page=2\u20137 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/ama_42.pdf |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> It is beginning to take shape there, for example among international churches in China.<ref name=\"MarkBlair\">{{cite journal |last1=Blair |first1=Mark |title=Looking for Gospel Laborers? Don't Forget the University! |journal=Asia Missions Advance |date=January 2019 |volume=62 |url=http://www.asiamissions.net/asian-missions-advances/amadvance-52-60/asian-missions-advance-62/ |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Momoh\">{{ cite web | last1=Momoh | first1=Miatta | url=https://www.chinasource.org/resource-library/chinasource-blog-posts/novel-gospel-opportunities | title=Novel Gospel Opportunities: How One International Church in China Is Maximizing New Gospel Opportunities | website=ChinaSource | date=21 February 2020 | access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=PhilJonesEMQ54-2>{{cite journal | last=Jones | first=Phil | date=April 2018 | url=https://www.missiontools.org/resources/emq-v54-i2/ | title=International Students in China: Who Will Reach This Vast and Strategic Yet Invisible Group? | journal=Evangelical Missions Quarterly | volume=54 | issue=2 | pages=46-57  | access-date=22 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=PhilJonesJan2019>{{cite web | title=The Birth of ISM in China: Is This God's Timing? | last1=Jones | first1=Phil | website=ChinaSource | date=25 January 2019 | access-date=22 February 2020 | url=https://www.chinasource.org/resource-library/chinasource-blog-posts/the-birth-of-ism-in-china }}</ref> Nascent ISMs exist in South Africa, Kenya and Ghana.<ref name=ChinnAgents/>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:International_student_religious_organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Philjones2510", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNetworks and organizations:Added paper by de Pater, Ryan and Tower", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_student_ministry"}
{"title_page": "Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections", "text_new": "{{Short description|national security concern}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections''' has become a question of concern at the highest level of [[National security of the United States|national security]] as well as in the [[computer industry|computer]] and [[social media]] industries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |title=Hackers Are Coming for the 2020 Election \u2014 And We're Not Ready |first=Andy |last=Kroll |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117192107/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, the American intelligence community advised members of Congress that Russia was attempting to interfere in the 2020 election.\n\n==Reports of attempted interference==\n\nIn response to [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], special counsel [[Robert Mueller]] conducted a two-year-long [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation]]. The resulting [[Mueller Report|report]] concluded that Russia interfered in \u201csweeping and systematic fashion\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422095933/https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf |date=April 22, 2019 }}'', vol. I, p. 1: \"The Russian government interfered in the 2016 presidential election in sweeping and systematic fashion\"</ref> In his July 2019 Congressional testimony, Mueller stated that the Russians continue to interfere in U.S. elections \"as we sit here\u201d, and that \"many more countries\" have developed disinformation campaigns targeting U.S. elections, based partly on the Russian model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mueller rejects Trump's claims of exoneration, 'witch hunt' |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |last1=Tucker |first1=Eric |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |last3=Balsamo |first3=Michael |quote=And [Mueller] said of the interference by Russians and others: \"They are doing it as we sit here. And they expect to do it during the next campaign.\" |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155844/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=July 25, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |title=Robert Mueller's testimony: The biggest takeaway is Russia's interference in US elections |work=CNN |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726211452/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso in July 2019, the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] released the first volume of a bipartisan report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections, a report that included recommendations for securing the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Targeted Election Systems in All 50 States, Report Finds |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-07-25 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Edmondson |first2=Catie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |quote=But while the bipartisan report's warning that the United States remains vulnerable in the next election is clear, its findings were so heavily redacted at the insistence of American intelligence agencies that even some key recommendations for 2020 were blacked out. |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727201549/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210348/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume of that report noted, based on social-media data from October 2018, that \"Russian disinformation efforts may be focused on gathering information and data points in support of an active measures campaign targeted at the 2020 U.S. presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election, Volume 2 |access-date=2019-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008172455/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |archive-date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nU.S. officials have accused [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Iran]] of trying to influence the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=US warns of 'ongoing' election interference by Russia, China, Iran |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |work=The Hill |date=October 19, 2018 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Sees Russia, China, Iran Trying to Influence 2020 Elections |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |work=Bloomberg |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US says Russia, China and Iran are trying to influence 2020 elections |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |work=The National |date=June 25, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082401/https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=2020 Election Meddling by China, Iran, N. Korea Likely, Administration Officials Warn |url=https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |work=Yahoo News |date=June 28, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082400/https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between January and late July 2017, [[Twitter]] identified and shut down over 7,000 phony accounts created by [[Iran]]ian influence operations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |title=It's not just the Russians anymore as Iranians and others turn up disinformation efforts ahead of 2020 vote |date=2019-07-25 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last1=Timberg |first1=Craig |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728001957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Christopher A. Wray]], the [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]], Russia is attempting to interfere with the [[2020 United States elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|title=FBI Director Wray: Russia intent on interfering with U.S. elections|date=July 23, 2019|work=Reuters|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723221517/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman-nyt\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Goldman |authorlink=Adam Goldman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |title=F.B.I. Warns of Russian Interference in 2020 Race and Boosts Counterintelligence Operations |work=The New York Times |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724161858/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Internet Trolls Are Apparently Switching Strategies for 2020 U.S. Elections |url=https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2019-03-09 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last=Sebenius |first=Alyza |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618030544/https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |archive-date=June 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Speaking to the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] in July 2019, Wray stated, \"We are very much viewing 2018 as just kind of a dress rehearsal for the big show in 2020.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |title=A brief history of administration officials warning that our elections are at risk from Russia |last=Bump |first=Philip |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729132406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Dan Coats]], the former [[Director of National Intelligence]], believes that Russia and China will both attempt to influence the elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |title=U.S. intel agencies: Russia and China plotting to interfere in 2020 election |website=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724194211/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |title=Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community |first=Daniel R. |last=Coats |authorlink=Dan Coats |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=2019-01-29 |website=[[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] |quote=Russia's social media efforts will continue to focus on aggravating social and racial tensions, undermining trust in authorities, and criticizing perceived anti-Russia politicians.  Moscow may employ additional influence toolkits\u2014such as spreading disinformation, conducting hack-and-leak operations, or manipulating data\u2014in a more targeted fashion to influence US policy, actions, and elections. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810023229/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVarious disinformation campaigns on social media have targeted the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates running in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |title='Sustained and ongoing' disinformation assault targets Dem presidential candidates; A coordinated barrage of social media attacks suggests the involvement of foreign state actors. |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |authorlink=Natasha Korecki |date=February 20, 2019 |website=[[Politico.com]] |publisher= |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724011259/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> This has prompted considerable concern regarding the ability of [[social media]] companies to cope with disinformation and manipulation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |title=The Technology 202: Social media companies readying to combat disinformation in Democratic debates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Zakrzewski |first=Cat |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |quote=Facebook and Twitter say they're taking additional precautions this week after analysis found debates were a key target for Russian actors seeking to sow discord on social media ahead of the 2016 election. The companies are under immense public pressure to avoid a repeat in 2020 after they say they were caught off guard by the foreign influence operations in 2016. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629042008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |archive-date=June 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |work=[[CBS News]] |title=Russian trolls fueled anti-vaccination debate in U.S. by spreading misinformation on Twitter, study finds |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |date=2019-05-31 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |quote=Facebook also said it would crack down on the spread of vaccine misinformation by de-prioritizing medical myths across the platform ...  however, misinformation about vaccines is not the only threat, as Russia is focusing on spreading misinformation around health care issues ahead of the 2020 election. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723003409/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By August 2019, [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] had banned advertisements that use misinformation to attempt the suppression of voter turnout.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |title=Maryland was never in play in 2016. The Russians targeted it anyway |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-08-28 |accessdate=2019-08-28 |last1=Priest |first1=Dana |last2=Aljas |first2=Riin |last3=Gelman |first3=Scott |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828211553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Microsoft]] developed an open source software called ElectionGuard to help safeguard the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |title=Ahead Of 2020, Microsoft Unveils Tool To Allow Voters To Track Their Ballots |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-05-06 |last=Parks |first=Miles |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727112620/https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-July 2019, Microsoft announced that it had, over the prior year, \"notified nearly 10,000 customers they've been targeted or compromised by nation-state attacks\". Based on attacks that had targeted political organizations, and on experience from 2016 and 2018, Microsoft anticipated \"attacks targeting U.S. election systems, political campaigns or NGOs that work closely with campaigns\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |title=New cyberthreats require new ways to protect democracy |last=Burt |first=Tom |website=[[Microsoft]] |date=2019-07-17 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727025240/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Of the \"nation-state attacks\" that had originated from Russia, Microsoft claimed that they followed the \"same pattern of engagement\" as Russian operations in 2016 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |title=Iranian cyber activity \"spiked\" after U.S. withdrawal from nuclear deal, says Microsoft official |last=Gazis |first=Olivia |date=2019-07-19 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130910/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 20, 2019, Microsoft announced that it would provide free security updates for [[Windows 7]], which reached its [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] on January 14, 2020, on federally-certified voting machines through the 2020 United States elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|title=Extending free Windows 7 security updates to voting systems|last=Burt|first=Tom|date=September 20, 2019|website=Microsoft On The Issues|url-status=live|access-date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218214735/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> On October 4, 2019, Microsoft announced that \"Phosphorus\", a group of hackers linked to the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]], had attempted to compromise e-mail accounts belonging to journalists, prominent Iranian expatriates, U.S. government officials and the campaign of a U.S. presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |title=Iranians tried to hack U.S. presidential candidate in effort that targeted hundreds, Microsoft says |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Jay |last1=Greene |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |title=Recent cyberattacks require us all to be vigilant |last=Burt |first=Tom |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |website=[[Microsoft]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004174845/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> While Microsoft did not disclose which campaign had been the target of the cyber attack, unnamed sources informed [[Reuters]] that it had been [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|that of Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump campaign targeted by Iran-linked hackers |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=October 4, 2019 |access-date=October 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006084141/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2019, Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] announced that his company has detected a \"highly sophisticated\" set of campaigns to interfere with the 2020 elections. These campaigns originated from Russia and from Iran.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |title=Mark Zuckerberg: Facebook caught Russia and Iran trying to interfere in 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Jason |last=Abbruzzese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021194958/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fake accounts based in Russia posed as Americans of varied political backgrounds and worked to undermine the campaign of [[Joe Biden]], aiming to sow discontent with Biden from [[Left\u2013right political spectrum|both the left and the right]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |title=Facebook: Russian trolls are back. And they're here to meddle with 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Donie |last=O'Sullivan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021170904/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA September 2019 report from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' demonstrated that due to bad default passwords and weak encryption, hackers with physical access can easily get into voting machines designed for use in the [[2020 United States elections]], and remote hacking was possible if the machines were accidentally misconfigured.<ref>{{cite web|website=Yahoo! Finance|title=Researchers easily breached voting machines for the 2020 election|author=Christine Fisher|date=Sep 27, 2019|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|access-date=January 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219201412/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2020, American intelligence officials advised members of the [[House Intelligence Committee]] that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |title=FBI official: Russia wants to see US 'tear ourselves apart' |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=2020-02-24 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |last=Tucker |first=Eric |quote=One intelligence official said lawmakers were not told that Russia was working directly to aid Trump. But other people familiar with the meeting said they were told the Kremlin was looking to help Trump's candidacy. The people spoke on condition of anonymity to discussed the classified briefing. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204303/https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The briefing was delivered by [[Shelby Pierson]], the intelligence community's top election security official and an aide to acting [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[Joseph Maguire]]. Trump allies on the committee challenged the findings, and Trump was angered to learn of the briefing as he believed Democrats might \"weaponize\" the information against him. He chastised Maguire for allowing the briefing to occur, and days later he appointed [[Richard Grenell]] to replace Maguire.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last1=Goldman | first1=Adam | last2=Barnes | first2=Julian E. | last3=Haberman | first3=Maggie | last4=Fandos | first4=Nicholas | title=Lawmakers Are Warned That Russia Is Meddling to Re-elect Trump | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225234247/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Acosta | first=Jim | last2=Cohen | first2=Zachary | last3=Bash | first3=Dana | last4=Herb | first4=Jeremy | title=Russia is looking to help Trump win in 2020, election security official told lawmakers | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226001124/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Nakashima | first=Ellen | last2=Harris | first2=Shane | last3=Dawsey | first3=Josh | last4=Gearan | first4=Anne | title=Senior intelligence official told lawmakers that Russia wants to see Trump reelected | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225222025/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that, according to unnamed US officials, Russia was interfering in the Democratic primary in an effort to support the nomination of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]. Sanders issued a statement after the news report, saying in part, \"I don't care, frankly, who Putin wants to be president. My message to Putin is clear: stay out of American elections, and as president I will make sure that you do.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders acknowledged that his campaign was briefed about Russia's alleged efforts about a month prior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Is Said to Be Interfering to Aid Sanders in Democratic Primaries |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222132741/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders suggested that Russians were impersonating people claiming to be his supporters online in order to create an atmosphere of toxicity and give \"[[Bernie Bro]]s\" a bad reputation, a suggestion that [[Twitter]] rejected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts Say There's 'No Evidence' for Bernie's Russian Bot Claim |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/experts-call-bs-on-bernies-russian-bot-theory |work=The Daily Beast |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter knocks down Bernie Sanders' suggestion that Russian trolls are behind online attacks from his supporters |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |work=CNBC |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222115000/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to election-security expert Laura Rosenberger, \"Russian attempts to sow discord in the Democratic primary would be consistent with its strategy of undermining Americans' faith in democratic institutions and processes.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\"/>\n\nIn March 2020, the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] published a report indicating that Russia-linked social media accounts have been spreading [[Instagram]] posts calculated to sow division among American voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|title=Report: Russian social accounts sow election discord - again|last=Seitz|first=Amanda|last2=Ortutay|first2=Barbara|date=2020-03-05|website=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309180450/https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"brennan\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|title=New Evidence Shows How Russia's Election Interference Has Gotten More Brazen|last=Kim|first=Young Mie|date=2020-05-05|website=[[Brennan Center for Justice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311173959/https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to the report, Russian operatives were increasingly impersonating real political candidates and groups rather than creating fictional groups.<ref name=\"brennan\" /> According to Twitter's head of site integrity, Russian agents also attempted in 2018 to create the impression of more election interference than is actually happening to undermine confidence in the process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/05/812497423/report-russian-election-trolling-becoming-subtler-tougher-to-detect Report: Russian Election Trolling Becoming Subtler, Tougher To Detect]</ref> Shortly thereafter, the ''New York Times'' reported that according to American intelligence officials Russian operatives have been promoting and pressuring [[hate group]]s, including [[neo-Nazis]], in order to create strife within American society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|title=Russia Trying to Stoke U.S. Racial Tensions Before Election, Officials Say|date=2020-03-10|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310192420/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A [[CNN]] investigation found that Russian efforts had partly been outsourced to [[troll farm]]s in [[Ghana]] and [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |title=Russian election meddling is back \u2014 via Ghana and Nigeria \u2014 and in your feeds |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-12 |work=[[CNN]] |first1=Clarissa |last1=Ward |first2=Katie |last2=Polglase |first3=Sebastian |last3=Shukla |first4=Gianluca |last4=Mezzofiore |first5=Tim |last5=Lister |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312232339/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government reaction==\n\n[[Dan Coats]] appointed [[Shelby Pierson]] as the U.S. election security [[Czar (political term)|czar]] in July 2019, creating a new position in a move seen as an acknowledgment that foreign influence operations against U.S. elections will be ongoing indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |title=Intelligence Chief Names New Election Security Oversight Official |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140612/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |title=Dan Coats, Who Challenged President Trump, Is Ousted From Top Intelligence Job |last=Myre |first=Greg |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728220444/https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security task forces established before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] at the FBI, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], the [[National Security Agency]] and the [[United States Cyber Command]] have been expanded and \"made permanent\".<ref name=\"goldman-nyt\"/> The Department of Homeland Security indicated that the threat of [[ransomware]] attacks upon [[voter registration]] databases was a particular concern.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |title=U.S. officials fear ransomware attack against 2020 election |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2019-08-26 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Bing |first=Christopher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827174333/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to resigning as [[U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security]], [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] attempted to organize a meeting of the [[U.S. Cabinet]] to discuss how to address potential foreign interference in the 2020 elections. [[Mick Mulvaney]], the [[White House Chief of Staff]], reportedly warned her to keep the subject away from Trump, who views the discussion as questioning the legitimacy of his victory in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-04-24 |title=In Push for 2020 Election Security, Top Official Was Warned: Don't Tell Trump |last1=Schmitt |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric P. Schmitt |last2=Sanger |first2=David E. |authorlink2=David E. Sanger |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |authorlink3=Maggie Haberman |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727194235/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]], the [[Senate Majority Leader]], has blocked various bills intended to improve election security from being considered,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |title=Russia Is Using Cold War Strategy to Undermine the Faith of Americans in the 2020 Election\u2014Will It Work? |website=[[Newsweek]] |date=2019-07-23 |last=Piore |first=Adam |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727231644/https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |url=https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |title=#MoscowMitch Trends on Twitter as Mitch McConnell Blocks Election Security Bills Despite 'Unprecedented Level' of Russian Interference |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726192133/https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |title=How the U.S. is trying to improve election security ahead of 2020 |last=Martinez |first=Gabriela |date=2019-07-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |website=[[PBS Newshour]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727232600/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> including some measures that have had bipartisan support.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |title=Hill push to battle foreign election interference is stuck at McConnell roadblock |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-06-13 |accessdate=2019-07-30 |quote=In fact, some GOP senators have joined with Democrats to co-sponsor legislation designed to shore up voting machines and make it harder for foreign intelligence operatives to hack, leak and manipulate social media the way the Russians did in 2016. But those bills are going nowhere \u2014 because Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has not allowed a vote on any of them. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723050705/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |title=Russia Is Going To Up Its Game For The 2020 Elections |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Laslo |first=Matt |date=2019-07-31 |accessdate=2019-08-02 |quote=Both bills have bipartisan support\u2014Senator Susan Collins became the first Republican to cosponsor the Foreign Influence Reporting in Elections Act earlier this week. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801204804/https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security legislation remains stalled in the Senate as of February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|title=Senate GOP blocks three election security bills|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=2020-02-11|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211215724/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> However, various states have implemented changes, such as [[paper ballot]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=States Rush to Make Voting Systems More Secure as New Threats Emerge |date=2019-07-26 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Epstein |first2=Reid J. |last3=Wines |first3=Michael |authorlink3=Michael Wines |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727001938/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Florida]] has expanded its paper-ballot backup system since 2016, but experts warn that its voting systems are still vulnerable to manipulation, a particular concern being the electronic poll books that store lists of registered voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |title=Russian hackers likely to target Florida again in 2020 election, experts warn |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-08-27 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Stone |first=Peter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827143332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> All 67 election supervisors in Florida have been required to sign [[nondisclosure agreement]]s, and consequently, information such as the identity of which four counties had been hacked by Russian intelligence in 2016 remains unknown to the public.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |title=Will your vote count? Veil of secrecy makes it impossible for Florida voters to know |first=Jeffrey |last=Schweers |date=2020-02-25 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204743/https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] members of Congress cited the lack of effort to secure U.S. elections against foreign interference, particularly from Russia, as among grounds to begin an [[impeachment]] inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |title=Dem lawmaker to her party: 'Take action' on impeachment by September or 'shut it down' |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |work=[[CNN]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727145555/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |title=Rep. Clark Backs Impeachment Probe, Putting Pressure On Pelosi |work=[[WBUR]] |last1=Swasey |first1=Benjamin |last2=Atkins |first2=Kimberley |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727170338/https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |title=All Washington House Democrats now favor Trump impeachment inquiry |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729131505/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article233239221.html |title=U.S. Reps Heck, Kilmer, Schreir, and Del Bene announce support of impeachment inquiry |work=[[The Olympian]] |last=Boone |first=Rolf |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, the United States issued economic sanctions against seven Russians affiliated with the [[Internet Research Agency]], an organization that manipulates social media for misinformation purposes. The sanctions were described as a warning against foreign interference in United States elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |title=With Sanctions on Russians, U.S. Warns Against Foreign Election Meddling |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 30, 2019 |last=Jakes |first=Lara |access-date=October 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001022221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2019, FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray]] told ABC News: \"as far as the [2020] election itself goes, we think Russia represents the most significant threat.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|title=FBI Director Chris Wray reacts to DOJ watchdog report on Russia investigation: Exclusive|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219051108/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[William Evanina]], director of the [[National Counterintelligence and Security Center]], Russia is \"using social media and many other tools to inflame social divisions, promote conspiracy theories and sow distrust in our democracy and elections.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |title=U.S. Probes If Russia Is Targeting Biden in 2020 Election Meddling |first=Chris |last=Strohm |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110210442/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |archive-date=January 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Bloomberg News'' reported in January 2020 that American intelligence and law enforcement were examining whether Russia was involved in promoting disinformation to undermine Joe Biden as part of a campaign to disrupt the 2020 election.<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\"/> The following month, the [[Estonian Foreign Intelligence Service]] warned that Russia would attempt to interfere in the [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[2020 Georgian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] in October 2020 as well as the US election in November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |title=Russia will try to meddle in 2020 U.S. election, intelligence report says |work=[[NBC News]] |date=February 12, 2020 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |last=Kube |first=Courtney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration reaction ===\n\nThe Trump administration reacted to the briefing by American intelligence officials to the House Intelligence Committee that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>  by rejecting the efforts were in favor of Trump<ref name=\"Diamond_Tapper_Cohen_2/23/2020\">{{cite web | last=Diamond | first=Jeremy | last2=Tapper | first2=Jake | last3=Cohen | first3=Zachary | title=US intelligence briefer appears to have overstated assessment of 2020 Russian interference | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 23, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226015505/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by firing Joseph Maguire, who was involved in those reports.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Trump and his national security adviser [[Robert C. O'Brien (attorney)|Robert O'Brien]]<ref name=\"Sanger_2/24/2020\">{{cite web | last=Sanger | first=David E. | title=Dueling Narratives Emerge From Muddied Account of Russia's 2020 Interference | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 24, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225231616/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> accepted reports the Russians were supporting the nomination of Bernie Sanders.<ref name=\"Pengelly_2/22/2020\">{{cite web | last=Pengelly | first=Martin | title=Donald Trump pounces on reports Russia is seeking to help Bernie Sanders | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=February 22, 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225170801/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after Trump loyalist [[Richard Grenell]] was appointed acting [[Director of National Intelligence]], intelligence officials briefed members of Congress behind closed doors that they had \"not concluded that the Kremlin is directly aiding any candidate\u2019s re-election or any other candidates\u2019 election,\" which differed from testimony they had provided the previous month indicating that Russia was working to aid Trump's candidacy. Two intelligence officials pushed back on suggestions the new testimony was politically motivated. One intelligence official asserted the earlier testimony had overreached and that Democrats had mischaracterized it. [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal#Kashyap Patel|Kash Patel]], a former aide to congressman [[Devin Nunes]] who joined Grenell at the ODNI, imposed limits on what intelligence officials could tell Congress about foreign influence operations. The briefers reportedly did not intend to contradict their previous testimony, though they avoided repeating it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311165910/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221010559/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency of Donald Trump==\n\nIn a June 2019 interview with [[George Stephanopoulos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] said that he would accept information from other nations about his opponents in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Baker (journalist) |title=Trump Says 'I'd Take It' if Russia Again Offered Dirt on Opponent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |work=The New York Times |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |title=Transcript: ABC News' George Stephanopoulos' exclusive interview with President Trump |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=June 16, 2019 |website=ABC News |access-date=31 July 2019 |quote=[[George Stephanopoulos|STEPHANOPOULOS]]: Your campaign this time around, if foreigners, if Russia, if China, if someone else offers you information on opponents, should they accept it or should they call the FBI?  TRUMP: I think maybe you do both. I think you might want to listen, I don't, there's nothing wrong with listening. If somebody called from a country, Norway, \"We have information on your opponent.\" Oh, I think I'd want to hear it.  STEPHANOPOULOS: You want that kind of interference in our elections?  TRUMP: It's not an interference, they have information. I think I'd take it. If I thought there was something wrong, I'd go maybe to the FBI. If I thought there was something wrong. But when somebody comes up with oppo research, right, that they come up with oppo research. Oh, let's call the FBI. The FBI doesn't have enough agents to take care of it, but you go and talk honestly to congressmen, they all do it, they always have. And that's the way it is. It's called oppo research.  STEPHANOPOULOS: Surprising. Thank you.  TRUMP: Thank you. Okay. Fine. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801032648/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to reporting by ''The Wall Street Journal'', ''The Washington Post'' and ''The New York Times'', Trump and his personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] repeatedly pressed the [[Government of Ukraine|Ukrainian government]] to investigate [[Hunter Biden]], the son of [[Joe Biden]], leading to the {{As of|2020|1|9|df=US|alt=ongoing}} [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive &#124; Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|title=Trump pressed Ukrainian leader to investigate Biden's son, according to people familiar with the matter|website=Washington Post|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922233816/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|archive-date=September 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|title=Trump Pressed Ukraine's Leader on Inquiry Into Biden's Son|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael S.|last2=Schmidt|first3=Kenneth P.|last3=Vogel|first4=Adam|last4=Goldman|first5=Maggie|last5=Haberman|date=September 20, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923114022/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Biden is a potentially strong Trump challenger in the 2020 presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|last=Volz|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine Pressured on U.S. Political Investigations|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=September 20, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920171010/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The purpose of the requested investigation was alleged to be to damage [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's election campaign]] for president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|title=WSJ: Trump urged Ukrainian president \"about 8 times\" to investigate Biden's son|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210637/https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|title=Is Trump Trying to Get Ukraine to Take Out Biden for Him?|last=Mackinnon|first=Amy|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210034/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggested that Trump threatened to withhold [[military aid]] from [[Ukraine]] unless they investigate Biden.<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|title=Did Trump Try to Extort the President of Ukraine Into Investigating Joe Biden?|last=Cassidy|first=John|date=September 20, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920205009/https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The controversy triggered the commencement of the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|formal process of impeachment inquiries against Trump]] on September 24, with House speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] directing six House committee chairmen to proceed \"under that umbrella of impeachment inquiry\".<ref name = formal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |title=House Speaker Nancy Pelosi announces formal impeachment inquiry of Trump, says his actions were a 'betrayal of national security' |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201421/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |archive-date=September 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2019, Trump said that \"[[China]] should start an investigation\" into [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|presidential candidate]] Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Moments before, while discussing negotiations on a possible agreement in the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]], he said that \"if they [China] don't do what we want, we have tremendous power.\" Chair of the [[Federal Election Commission]] [[Ellen Weintraub]] then retweeted a June statement explaining that \"it is illegal for any person to solicit, accept, or receive anything of value from a foreign national in connection with a U.S. election\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|publisher=NBC News|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003160859/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|10|alt=As of early October 2019}}, there is evidence President Trump, Vice President [[Mike Pence]], U.S. Attorney General [[William Barr]], as well as Trump's personal attorney Giuliani have solicited help from Ukraine, Australia, Italy, the United Kingdom, and China for assistance in discrediting Trump's political opponents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|title=Trump ordered removal of ambassador over Biden probe; president calls for China to investigate Bidens|first1=Colby|last1=Itkowitz|first2=John|last2=Wagner|first3=Felicia|last3=Sonmez|date=October 4, 2019|via=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004204355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|title=Trump Publicly Urges China to Investigate the Bidens|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Eileen|last2=Sullivan|date=October 3, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004231604/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|title=Trump Administration Used Potential Meeting to Pressure Ukraine on Biden, Texts Indicate|first=Rebecca Ballhaus, Siobhan Hughes and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004172356/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|title=Trump now says both China and Ukraine should investigate Bidens|author=Kevin Liptak|website=CNN|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193006/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|title=Not just Ukraine: Trump now calls for China to probe Bidens|date=October 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175445/https://www.apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|title=Trump says China should investigate Bidens|website=Axios|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004081222/https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|website=NBC News|access-date=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205659/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|title=Trump says China should investigate the Bidens, doubles down on Ukraine probe|first=Kevin|last=Breuninger|date=October 3, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193118/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|first1=Julian|last1=Borger|first2=Lauren|last2=Gambino|date=October 3, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027153313/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=October 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Second American Civil War#Culture war as Second American Civil War|Cold Civil war]]\n*[[Cold War II]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare and Iran]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare by Russia]]\n*[[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks]]\n*[[Foreign electoral intervention]]\n*[[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n*[[Russian espionage in the United States]]\n*[[Russian interference in the 2018 United States elections]]\n*[[Social media in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n*[[Social media in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n*2016 interference timeline\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n**[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[1996 United States campaign finance controversy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]-->\n[[Category:2020 elections in the United States]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign electoral intervention]]\n[[Category:Internet manipulation and propaganda]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:Information operations and warfare]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|national security concern}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections''' has become a question of concern at the highest level of [[National security of the United States|national security]] as well as in the [[computer industry|computer]] and [[social media]] industries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |title=Hackers Are Coming for the 2020 Election \u2014 And We're Not Ready |first=Andy |last=Kroll |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117192107/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, the American intelligence community advised members of Congress that Russia was attempting to interfere in the 2020 election.\n\n==Reports of attempted interference==\n\nIn response to [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], special counsel [[Robert Mueller]] conducted a two-year-long [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation]]. The resulting [[Mueller Report|report]] concluded that Russia interfered in \u201csweeping and systematic fashion\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422095933/https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf |date=April 22, 2019 }}'', vol. I, p. 1: \"The Russian government interfered in the 2016 presidential election in sweeping and systematic fashion\"</ref> In his July 2019 Congressional testimony, Mueller stated that the Russians continue to interfere in U.S. elections \"as we sit here\u201d, and that \"many more countries\" have developed disinformation campaigns targeting U.S. elections, based partly on the Russian model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mueller rejects Trump's claims of exoneration, 'witch hunt' |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |last1=Tucker |first1=Eric |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |last3=Balsamo |first3=Michael |quote=And [Mueller] said of the interference by Russians and others: \"They are doing it as we sit here. And they expect to do it during the next campaign.\" |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155844/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=July 25, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |title=Robert Mueller's testimony: The biggest takeaway is Russia's interference in US elections |work=CNN |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726211452/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso in July 2019, the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] released the first volume of a bipartisan report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections, a report that included recommendations for securing the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Targeted Election Systems in All 50 States, Report Finds |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-07-25 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Edmondson |first2=Catie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |quote=But while the bipartisan report's warning that the United States remains vulnerable in the next election is clear, its findings were so heavily redacted at the insistence of American intelligence agencies that even some key recommendations for 2020 were blacked out. |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727201549/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210348/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume of that report noted, based on social-media data from October 2018, that \"Russian disinformation efforts may be focused on gathering information and data points in support of an active measures campaign targeted at the 2020 U.S. presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election, Volume 2 |access-date=2019-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008172455/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |archive-date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nU.S. officials have accused [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Iran]] of trying to influence the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=US warns of 'ongoing' election interference by Russia, China, Iran |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |work=The Hill |date=October 19, 2018 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Sees Russia, China, Iran Trying to Influence 2020 Elections |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |work=Bloomberg |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US says Russia, China and Iran are trying to influence 2020 elections |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |work=The National |date=June 25, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082401/https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=2020 Election Meddling by China, Iran, N. Korea Likely, Administration Officials Warn |url=https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |work=Yahoo News |date=June 28, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082400/https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between January and late July 2017, [[Twitter]] identified and shut down over 7,000 phony accounts created by [[Iran]]ian influence operations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |title=It's not just the Russians anymore as Iranians and others turn up disinformation efforts ahead of 2020 vote |date=2019-07-25 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last1=Timberg |first1=Craig |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728001957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Christopher A. Wray]], the [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]], Russia is attempting to interfere with the [[2020 United States elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|title=FBI Director Wray: Russia intent on interfering with U.S. elections|date=July 23, 2019|work=Reuters|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723221517/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman-nyt\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Goldman |authorlink=Adam Goldman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |title=F.B.I. Warns of Russian Interference in 2020 Race and Boosts Counterintelligence Operations |work=The New York Times |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724161858/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Internet Trolls Are Apparently Switching Strategies for 2020 U.S. Elections |url=https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2019-03-09 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last=Sebenius |first=Alyza |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618030544/https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |archive-date=June 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Speaking to the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] in July 2019, Wray stated, \"We are very much viewing 2018 as just kind of a dress rehearsal for the big show in 2020.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |title=A brief history of administration officials warning that our elections are at risk from Russia |last=Bump |first=Philip |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729132406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Dan Coats]], the former [[Director of National Intelligence]], believes that Russia and China will both attempt to influence the elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |title=U.S. intel agencies: Russia and China plotting to interfere in 2020 election |website=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724194211/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |title=Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community |first=Daniel R. |last=Coats |authorlink=Dan Coats |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=2019-01-29 |website=[[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] |quote=Russia's social media efforts will continue to focus on aggravating social and racial tensions, undermining trust in authorities, and criticizing perceived anti-Russia politicians.  Moscow may employ additional influence toolkits\u2014such as spreading disinformation, conducting hack-and-leak operations, or manipulating data\u2014in a more targeted fashion to influence US policy, actions, and elections. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810023229/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVarious disinformation campaigns on social media have targeted the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates running in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |title='Sustained and ongoing' disinformation assault targets Dem presidential candidates; A coordinated barrage of social media attacks suggests the involvement of foreign state actors. |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |authorlink=Natasha Korecki |date=February 20, 2019 |website=[[Politico.com]] |publisher= |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724011259/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> This has prompted considerable concern regarding the ability of [[social media]] companies to cope with disinformation and manipulation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |title=The Technology 202: Social media companies readying to combat disinformation in Democratic debates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Zakrzewski |first=Cat |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |quote=Facebook and Twitter say they're taking additional precautions this week after analysis found debates were a key target for Russian actors seeking to sow discord on social media ahead of the 2016 election. The companies are under immense public pressure to avoid a repeat in 2020 after they say they were caught off guard by the foreign influence operations in 2016. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629042008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |archive-date=June 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |work=[[CBS News]] |title=Russian trolls fueled anti-vaccination debate in U.S. by spreading misinformation on Twitter, study finds |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |date=2019-05-31 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |quote=Facebook also said it would crack down on the spread of vaccine misinformation by de-prioritizing medical myths across the platform ...  however, misinformation about vaccines is not the only threat, as Russia is focusing on spreading misinformation around health care issues ahead of the 2020 election. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723003409/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By August 2019, [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] had banned advertisements that use misinformation to attempt the suppression of voter turnout.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |title=Maryland was never in play in 2016. The Russians targeted it anyway |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-08-28 |accessdate=2019-08-28 |last1=Priest |first1=Dana |last2=Aljas |first2=Riin |last3=Gelman |first3=Scott |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828211553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Microsoft]] developed an open source software called ElectionGuard to help safeguard the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |title=Ahead Of 2020, Microsoft Unveils Tool To Allow Voters To Track Their Ballots |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-05-06 |last=Parks |first=Miles |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727112620/https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-July 2019, Microsoft announced that it had, over the prior year, \"notified nearly 10,000 customers they've been targeted or compromised by nation-state attacks\". Based on attacks that had targeted political organizations, and on experience from 2016 and 2018, Microsoft anticipated \"attacks targeting U.S. election systems, political campaigns or NGOs that work closely with campaigns\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |title=New cyberthreats require new ways to protect democracy |last=Burt |first=Tom |website=[[Microsoft]] |date=2019-07-17 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727025240/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Of the \"nation-state attacks\" that had originated from Russia, Microsoft claimed that they followed the \"same pattern of engagement\" as Russian operations in 2016 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |title=Iranian cyber activity \"spiked\" after U.S. withdrawal from nuclear deal, says Microsoft official |last=Gazis |first=Olivia |date=2019-07-19 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130910/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 20, 2019, Microsoft announced that it would provide free security updates for [[Windows 7]], which reached its [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] on January 14, 2020, on federally-certified voting machines through the 2020 United States elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|title=Extending free Windows 7 security updates to voting systems|last=Burt|first=Tom|date=September 20, 2019|website=Microsoft On The Issues|url-status=live|access-date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218214735/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> On October 4, 2019, Microsoft announced that \"Phosphorus\", a group of hackers linked to the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]], had attempted to compromise e-mail accounts belonging to journalists, prominent Iranian expatriates, U.S. government officials and the campaign of a U.S. presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |title=Iranians tried to hack U.S. presidential candidate in effort that targeted hundreds, Microsoft says |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Jay |last1=Greene |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |title=Recent cyberattacks require us all to be vigilant |last=Burt |first=Tom |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |website=[[Microsoft]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004174845/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> While Microsoft did not disclose which campaign had been the target of the cyber attack, unnamed sources informed [[Reuters]] that it had been [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|that of Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump campaign targeted by Iran-linked hackers |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=October 4, 2019 |access-date=October 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006084141/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2019, Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] announced that his company has detected a \"highly sophisticated\" set of campaigns to interfere with the 2020 elections. These campaigns originated from Russia and from Iran.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |title=Mark Zuckerberg: Facebook caught Russia and Iran trying to interfere in 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Jason |last=Abbruzzese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021194958/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fake accounts based in Russia posed as Americans of varied political backgrounds and worked to undermine the campaign of [[Joe Biden]], aiming to sow discontent with Biden from [[Left\u2013right political spectrum|both the left and the right]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |title=Facebook: Russian trolls are back. And they're here to meddle with 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Donie |last=O'Sullivan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021170904/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA September 2019 report from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' demonstrated that due to bad default passwords and weak encryption, hackers with physical access can easily get into voting machines designed for use in the [[2020 United States elections]], and remote hacking was possible if the machines were accidentally misconfigured.<ref>{{cite web|website=Yahoo! Finance|title=Researchers easily breached voting machines for the 2020 election|author=Christine Fisher|date=Sep 27, 2019|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|access-date=January 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219201412/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2020, American intelligence officials advised members of the [[House Intelligence Committee]] that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |title=FBI official: Russia wants to see US 'tear ourselves apart' |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=2020-02-24 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |last=Tucker |first=Eric |quote=One intelligence official said lawmakers were not told that Russia was working directly to aid Trump. But other people familiar with the meeting said they were told the Kremlin was looking to help Trump's candidacy. The people spoke on condition of anonymity to discussed the classified briefing. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204303/https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The briefing was delivered by [[Shelby Pierson]], the intelligence community's top election security official and an aide to acting [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[Joseph Maguire]]. Trump allies on the committee challenged the findings, and Trump was angered to learn of the briefing as he believed Democrats might \"weaponize\" the information against him. He chastised Maguire for allowing the briefing to occur, and days later he appointed [[Richard Grenell]] to replace Maguire.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last1=Goldman | first1=Adam | last2=Barnes | first2=Julian E. | last3=Haberman | first3=Maggie | last4=Fandos | first4=Nicholas | title=Lawmakers Are Warned That Russia Is Meddling to Re-elect Trump | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225234247/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Acosta | first=Jim | last2=Cohen | first2=Zachary | last3=Bash | first3=Dana | last4=Herb | first4=Jeremy | title=Russia is looking to help Trump win in 2020, election security official told lawmakers | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226001124/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Nakashima | first=Ellen | last2=Harris | first2=Shane | last3=Dawsey | first3=Josh | last4=Gearan | first4=Anne | title=Senior intelligence official told lawmakers that Russia wants to see Trump reelected | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225222025/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that, according to unnamed US officials, Russia was interfering in the Democratic primary in an effort to support the nomination of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]. Sanders issued a statement after the news report, saying in part, \"I don't care, frankly, who Putin wants to be president. My message to Putin is clear: stay out of American elections, and as president I will make sure that you do.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders acknowledged that his campaign was briefed about Russia's alleged efforts about a month prior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Is Said to Be Interfering to Aid Sanders in Democratic Primaries |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222132741/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders suggested that Russians were impersonating people claiming to be his supporters online in order to create an atmosphere of toxicity and give \"[[Bernie Bro]]s\" a bad reputation, a suggestion that [[Twitter]] rejected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts Say There's 'No Evidence' for Bernie's Russian Bot Claim |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/experts-call-bs-on-bernies-russian-bot-theory |work=The Daily Beast |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter knocks down Bernie Sanders' suggestion that Russian trolls are behind online attacks from his supporters |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |work=CNBC |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222115000/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to election-security expert Laura Rosenberger, \"Russian attempts to sow discord in the Democratic primary would be consistent with its strategy of undermining Americans' faith in democratic institutions and processes.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\"/>\n\nIn March 2020, the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] published a report indicating that Russia-linked social media accounts have been spreading [[Instagram]] posts calculated to sow division among American voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|title=Report: Russian social accounts sow election discord - again|last=Seitz|first=Amanda|last2=Ortutay|first2=Barbara|date=2020-03-05|website=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309180450/https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"brennan\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|title=New Evidence Shows How Russia's Election Interference Has Gotten More Brazen|last=Kim|first=Young Mie|date=2020-05-05|website=[[Brennan Center for Justice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311173959/https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to the report, Russian operatives were increasingly impersonating real political candidates and groups rather than creating fictional groups.<ref name=\"brennan\" /> According to Twitter's head of site integrity, Russian agents also attempted in 2018 to create the impression of more election interference than is actually happening to undermine confidence in the process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/05/812497423/report-russian-election-trolling-becoming-subtler-tougher-to-detect Report: Russian Election Trolling Becoming Subtler, Tougher To Detect]</ref> Shortly thereafter, the ''New York Times'' reported that according to American intelligence officials Russian operatives have been promoting and pressuring [[hate group]]s, including [[neo-Nazis]], in order to create strife within American society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|title=Russia Trying to Stoke U.S. Racial Tensions Before Election, Officials Say|date=2020-03-10|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310192420/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A [[CNN]] investigation found that Russian efforts had partly been outsourced to [[troll farm]]s in [[Ghana]] and [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |title=Russian election meddling is back \u2014 via Ghana and Nigeria \u2014 and in your feeds |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-12 |work=[[CNN]] |first1=Clarissa |last1=Ward |first2=Katie |last2=Polglase |first3=Sebastian |last3=Shukla |first4=Gianluca |last4=Mezzofiore |first5=Tim |last5=Lister |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312232339/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government reaction==\n\n[[Dan Coats]] appointed [[Shelby Pierson]] as the U.S. election security [[Czar (political term)|czar]] in July 2019, creating a new position in a move seen as an acknowledgment that foreign influence operations against U.S. elections will be ongoing indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |title=Intelligence Chief Names New Election Security Oversight Official |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140612/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |title=Dan Coats, Who Challenged President Trump, Is Ousted From Top Intelligence Job |last=Myre |first=Greg |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728220444/https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security task forces established before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] at the FBI, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], the [[National Security Agency]] and the [[United States Cyber Command]] have been expanded and \"made permanent\".<ref name=\"goldman-nyt\"/> The Department of Homeland Security indicated that the threat of [[ransomware]] attacks upon [[voter registration]] databases was a particular concern.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |title=U.S. officials fear ransomware attack against 2020 election |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2019-08-26 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Bing |first=Christopher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827174333/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to resigning as [[U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security]], [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] attempted to organize a meeting of the [[U.S. Cabinet]] to discuss how to address potential foreign interference in the 2020 elections. [[Mick Mulvaney]], the [[White House Chief of Staff]], reportedly warned her to keep the subject away from Trump, who views the discussion as questioning the legitimacy of his victory in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-04-24 |title=In Push for 2020 Election Security, Top Official Was Warned: Don't Tell Trump |last1=Schmitt |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric P. Schmitt |last2=Sanger |first2=David E. |authorlink2=David E. Sanger |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |authorlink3=Maggie Haberman |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727194235/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]], the [[Senate Majority Leader]], has blocked various bills intended to improve election security from being considered,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |title=Russia Is Using Cold War Strategy to Undermine the Faith of Americans in the 2020 Election\u2014Will It Work? |website=[[Newsweek]] |date=2019-07-23 |last=Piore |first=Adam |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727231644/https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |url=https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |title=#MoscowMitch Trends on Twitter as Mitch McConnell Blocks Election Security Bills Despite 'Unprecedented Level' of Russian Interference |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726192133/https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |title=How the U.S. is trying to improve election security ahead of 2020 |last=Martinez |first=Gabriela |date=2019-07-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |website=[[PBS Newshour]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727232600/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> including some measures that have had bipartisan support.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |title=Hill push to battle foreign election interference is stuck at McConnell roadblock |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-06-13 |accessdate=2019-07-30 |quote=In fact, some GOP senators have joined with Democrats to co-sponsor legislation designed to shore up voting machines and make it harder for foreign intelligence operatives to hack, leak and manipulate social media the way the Russians did in 2016. But those bills are going nowhere \u2014 because Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has not allowed a vote on any of them. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723050705/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |title=Russia Is Going To Up Its Game For The 2020 Elections |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Laslo |first=Matt |date=2019-07-31 |accessdate=2019-08-02 |quote=Both bills have bipartisan support\u2014Senator Susan Collins became the first Republican to cosponsor the Foreign Influence Reporting in Elections Act earlier this week. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801204804/https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security legislation remains stalled in the Senate as of February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|title=Senate GOP blocks three election security bills|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=2020-02-11|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211215724/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> However, various states have implemented changes, such as [[paper ballot]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=States Rush to Make Voting Systems More Secure as New Threats Emerge |date=2019-07-26 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Epstein |first2=Reid J. |last3=Wines |first3=Michael |authorlink3=Michael Wines |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727001938/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Florida]] has expanded its paper-ballot backup system since 2016, but experts warn that its voting systems are still vulnerable to manipulation, a particular concern being the electronic poll books that store lists of registered voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |title=Russian hackers likely to target Florida again in 2020 election, experts warn |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-08-27 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Stone |first=Peter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827143332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> All 67 election supervisors in Florida have been required to sign [[nondisclosure agreement]]s, and consequently, information such as the identity of which four counties had been hacked by Russian intelligence in 2016 remains unknown to the public.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |title=Will your vote count? Veil of secrecy makes it impossible for Florida voters to know |first=Jeffrey |last=Schweers |date=2020-02-25 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204743/https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] members of Congress cited the lack of effort to secure U.S. elections against foreign interference, particularly from Russia, as among grounds to begin an [[impeachment]] inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |title=Dem lawmaker to her party: 'Take action' on impeachment by September or 'shut it down' |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |work=[[CNN]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727145555/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |title=Rep. Clark Backs Impeachment Probe, Putting Pressure On Pelosi |work=[[WBUR]] |last1=Swasey |first1=Benjamin |last2=Atkins |first2=Kimberley |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727170338/https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |title=All Washington House Democrats now favor Trump impeachment inquiry |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729131505/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article233239221.html |title=U.S. Reps Heck, Kilmer, Schreir, and Del Bene announce support of impeachment inquiry |work=[[The Olympian]] |last=Boone |first=Rolf |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, the United States issued economic sanctions against seven Russians affiliated with the [[Internet Research Agency]], an organization that manipulates social media for misinformation purposes. The sanctions were described as a warning against foreign interference in United States elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |title=With Sanctions on Russians, U.S. Warns Against Foreign Election Meddling |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 30, 2019 |last=Jakes |first=Lara |access-date=October 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001022221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2019, FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray]] told ABC News: \"as far as the [2020] election itself goes, we think Russia represents the most significant threat.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|title=FBI Director Chris Wray reacts to DOJ watchdog report on Russia investigation: Exclusive|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219051108/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[William Evanina]], director of the [[National Counterintelligence and Security Center]], Russia is \"using social media and many other tools to inflame social divisions, promote conspiracy theories and sow distrust in our democracy and elections.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |title=U.S. Probes If Russia Is Targeting Biden in 2020 Election Meddling |first=Chris |last=Strohm |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110210442/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |archive-date=January 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Bloomberg News'' reported in January 2020 that American intelligence and law enforcement were examining whether Russia was involved in promoting disinformation to undermine Joe Biden as part of a campaign to disrupt the 2020 election.<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\"/> The following month, the [[Estonian Foreign Intelligence Service]] warned that Russia would attempt to interfere in the [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[Elections in Georgia (country)|parliamentary elections]] in October 2020 as well as the US election in November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |title=Russia will try to meddle in 2020 U.S. election, intelligence report says |work=[[NBC News]] |date=February 12, 2020 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |last=Kube |first=Courtney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration reaction ===\n\nThe Trump administration reacted to the briefing by American intelligence officials to the House Intelligence Committee that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>  by rejecting the efforts were in favor of Trump<ref name=\"Diamond_Tapper_Cohen_2/23/2020\">{{cite web | last=Diamond | first=Jeremy | last2=Tapper | first2=Jake | last3=Cohen | first3=Zachary | title=US intelligence briefer appears to have overstated assessment of 2020 Russian interference | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 23, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226015505/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by firing Joseph Maguire, who was involved in those reports.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Trump and his national security adviser [[Robert C. O'Brien (attorney)|Robert O'Brien]]<ref name=\"Sanger_2/24/2020\">{{cite web | last=Sanger | first=David E. | title=Dueling Narratives Emerge From Muddied Account of Russia's 2020 Interference | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 24, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225231616/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> accepted reports the Russians were supporting the nomination of Bernie Sanders.<ref name=\"Pengelly_2/22/2020\">{{cite web | last=Pengelly | first=Martin | title=Donald Trump pounces on reports Russia is seeking to help Bernie Sanders | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=February 22, 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225170801/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after Trump loyalist [[Richard Grenell]] was appointed acting [[Director of National Intelligence]], intelligence officials briefed members of Congress behind closed doors that they had \"not concluded that the Kremlin is directly aiding any candidate\u2019s re-election or any other candidates\u2019 election,\" which differed from testimony they had provided the previous month indicating that Russia was working to aid Trump's candidacy. Two intelligence officials pushed back on suggestions the new testimony was politically motivated. One intelligence official asserted the earlier testimony had overreached and that Democrats had mischaracterized it. [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal#Kashyap Patel|Kash Patel]], a former aide to congressman [[Devin Nunes]] who joined Grenell at the ODNI, imposed limits on what intelligence officials could tell Congress about foreign influence operations. The briefers reportedly did not intend to contradict their previous testimony, though they avoided repeating it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311165910/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221010559/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency of Donald Trump==\n\nIn a June 2019 interview with [[George Stephanopoulos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] said that he would accept information from other nations about his opponents in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Baker (journalist) |title=Trump Says 'I'd Take It' if Russia Again Offered Dirt on Opponent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |work=The New York Times |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |title=Transcript: ABC News' George Stephanopoulos' exclusive interview with President Trump |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=June 16, 2019 |website=ABC News |access-date=31 July 2019 |quote=[[George Stephanopoulos|STEPHANOPOULOS]]: Your campaign this time around, if foreigners, if Russia, if China, if someone else offers you information on opponents, should they accept it or should they call the FBI?  TRUMP: I think maybe you do both. I think you might want to listen, I don't, there's nothing wrong with listening. If somebody called from a country, Norway, \"We have information on your opponent.\" Oh, I think I'd want to hear it.  STEPHANOPOULOS: You want that kind of interference in our elections?  TRUMP: It's not an interference, they have information. I think I'd take it. If I thought there was something wrong, I'd go maybe to the FBI. If I thought there was something wrong. But when somebody comes up with oppo research, right, that they come up with oppo research. Oh, let's call the FBI. The FBI doesn't have enough agents to take care of it, but you go and talk honestly to congressmen, they all do it, they always have. And that's the way it is. It's called oppo research.  STEPHANOPOULOS: Surprising. Thank you.  TRUMP: Thank you. Okay. Fine. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801032648/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to reporting by ''The Wall Street Journal'', ''The Washington Post'' and ''The New York Times'', Trump and his personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] repeatedly pressed the [[Government of Ukraine|Ukrainian government]] to investigate [[Hunter Biden]], the son of [[Joe Biden]], leading to the {{As of|2020|1|9|df=US|alt=ongoing}} [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive &#124; Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|title=Trump pressed Ukrainian leader to investigate Biden's son, according to people familiar with the matter|website=Washington Post|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922233816/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|archive-date=September 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|title=Trump Pressed Ukraine's Leader on Inquiry Into Biden's Son|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael S.|last2=Schmidt|first3=Kenneth P.|last3=Vogel|first4=Adam|last4=Goldman|first5=Maggie|last5=Haberman|date=September 20, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923114022/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Biden is a potentially strong Trump challenger in the 2020 presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|last=Volz|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine Pressured on U.S. Political Investigations|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=September 20, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920171010/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The purpose of the requested investigation was alleged to be to damage [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's election campaign]] for president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|title=WSJ: Trump urged Ukrainian president \"about 8 times\" to investigate Biden's son|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210637/https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|title=Is Trump Trying to Get Ukraine to Take Out Biden for Him?|last=Mackinnon|first=Amy|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210034/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggested that Trump threatened to withhold [[military aid]] from [[Ukraine]] unless they investigate Biden.<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|title=Did Trump Try to Extort the President of Ukraine Into Investigating Joe Biden?|last=Cassidy|first=John|date=September 20, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920205009/https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The controversy triggered the commencement of the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|formal process of impeachment inquiries against Trump]] on September 24, with House speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] directing six House committee chairmen to proceed \"under that umbrella of impeachment inquiry\".<ref name = formal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |title=House Speaker Nancy Pelosi announces formal impeachment inquiry of Trump, says his actions were a 'betrayal of national security' |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201421/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |archive-date=September 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2019, Trump said that \"[[China]] should start an investigation\" into [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|presidential candidate]] Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Moments before, while discussing negotiations on a possible agreement in the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]], he said that \"if they [China] don't do what we want, we have tremendous power.\" Chair of the [[Federal Election Commission]] [[Ellen Weintraub]] then retweeted a June statement explaining that \"it is illegal for any person to solicit, accept, or receive anything of value from a foreign national in connection with a U.S. election\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|publisher=NBC News|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003160859/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|10|alt=As of early October 2019}}, there is evidence President Trump, Vice President [[Mike Pence]], U.S. Attorney General [[William Barr]], as well as Trump's personal attorney Giuliani have solicited help from Ukraine, Australia, Italy, the United Kingdom, and China for assistance in discrediting Trump's political opponents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|title=Trump ordered removal of ambassador over Biden probe; president calls for China to investigate Bidens|first1=Colby|last1=Itkowitz|first2=John|last2=Wagner|first3=Felicia|last3=Sonmez|date=October 4, 2019|via=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004204355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|title=Trump Publicly Urges China to Investigate the Bidens|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Eileen|last2=Sullivan|date=October 3, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004231604/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|title=Trump Administration Used Potential Meeting to Pressure Ukraine on Biden, Texts Indicate|first=Rebecca Ballhaus, Siobhan Hughes and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004172356/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|title=Trump now says both China and Ukraine should investigate Bidens|author=Kevin Liptak|website=CNN|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193006/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|title=Not just Ukraine: Trump now calls for China to probe Bidens|date=October 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175445/https://www.apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|title=Trump says China should investigate Bidens|website=Axios|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004081222/https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|website=NBC News|access-date=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205659/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|title=Trump says China should investigate the Bidens, doubles down on Ukraine probe|first=Kevin|last=Breuninger|date=October 3, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193118/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|first1=Julian|last1=Borger|first2=Lauren|last2=Gambino|date=October 3, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027153313/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=October 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Second American Civil War#Culture war as Second American Civil War|Cold Civil war]]\n*[[Cold War II]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare and Iran]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare by Russia]]\n*[[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks]]\n*[[Foreign electoral intervention]]\n*[[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n*[[Russian espionage in the United States]]\n*[[Russian interference in the 2018 United States elections]]\n*[[Social media in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n*[[Social media in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n*2016 interference timeline\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n**[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[1996 United States campaign finance controversy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]-->\n[[Category:2020 elections in the United States]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign electoral intervention]]\n[[Category:Internet manipulation and propaganda]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:Information operations and warfare]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernment reaction:fix wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_interference_in_the_2020_United_States_elections"}
{"title_page": "Pichia pastoris", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox \n| name = ''Pichia pastoris''\n| regnum = [[fungus|Fungi]]\n| phylum = [[Ascomycota]]\n| classis = [[Saccharomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Saccharomycetales]]\n| familia = [[Saccharomycetaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Pichia]]'' / ''[[Komagataella]]''\n| species = '''''pastoris'''''\n| binomial = ''Pichia pastoris''\n}}\n\n'''''Pichia pastoris''''' is a species of [[methylotroph]]ic [[yeast]]. It was found in 1960s, with its feature of using [[methanol]], as source of carbon and energy.<ref name=\"Koichi Ogata, Hideo Nishikawa & Masahiro Ohsugi (1969)\">{{Cite journal | author=Koichi Ogata, Hideo Nishikawa & Masahiro Ohsugi | title=A Yeast Capable of Utilizing Methanol | journal=[[Agricultural and Biological Chemistry]]  | year=1969 | pages=1519\u20131520 | doi=10.1080/00021369.1969.10859497 }}</ref> After years of study, ''P.Pichia'' was widely used in [[biochemistry|Biochemical]] researches and [[biotechnology|Biotech industries]]. With strong ablities of being [[Gene expression|expression system]] for [[protein production]], as well as being [[model organism]] for genetic study,  ''P. pastoris'' became important for biological research and biotech applications. In last decade, some reports reassigned ''P. pastoris'' to the genus [[Komagataella]] with [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic analysis]], by  [[DNA sequencing|genome sequencing]] of ''P. pastoris''. The species was split into '''''K. phaffii''''', '''''K. pastoris''''', and '''''K. pseudopastoris'''''.<ref name=\"De Schutter, K., Lin, Y., Tiels, P. (2009)\">{{Cite journal | author=De Schutter, K., Lin, Y., Tiels, P. | title=Genome sequence of the recombinant protein production host Pichia pastoris. | journal=[[Nature Biotechnology]]  | year=2009 | pages=561\u2013566 | doi=10.1038/nbt.1544 }}</ref>\n\n==''P. pastoris'' in nature==\n===Natural habitat===\nNaturally, ''P. pastoris'' live on trees\uff0csuch as [[Chestnut | chestnut trees]]. They are heterotrophs and they can use several carbon sources for living, like [[glucose]], [[glycerol]] and [[methanol]].<ref name=\"Rebnegger, C., Vos, T., Graf, A. B., Valli, M., Pronk, J. T., Daran-Lapujade, P., & Mattanovich, D. (2016)\">{{Cite journal | author=Rebnegger, C., Vos, T., Graf, A. B., Valli, M., Pronk, J. T., Daran-Lapujade, P., & Mattanovich, D. | title=Pichia pastoris exhibits high viability and a low maintenance energy requirement at near-zero specific growth rates | journal=[[Applied and Environmental Microbiology]] | year=2016 | pages=4570\u20134583 | doi=10.1128/AEM.00638-16 }}</ref>  However, [[lactose]] cannot be used by them.\n\n===Reproduction===\n''P. pastoris'' can undergo both [[Asexual reproduction|asexual]] reproduction and [[Sexual reproduction|sexual]] reproduction, by [[budding]] and [[ascospore]].<ref name=\"Kurtzman. (1998)\">{{Cite journal | author=Kurtzman | title=42 - Pichia E.C. Hansen emend. Kurtzman | journal=[[The Yeasts]] | volume=1 | year=1998 | pages=273\u2013352 | doi=10.1016/B978-044481312-1/50046-0  }}</ref> In this case, two types of cells of ''P. pastoris''exist: [[Ploidy|haploid and diploid]] cells. In asexual [[Biological life cycle|life cycle]], haploid cells undergo mitosis for reproduction. In sexual life cycle,diploid cells undergo [[spore|sporulation]] and [[meiosis]].<ref name=\"Z\u00f6rg\u00f6 E, Chwialkowska K, Gjuvsland AB, Garr\u00e9 E, Sunnerhagen P, Liti G, Blomberg A, Omholt SW, Warringer J (2013)\">{{Cite journal | author=Z\u00f6rg\u00f6 E, Chwialkowska K, Gjuvsland AB, Garr\u00e9 E, Sunnerhagen P, Liti G, Blomberg A, Omholt SW, Warringer J | title=Ancient Evolutionary Trade-Offs between Yeast Ploidy States | journal=[[PLOS GENETICS]]  | year=2013 | doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1003388 }}</ref>  The growth rate of  its colonies can vary in a large range, from being near to 0 to a doubling time of one hour, which is suitable for industrial processes.<ref name=\"Kastilan, R., Boes, A., Spiegel, H.(2017)\">{{Cite journal | author=Kastilan, R., Boes, A., Spiegel, H. | title=Improvement of a fermentation process for the production of two PfAMA1-DiCo-based malaria vaccine candidates in Pichia pastoris | journal=[[Nature]] | volume=1 | year=2017 | pages=7 | doi=10.1038/s41598-017-11819-4 }}</ref>\n\n==''P. pastoris'' as a model organism==\nIn last few years, ''P. pastoris'' was inveistigated and identified as a good model organism with several advantages. For now it becomes much more widely used in labs.\nFirst of all, ''P. patoris'' can be raised and used easily in lab. Like other widely used yeast models, it has relatively short life span and fast regeneration time. Moreover, some inexpensive cultures had been designed, so that ''p. patoris can grow fast on them, with high cell density.<ref name=\"M. M. Guarna  G. J. Lesnicki  B. M. Tam  J. Robinson  C. Z. Radziminski  D. Hasenwinkle  A. Boraston E. Jervis  R. T. A. MacGillivray  R. F. B. Turner  D. G. Kilburn(1997)\">{{Cite journal | author=M. M. Guarna  G. J. Lesnicki  B. M. Tam  J. Robinson  C. Z. Radziminski  D. Hasenwinkle  A. Boraston E. Jervis  R. T. A. MacGillivray  R. F. B. Turner  D. G. Kilburn | title=On\u2010line monitoring and control of methanol concentration in shake\u2010flask cultures of Pichia pastoris | journal=[[BIOTECHNOLOGY and BIOENGINEERING]] | volume=56 | year=1997 | pages=279\u2013286 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-0290(19971105)56:3<279::AID-BIT5>3.0.CO;2-G}}</ref>\n\nThe whole genome sequencing for ''P. patoris'' had been done.The ''P. pastoris'' GS115 genome has been sequenced by the Flanders Institute for Biotechnology and Ghent University, and published in ''Nature Biotechnology''.<ref name = \"De Schutter\">{{cite journal | vauthors = De Schutter K, Lin YC, Tiels P, Van Hecke A, Glinka S, Weber-Lehmann J, Rouz\u00e9 P, Van de Peer Y, Callewaert N | title = Genome sequence of the recombinant protein production host Pichia pastoris | journal = Nature Biotechnology | volume = 27 | issue = 6 | pages = 561\u20136 | date = June 2009 | pmid = 19465926 | doi = 10.1038/nbt.1544 }}</ref> The genome sequence and gene annotation can be browsed through the [http://bioinformatics.psb.ugent.be/orcae/overview/Picpa ORCAE] system. The complete genomic data allows scientists to identify homologous proteins and evolutionary relationships between other yeast species and ''P. pastoris''. Furthurmore, ''P. pastoris'' has single [[eukaryotic]] cells, which means researchers could investigate the proteins inside ''P. pastoris'', which are homologous to other more complecated eukaryotic species, to obtain their functions and origins.<ref name=\"Brigitte Gasser, Roland Prielhofer, Hans Marx, Michael Maurer, Justyna Nocon, Matthias Steiger, Verena Puxbaum, Michael Sauer & Diethard Mattanovich(2013)\">{{Cite journal | author=Brigitte Gasser, Roland Prielhofer, Hans Marx, Michael Maurer, Justyna Nocon, Matthias Steiger, Verena Puxbaum, Michael Sauer & Diethard Mattanovich | title=Pichia pastoris: protein production host and model organism for biomedical research | journal=[[Future Microbiology]] | volume=8 | year=2013 | pages=191\u2013208 | doi=10.2217/fmb.12.133 }}</ref>\n\nAnother advantage of ''P. pastoris'' is its similarity to the well-studied yeast model--[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]. As a [[model organism]] for biology, ''S. cerevisiae'' have been used by researchers for various purposes throughout history, ''S. cerevisiae'' is well studied, to say the least. The two yeast genus; ''[[Pichia]]'' and ''[[Saccharomyces]]'', have similar growth conditions and tolerances; thus, the culture of ''P. pastoris'' can be adopted by labs without many modifications.<ref name=\"Tran, A., Nguyen, T., Nguyen, C.(2017)\">{{Cite journal | author=Tran, A., Nguyen, T., Nguyen, C. | title=Pichia pastoris versus Saccharomyces cerevisiae: a case study on the recombinant production of human granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor | journal=[[BMC Res Notes]] | volume=10 | year=2017  |doi=10.1186/s13104-017-2471-6}}</ref> Moreover, unlike ''S. cerevisiae'', ''P. pastoris'' has ability to functionally process proteins with large molecular weight, which can is useful for translational host.<ref name=\"Heidebrecht, Aniela, and Thomas Scheibel(2013)\">{{Cite journal | author=Heidebrecht, Aniela, and Thomas Scheibel | title=Recombinant production of spider silk proteins | journal=[[Advances in applied microbiology]] | volume=82 | year=2013 |pages=115\u2013153  |doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-407679-2.00004-1}}</ref>\nConsidering all the advantages, ''P. pastoris'' can be used as both genetic and experimental model organisms.\n\n==''P. pastoris'' as an expression system==\n''P. pastoris'' is frequently used as an [[gene expression#Expression system|expression system]] for the production of proteins. Several properties make ''P. pastoris'' suited for this task: ''P. pastoris'' has a high growth rate and is able to grow on a simple, inexpensive medium. ''P. pastoris'' can grow in either shake flasks or a [[fermenter]], which makes it suitable for both small- and large-scale production.\n\n''P. pastoris'' has two [[alcohol oxidase]] genes, ''Aox1'' and ''Aox2'', which have a strongly [[regulation of gene expression|inducible]] [[promoter (biology)|promoter]].<ref name=\"pmid15565717\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Daly R, Hearn MT | title = Expression of heterologous proteins in Pichia pastoris: a useful experimental tool in protein engineering and production | journal = Journal of Molecular Recognition | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 119\u201338 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15565717 | doi = 10.1002/jmr.687 }}</ref> These genes allow ''Pichia'' to use methanol as a [[carbon]] and energy source. The AOX promoters are induced by [[methanol]] and are repressed by e.g. [[glucose]]. Usually, the gene for the desired protein is introduced under the control of the ''Aox1'' promoter, which means that protein production can be induced by the addition of methanol. In a popular expression vector, the desired protein is produced as a fusion product to the [[secretion]] signal of the \u03b1-mating factor from ''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]'' (baker's yeast). This causes the protein to be secreted into the growth medium, which greatly facilitates subsequent [[protein purification]]. Some commercially available [[plasmid]]s have these features incorporated (such as the pPICZ\u03b1 vector).<ref name=\"Invitrogen-pICZ\">{{cite web |url=http://products.invitrogen.com/ivgn/product/V19520 |title=Description of pPICZ\u03b1 vector by its vendor Invitrogen |date= |format= |website= |publisher= |pages= |language= |archive-url= |archive-date= |quote= |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Biotherapeutic production==\n''Pichia pastoris'' was used for the production of over 500 [[biotherapeutic]]s like [[interferon gamma]]. However, one drawback of this protein expression system is the over-[[glycosylation]] with high [[mannose]] structure which is a potential cause of [[immunogenicity]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Razaghi A, Tan E, Lua LH, Owens L, Karthikeyan OP, Heimann K | title = Is Pichia pastoris a realistic platform for industrial production of recombinant human interferon gamma? | journal = Biologicals | volume = 45 | pages = 52\u201360 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27810255 | doi = 10.1016/j.biologicals.2016.09.015 | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1312349 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.degruyter.com/view/j/afpuc.2015.62.issue-2/afpuc-2015-0031/afpuc-2015-0031.xml?format=INT | title=Increased expression and secretion of recombinant hIFN\u03b3 through amino acid starvation-induced selective pressure on the adjacent HIS4 gene in Pichia pastoris | author=Ali Razaghi|author2=Roger Huerlimann|author3=Leigh Owens|author4=Kirsten Heimann | journal=European Pharmaceutical Journal | year=2015 | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=43\u201350 | doi=10.1515/afpuc-2015-0031}}</ref> In 2006, a research group managed to create a strain YSH597 that produces [[erythropoietin]] in its normal glycosylation form. This was achieved by exchanging the enzymes responsible for the fungal type glycosylation, with the mammalian homologs. Thus, the altered glycosylation pattern allowed the protein to be fully functional.<ref name=\"pmid16960007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hamilton SR, Davidson RC, Sethuraman N, Nett JH, Jiang Y, Rios S, Bobrowicz P, Stadheim TA, Li H, Choi BK, Hopkins D, Wischnewski H, Roser J, Mitchell T, Strawbridge RR, Hoopes J, Wildt S, Gerngross TU | title = Humanization of yeast to produce complex terminally sialylated glycoproteins | journal = Science | volume = 313 | issue = 5792 | pages = 1441\u20133 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 16960007 | doi = 10.1126/science.1130256 | bibcode = 2006Sci...313.1441H }}</ref>\n\nAs some proteins require [[chaperonin]]s for proper folding, ''Pichia'' is unable to produce a number of proteins for which the host lacks the appropriate chaperones. Introducing mammalian chaperonins into the yeast genome or overexpressing existing chaperonins improves production of these proteins and most secreted proteins in general.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bankefa |first1=OE |last2=Wang |first2=M |last3=Zhu |first3=T |last4=Li |first4=Y |title=Hac1p homologues from higher eukaryotes can improve the secretion of heterologous proteins in the yeast Pichia pastoris. |journal=Biotechnology Letters |date=July 2018 |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=1149\u20131156 |doi=10.1007/s10529-018-2571-y |pmid=29785668}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yu |first1=Xiao-Wei |last2=Sun |first2=Wei-Hong |last3=Wang |first3=Ying-Zheng |last4=Xu |first4=Yan |title=Identification of novel factors enhancing recombinant protein production in multi-copy Komagataella phaffii based on transcriptomic analysis of overexpression effects |journal=Scientific Reports |date=24 November 2017 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=16249 |doi=10.1038/s41598-017-16577-x |pmid=29176680 |pmc=5701153 |doi-access=free|bibcode=2017NatSR...716249Y }}</ref>\n\n==Comparison to other expression systems==\n\nIn standard [[molecular biology]] research, the bacterium ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' is the most frequently used organism for production of [[recombinant DNA]] and [[proteins]], due to ''E. coli's'' fast growth rate, good protein production rate, and undemanding growth conditions. Protein production in ''E. coli'' is usually faster than in ''P. pastoris'' for several reasons: [[competent cell|Competent]] ''E. coli'' cells can be stored frozen, and thawed immediately before use, whereas ''Pichia'' cells have to be produced immediately before use.Expression yields in Pichia vary between different [[Cloning|clones]], usually a large number of clones have to be screened for protein production before a good producer is found. Optimal induction times of ''Pichia'' are usually on the order of days, whereas ''E. coli'' usually reaches optimal yields within hours of induction. The major advantage of ''Pichia'' over ''E. coli'' is that ''Pichia'' is capable of producing [[disulfide]] bonds and [[glycosylation]]s in proteins.<ref name=\"pmid19892173\">{{Cite book |vauthors=Cregg JM, Tolstorukov I, Kusari A, Sunga J, Madden K, Chappell T |title=Expression in the yeast Pichia pastoris |journal=Meth. Enzymol. |volume=463 |issue= |pages=169\u201389 |year=2009 |pmid=19892173 |doi=10.1016/S0076-6879(09)63013-5 |url= |series=Methods in Enzymology |isbn=978-0-12-374536-1}}</ref> This means that in cases where disulfides are necessary, ''E. coli'' might produce a misfolded protein, that is usually inactive or insoluble.<ref name=\"pmid19892171\">{{Cite book |author=Brondyk WH |title=Selecting an appropriate method for expressing a recombinant protein |journal=Meth. Enzymol. |volume=463 |issue= |pages=131\u201347 |year=2009 |pmid=19892171 |doi=10.1016/S0076-6879(09)63011-1 |url= |series=Methods in Enzymology |isbn=978-0-12-374536-1}}</ref>\n\nThe well-studied ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' is also used as an expression system with similar advantages over ''E. coli'' as ''Pichia''. However ''Pichia'' has two main advantages over ''S. cerevisiae'' in laboratory and industrial settings:\n\n#''Pichia'', as mentioned above, is a [[methylotroph]], meaning it can grow with the simple [[alcohol]] methanol as its only source of energy \u2014 ''Pichia'' can easily be grown in [[cell suspension]] in reasonably strong methanol solutions that would kill most other micro-organisms, a system that is cheap to set up and maintain.\n#''Pichia'' can grow to very high cell densities, and under ideal conditions can multiply to the point where the cell suspension is practically a paste. As the protein yield from expression in a microbe is roughly equal to the product of the protein produced per cell and the number of cells, this makes ''Pichia'' of great use when trying to produce large quantities of protein without expensive equipment.<ref name=\"pmid19892173\"/>\n\nCompared to other expression systems such as S2-cells from ''[[Drosophila melanogaster]]'' or [[Chinese hamster ovary cell]]s, ''Pichia'' usually gives much better yields. Cell lines from multicellular organisms usually require complex rich media, including [[amino acids]], [[vitamin]]s, and [[growth factor]]s. These media significantly increase the cost of producing recombinant proteins. Additionally, since ''Pichia'' can grow in media containing only one carbon source and one [[nitrogen]] source, it is suitable for isotopic labelling applications in e.g. [[protein NMR]].<ref name=\"pmid19892173\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q148697}}\n\n[[Category:Saccharomycetaceae]]\n[[Category:Fungal models]]\n[[Category:Yeasts]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1956]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Taxobox \n| name = ''Pichia pastoris''\n| regnum = [[fungus|Fungi]]\n| phylum = [[Ascomycota]]\n| classis = [[Saccharomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Saccharomycetales]]\n| familia = [[Saccharomycetaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Pichia]]'' / ''[[Komagataella]]''\n| species = '''''pastoris'''''\n| binomial = ''Pichia pastoris''\n}}\n\n'''''Pichia pastoris''''' is a species of [[methylotroph]]ic [[yeast]]. It was found in 1960s, with its feature of using [[methanol]], as source of carbon and energy.<ref name=\"Koichi Ogata, Hideo Nishikawa & Masahiro Ohsugi (1969)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Koichi Ogata, Hideo Nishikawa & Masahiro Ohsugi | title=A Yeast Capable of Utilizing Methanol | journal=[[Agricultural and Biological Chemistry]]  | year=1969 | pages=1519-1520 | doi=10.1080/00021369.1969.10859497 }}  </ref> After years of study, ''P.Pichia'' was widely used in [[biochemistry|Biochemical]] researches and [[biotechnology|Biotech industries]]. With strong ablities of being [[Gene expression | expression system]] for [[protein production]], as well as being [[model organism]] for genetic study,  ''P. pastoris'' became important for biological research and biotech applications. In last decade, some reports reassigned ''P. pastoris'' to the genus [[Komagataella]] with [[Phylogenetics | phylogenetic analysis]], by  [[DNA sequencing | genome sequencing]] of ''P. pastoris''. The species was split into '''''K. phaffii''''', '''''K. pastoris''''', and '''''K. pseudopastoris'''''. <ref name=\"De Schutter, K., Lin, Y., Tiels, P. (2009)\">  {{Cite journal | author=De Schutter, K., Lin, Y., Tiels, P. | title=Genome sequence of the recombinant protein production host Pichia pastoris. | journal=[[Nature Biotechnology]]  | year=2009 | pages=561-566 | doi=10.1038/nbt.1544 }}  </ref>\n\n==''P. pastoris'' in nature==\n===Natural habitat===\nNaturally, ''P. pastoris'' live on trees\uff0csuch as [[Chestnut | chestnut trees]]. They are heterotrophs and they can use several carbon sources for living, like [[glucose]], [[glycerol]] and [[methanol]]. <ref name=\"Rebnegger, C., Vos, T., Graf, A. B., Valli, M., Pronk, J. T., Daran-Lapujade, P., & Mattanovich, D. (2016)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Rebnegger, C., Vos, T., Graf, A. B., Valli, M., Pronk, J. T., Daran-Lapujade, P., & Mattanovich, D. | title=Pichia pastoris exhibits high viability and a low maintenance energy requirement at near-zero specific growth rates | journal=[[Applied and Environmental Microbiology]] | year=2016 | pages=4570-4583 | doi=10.1128/AEM.00638-16 }}  </ref>  However, [[lactose]] cannot be used by them.\n===Reproduction===\n''P. pastoris'' can undergo both [[Asexual reproduction | asexual]] reproduction and [[Sexual reproduction | sexual]] reproduction, by [[budding]] and [[ascospore]].<ref name=Kurtzman. (1998)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Kurtzman | title=42 - Pichia E.C. Hansen emend. Kurtzman | journal=[[The Yeasts]] | volume=1 | year=1998 | pages=273-352 | doi=10.1016/B978-044481312-1/50046-0  }}  </ref>In this case, two types of cells of ''P. pastoris''exist: [[Ploidy | haploid and diploid]] cells. In asexual [[Biological life cycle|life cycle]], haploid cells undergo mitosis for reproduction. In sexual life cycle,diploid cells undergo [[spore | sporulation]] and [[meiosis]].<ref name=\"Z\u00f6rg\u00f6 E, Chwialkowska K, Gjuvsland AB, Garr\u00e9 E, Sunnerhagen P, Liti G, Blomberg A, Omholt SW, Warringer J (2013)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Z\u00f6rg\u00f6 E, Chwialkowska K, Gjuvsland AB, Garr\u00e9 E, Sunnerhagen P, Liti G, Blomberg A, Omholt SW, Warringer J | title=Ancient Evolutionary Trade-Offs between Yeast Ploidy States | journal=[[PLOS GENETICS]]  | year=2013 | doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1003388 }}  </ref>  The growth rate of  its colonies can vary in a large range, from being near to 0 to a doubling time of one hour, which is suitable for industrial processes.<ref name=\"Kastilan, R., Boes, A., Spiegel, H.(2017)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Kastilan, R., Boes, A., Spiegel, H. | title=Improvement of a fermentation process for the production of two PfAMA1-DiCo-based malaria vaccine candidates in Pichia pastoris | journal=[[Nature]] | volume=1 | year=2017 | pages=7 | doi=10.1038/s41598-017-11819-4 }}  </ref> \n\n\n==''P. pastoris'' as a model organism==\nIn last few years, ''P. pastoris'' was inveistigated and identified as a good model organism with several advantages. For now it becomes much more widely used in labs.\nFirst of all, ''P. patoris'' can be raised and used easily in lab. Like other widely used yeast models, it has relatively short life span and fast regeneration time. Moreover, some inexpensive cultures had been designed, so that ''p. patoris can grow fast on them, with high cell density. </ref>  <ref name=\"M. M. Guarna  G. J. Lesnicki  B. M. Tam  J. Robinson  C. Z. Radziminski  D. Hasenwinkle  A. Boraston E. Jervis  R. T. A. MacGillivray  R. F. B. Turner  D. G. Kilburn(1997)\">  {{Cite journal | author=M. M. Guarna  G. J. Lesnicki  B. M. Tam  J. Robinson  C. Z. Radziminski  D. Hasenwinkle  A. Boraston E. Jervis  R. T. A. MacGillivray  R. F. B. Turner  D. G. Kilburn | title=On\u2010line monitoring and control of methanol concentration in shake\u2010flask cultures of Pichia pastoris | journal=[[BIOTECHNOLOGY and BIOENGINEERING]] | volume=56 | year=1997 | pages=279-286 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1097-0290(19971105)56:3<279::AID-BIT5>3.0.CO;2-G}}  </ref> \n\nThe whole genome sequencing for ''P. patoris'' had been done.The ''P. pastoris'' GS115 genome has been sequenced by the Flanders Institute for Biotechnology and Ghent University, and published in ''Nature Biotechnology''.<ref name = \"De Schutter\">{{cite journal | vauthors = De Schutter K, Lin YC, Tiels P, Van Hecke A, Glinka S, Weber-Lehmann J, Rouz\u00e9 P, Van de Peer Y, Callewaert N | title = Genome sequence of the recombinant protein production host Pichia pastoris | journal = Nature Biotechnology | volume = 27 | issue = 6 | pages = 561\u20136 | date = June 2009 | pmid = 19465926 | doi = 10.1038/nbt.1544 }}</ref> The genome sequence and gene annotation can be browsed through the [http://bioinformatics.psb.ugent.be/orcae/overview/Picpa ORCAE] system. The complete genomic data allows scientists to identify homologous proteins and evolutionary relationships between other yeast species and ''P. pastoris''. Furthurmore, ''P. pastoris'' has single [[eukaryotic]] cells, which means researchers could investigate the proteins inside ''P. pastoris'', which are homologous to other more complecated eukaryotic species, to obtain their functions and origins.<ref name=\"Brigitte Gasser, Roland Prielhofer, Hans Marx, Michael Maurer, Justyna Nocon, Matthias Steiger, Verena Puxbaum, Michael Sauer & Diethard Mattanovich(2013)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Brigitte Gasser, Roland Prielhofer, Hans Marx, Michael Maurer, Justyna Nocon, Matthias Steiger, Verena Puxbaum, Michael Sauer & Diethard Mattanovich | title=Pichia pastoris: protein production host and model organism for biomedical research | journal=[[Future Microbiology]] | volume=8 | year=2013 | pages=191-208 | doi=10.2217/fmb.12.133 }}  </ref> \n\nAnother advantage of ''P. pastoris'' is its similarity to the well-studied yeast model--[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]. As a [[model organism]] for biology, ''S. cerevisiae'' have been used by researchers for various purposes throughout history, ''S. cerevisiae'' is well studied, to say the least. The two yeast genus; ''[[Pichia]]'' and ''[[Saccharomyces]]'', have similar growth conditions and tolerances; thus, the culture of ''P. pastoris'' can be adopted by labs without many modifications.</ref>  <ref name=\"Tran, A., Nguyen, T., Nguyen, C.(2017)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Tran, A., Nguyen, T., Nguyen, C. | title=Pichia pastoris versus Saccharomyces cerevisiae: a case study on the recombinant production of human granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor | journal=[[BMC Res Notes]] | volume=10 | year=2017  |doi=10.1186/s13104-017-2471-6}}  </ref> Moreover, unlike ''S. cerevisiae'', ''P. pastoris'' has ability to functionally process proteins with large molecular weight, which can is useful for translational host.</ref>  <ref name=\"Heidebrecht, Aniela, and Thomas Scheibel(2013)\">  {{Cite journal | author=Heidebrecht, Aniela, and Thomas Scheibel | title=Recombinant production of spider silk proteins | journal=[[Advances in applied microbiology]] | volume=82 | year=2013 |page=115-153  |doi=10.1016/B978-0-12-407679-2.00004-1}}  </ref>\nConsidering all the advantages, ''P. pastoris'' can be used as both genetic and experimental model organisms.\n\n\n==''P. pastoris'' as an expression system==\n''P. pastoris'' is frequently used as an [[gene expression#Expression system|expression system]] for the production of proteins. Several properties make ''P. pastoris'' suited for this task: ''P. pastoris'' has a high growth rate and is able to grow on a simple, inexpensive medium. ''P. pastoris'' can grow in either shake flasks or a [[fermenter]], which makes it suitable for both small- and large-scale production.\n\n''P. pastoris'' has two [[alcohol oxidase]] genes, ''Aox1'' and ''Aox2'', which have a strongly [[regulation of gene expression|inducible]] [[promoter (biology)|promoter]].<ref name=\"pmid15565717\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Daly R, Hearn MT | title = Expression of heterologous proteins in Pichia pastoris: a useful experimental tool in protein engineering and production | journal = Journal of Molecular Recognition | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 119\u201338 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15565717 | doi = 10.1002/jmr.687 }}</ref> These genes allow ''Pichia'' to use methanol as a [[carbon]] and energy source. The AOX promoters are induced by [[methanol]] and are repressed by e.g. [[glucose]]. Usually, the gene for the desired protein is introduced under the control of the ''Aox1'' promoter, which means that protein production can be induced by the addition of methanol. In a popular expression vector, the desired protein is produced as a fusion product to the [[secretion]] signal of the \u03b1-mating factor from ''[[Saccharomyces cerevisiae]]'' (baker's yeast). This causes the protein to be secreted into the growth medium, which greatly facilitates subsequent [[protein purification]]. Some commercially available [[plasmid]]s have these features incorporated (such as the pPICZ\u03b1 vector).<ref name=\"Invitrogen-pICZ\">{{cite web |url=http://products.invitrogen.com/ivgn/product/V19520 |title=Description of pPICZ\u03b1 vector by its vendor Invitrogen |date= |format= |website= |publisher= |pages= |language= |archive-url= |archive-date= |quote= |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Biotherapeutic production==\n''Pichia pastoris'' was used for the production of over 500 [[biotherapeutic]]s like [[interferon gamma]]. However, one drawback of this protein expression system is the over-[[glycosylation]] with high [[mannose]] structure which is a potential cause of [[immunogenicity]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Razaghi A, Tan E, Lua LH, Owens L, Karthikeyan OP, Heimann K | title = Is Pichia pastoris a realistic platform for industrial production of recombinant human interferon gamma? | journal = Biologicals | volume = 45 | pages = 52\u201360 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 27810255 | doi = 10.1016/j.biologicals.2016.09.015 | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1312349 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.degruyter.com/view/j/afpuc.2015.62.issue-2/afpuc-2015-0031/afpuc-2015-0031.xml?format=INT | title=Increased expression and secretion of recombinant hIFN\u03b3 through amino acid starvation-induced selective pressure on the adjacent HIS4 gene in Pichia pastoris | author=Ali Razaghi|author2=Roger Huerlimann|author3=Leigh Owens|author4=Kirsten Heimann | journal=European Pharmaceutical Journal | year=2015 | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=43\u201350 | doi=10.1515/afpuc-2015-0031}}</ref> In 2006, a research group managed to create a strain YSH597 that produces [[erythropoietin]] in its normal glycosylation form. This was achieved by exchanging the enzymes responsible for the fungal type glycosylation, with the mammalian homologs. Thus, the altered glycosylation pattern allowed the protein to be fully functional.<ref name=\"pmid16960007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hamilton SR, Davidson RC, Sethuraman N, Nett JH, Jiang Y, Rios S, Bobrowicz P, Stadheim TA, Li H, Choi BK, Hopkins D, Wischnewski H, Roser J, Mitchell T, Strawbridge RR, Hoopes J, Wildt S, Gerngross TU | title = Humanization of yeast to produce complex terminally sialylated glycoproteins | journal = Science | volume = 313 | issue = 5792 | pages = 1441\u20133 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 16960007 | doi = 10.1126/science.1130256 | bibcode = 2006Sci...313.1441H }}</ref>\n\nAs some proteins require [[chaperonin]]s for proper folding, ''Pichia'' is unable to produce a number of proteins for which the host lacks the appropriate chaperones. Introducing mammalian chaperonins into the yeast genome or overexpressing existing chaperonins improves production of these proteins and most secreted proteins in general.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bankefa |first1=OE |last2=Wang |first2=M |last3=Zhu |first3=T |last4=Li |first4=Y |title=Hac1p homologues from higher eukaryotes can improve the secretion of heterologous proteins in the yeast Pichia pastoris. |journal=Biotechnology Letters |date=July 2018 |volume=40 |issue=7 |pages=1149\u20131156 |doi=10.1007/s10529-018-2571-y |pmid=29785668}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yu |first1=Xiao-Wei |last2=Sun |first2=Wei-Hong |last3=Wang |first3=Ying-Zheng |last4=Xu |first4=Yan |title=Identification of novel factors enhancing recombinant protein production in multi-copy Komagataella phaffii based on transcriptomic analysis of overexpression effects |journal=Scientific Reports |date=24 November 2017 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=16249 |doi=10.1038/s41598-017-16577-x |pmid=29176680 |pmc=5701153 |doi-access=free|bibcode=2017NatSR...716249Y }}</ref>\n\n==Comparison to other expression systems==\n\nIn standard [[molecular biology]] research, the bacterium ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' is the most frequently used organism for production of [[recombinant DNA]] and [[proteins]], due to ''E. coli's'' fast growth rate, good protein production rate, and undemanding growth conditions. Protein production in ''E. coli'' is usually faster than in ''P. pastoris'' for several reasons: [[competent cell|Competent]] ''E. coli'' cells can be stored frozen, and thawed immediately before use, whereas ''Pichia'' cells have to be produced immediately before use.Expression yields in Pichia vary between different [[Cloning|clones]], usually a large number of clones have to be screened for protein production before a good producer is found. Optimal induction times of ''Pichia'' are usually on the order of days, whereas ''E. coli'' usually reaches optimal yields within hours of induction. The major advantage of ''Pichia'' over ''E. coli'' is that ''Pichia'' is capable of producing [[disulfide]] bonds and [[glycosylation]]s in proteins.<ref name=\"pmid19892173\">{{Cite book |vauthors=Cregg JM, Tolstorukov I, Kusari A, Sunga J, Madden K, Chappell T |title=Expression in the yeast Pichia pastoris |journal=Meth. Enzymol. |volume=463 |issue= |pages=169\u201389 |year=2009 |pmid=19892173 |doi=10.1016/S0076-6879(09)63013-5 |url= |series=Methods in Enzymology |isbn=978-0-12-374536-1}}</ref> This means that in cases where disulfides are necessary, ''E. coli'' might produce a misfolded protein, that is usually inactive or insoluble.<ref name=\"pmid19892171\">{{Cite book |author=Brondyk WH |title=Selecting an appropriate method for expressing a recombinant protein |journal=Meth. Enzymol. |volume=463 |issue= |pages=131\u201347 |year=2009 |pmid=19892171 |doi=10.1016/S0076-6879(09)63011-1 |url= |series=Methods in Enzymology |isbn=978-0-12-374536-1}}</ref>\n\nThe well-studied ''Saccharomyces cerevisiae'' is also used as an expression system with similar advantages over ''E. coli'' as ''Pichia''. However ''Pichia'' has two main advantages over ''S. cerevisiae'' in laboratory and industrial settings:\n\n#''Pichia'', as mentioned above, is a [[methylotroph]], meaning it can grow with the simple [[alcohol]] methanol as its only source of energy \u2014 ''Pichia'' can easily be grown in [[cell suspension]] in reasonably strong methanol solutions that would kill most other micro-organisms, a system that is cheap to set up and maintain.\n#''Pichia'' can grow to very high cell densities, and under ideal conditions can multiply to the point where the cell suspension is practically a paste. As the protein yield from expression in a microbe is roughly equal to the product of the protein produced per cell and the number of cells, this makes ''Pichia'' of great use when trying to produce large quantities of protein without expensive equipment.<ref name=\"pmid19892173\"/>\n\nCompared to other expression systems such as S2-cells from ''[[Drosophila melanogaster]]'' or [[Chinese hamster ovary cell]]s, ''Pichia'' usually gives much better yields. Cell lines from multicellular organisms usually require complex rich media, including [[amino acids]], [[vitamin]]s, and [[growth factor]]s. These media significantly increase the cost of producing recombinant proteins. Additionally, since ''Pichia'' can grow in media containing only one carbon source and one [[nitrogen]] source, it is suitable for isotopic labelling applications in e.g. [[protein NMR]].<ref name=\"pmid19892173\"/>\n\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q148697}}\n\n[[Category:Saccharomycetaceae]]\n[[Category:Fungal models]]\n[[Category:Yeasts]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1956]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref tags fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pichia_pastoris"}
{"title_page": "Jedwabne pogrom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1941 massacre of Jews in Poland}}\n[[File:Pogrom w Jedwabnem Muzeum Historii \u017byd\u00f3w Polskich.JPG|thumb|upright=1.3|Jedwabne memorial, [[POLIN Museum of the History of Polish Jews]], Warsaw]]\n\nThe '''Jedwabne pogrom''' ({{lang-pl|Pogrom w Jedwabnem}}, {{IPA-pl|j\u025bd\u02c8vabn\u025b|pron}}) was a massacre of [[Polish Jews]] in the town of [[Jedwabne]], [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German-occupied Poland]], on 10 July 1941, during [[World War II]].{{sfn|Cesarani|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=mimNBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA371 371]}}\n\nAt least 340 men, women and children were murdered, some 300 of whom were locked in a barn that was set on fire.<ref>For 300, see {{harvnb|Musial|2003|p=300}}.</ref> About 40 ethnic Poles were implicated in the murders.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=229}} German police were present in the town.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=229}}{{efn|[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]]: \"On July 10, 1941, Polish residents of Jedwabne, a small town located in Bialystok District of first Soviet-occupied and then German-occupied Poland, participated in the murder of hundreds of their Jewish neighbors. Although responsibility for instigating this 'pogrom' has not been fully established, scholars have documented at least a German police presence in the town at the time of the killings.\"<ref>[https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005183 \"Pogroms\"]. ''Holocaust Encyclopedia''. United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n===Jedwabne===\n[[File:Jedwabne Synagogue.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Jedwabne Synagogue]] before 1913]]\nThe Jewish community in [[Jedwabne]] was established in the 17th or 18th century.{{sfn|Baker|Tzinovitz|1980|p=5}} There were approximately 1,500 Jews out of a population of 2,167 in Jedwabne in the 1930s.<ref>[http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/printarticle.aspx?id=466 \"Jedwabne\"]. YIVO Encyclopedia.</ref> It was a typical [[shtetl]], a small town with a majority Jewish community coexistent with its Polish minority and surrounded by majority Polish countryside, one of many such towns in [[Second Polish Republic|prewar Poland]]. The region politically supported the right-wing [[National Democracy|National Democrats]],{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=18}} who sought to counter what they said was Jewish economic competition against Catholic Poles, and opposed the Polish socialist government of [[J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski]] and his successors. Nevertheless, there were good prewar Polish-Jewish relations in the town, possibly better than elsewhere in the country. At their most tense, a 1934 rumor that drew a connection between the killing of a Jewish woman and the killing of a Catholic man was quashed by a priest and a rabbi addressing the matter together, before it escalated.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=19}}\n\nResidents of Jedwabne had memory of the nearby [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom#Background|Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom]] of 1933, organized by [[National Democracy]]'s far-right faction, the [[Camp of Great Poland]] (OWP). The organization referred to the violence as a \"revolution\" against the Polish state, which it saw as a protector of Jews. One Jew was killed by the pogromists and four pogromists were killed by the Polish police; the OWP was then banned by Poland in 1934 for anti-state and racist activities.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|p=9}}\n\nAccording to [[Anna Bikont]], archival documents show Poland's government at this time was hostile to the Polish nationalist movement, because of the latter's attacks on Jews as well as its opposition to the Polish state; the government felt responsible for Jews and tried to protect them (arresting violent nationalists) and it perceived Jews as trying to show loyalty to the Polish state.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|p=31}} \n\n===World War II===\nThe start of [[European Theatre of World War II|World War II in Europe]] began with the [[Invasion of Poland (1939)|invasion of Poland]] by [[Nazi Germany]] on 1 September 1939. Later in the same month, on 17 September, the Soviet [[Red Army]] [[Soviet invasion of Poland (1939)|invaded]] the [[Kresy|eastern regions of Poland]] under the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]].{{sfn|Kitchen|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QAStAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]}} {{efn|\"The generals of the two invading armies went over the details of the prearranged line that would mark the two zones of conquest for Germany and Soviet Russia, subsequently to be rearranged one more time in Moscow. The military parade that followed was recorded by Nazi cameras and celebrated in the German newsreel: German and Soviet generals cheek by jowl in military homage to each other's armies and victories.\"{{sfn|Raack|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pAdZMaWn8cIC&pg=PA58 58]}}}} The area of Jedwabne was originally occupied by the Germans, who crushed local resistance and burned the synagogue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,173800.html|title=Dokumenty, o\u015bwiadczenia, wyst\u0105pienia publiczne dotycz\u0105ce mordu w Jedwabnem|last=|first=|date=8 March 2001|work=Gazeta Wyborcza}}</ref> Jedwabne was then transferred to the Soviets in accordance with the [[German\u2013Soviet Boundary and Friendship Treaty|German\u2013Soviet Boundary Treaty]] of 28 September 1939. At first, many [[Polish Jews]] were relieved to learn that the Soviets, rather than the Nazis, were to occupy their town. Unlike most ethnic Poles, some Jews prominently welcomed the [[Red Army]] as protectors from Nazism, as did other ethnic groups in the ''[[Kresy]]'' (Polish borderlands), particularly [[Belarusians]].{{sfn|Tec|1993}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} In what [[Jan Gross]] has termed \"the institutionalization of resentment\", the occupiers used privileges and punishments to accommodate and encourage ethnic and religious differences among the local population.{{sfn|Holc|2002|p=454}}\n\nAccording to Anna Bikont, the Soviets brought in Russian and atheistic anti-religious policies: Poland's Hebrew schools were shut by the Soviets, who banned holy days that Poland had recognized, such as [[Yom Kippur]], and appropriated shops and businesses, which were mostly Jewish.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|pp=146\u2013148}} Some Jews and Belarusians formed militias (known as ''\"opaskowcy\"'' for their red armbands).{{sfn|Wierzbicki|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_BbvQbiaqAEC&pg=PA151 151]}} Local people said Jews had helped the [[NKVD]] compile lists of Poles to be sent to the \"Soviet interior\".{{sfn|Strzembosz|2002|p=6}} A total of 22,353 Poles (entire families) were deported from the vicinity.{{efn|\"Following his detailed Report of the Jedwabne Investigation, [[Leon Kieres]] responds to questions from the Senate. Statement by Senator Jadwiga Stokarska (translation): 'With the Soviet arrival, Poles were laid off immediately, and all administrative offices, including municipal, were staffed by Jews who were also handed out weapons and formed the local militia. Many joined the [[NKVD]], the [[Komsomol]] and the Bolshevik Party, compiled the list of Poles to be sent to Siberia, and performed their deportations directly.' Original: 'Po wej\u015bciu Rosjan natychmiast z urz\u0119d\u00f3w zwolniono Polak\u00f3w i wszystkie urz\u0119dy, \u0142\u0105cznie z miejskim, obsadzili \u017bydzi. Otrzymali oni od Rosjan bro\u0144 i utworzyli miejscow\u0105 milicj\u0119. Sporo m\u0142odych \u017byd\u00f3w wst\u0105pi\u0142o do NKWD, do Komsomo\u0142u, do partii bolszewickiej. W Jedwabnem \u017bydzi utworzyli list\u0119 Polak\u00f3w do wyw\u00f3zki na Sybir i bezpo\u015brednio j\u0105 nadzorowali.'<ref name=\"Senat_RP\">{{cite web |last=Stokarska |first=Jadwiga |title=90. posiedzenie Senatu RP [90th session of the Senate of the Republic of Poland] |language=pl |url=http://ww2.senat.pl/k4/dok/sten/090/22.HTM |publisher=The Senate of the Republic of Poland |website=ww2.senat.pl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018225107/http://ww2.senat.pl/k4/dok/sten/090/22.HTM |url-status=live |date=23 April 2008 |archive-date=18 October 2014}}</ref>}} Red Army troops requisitioned food and other goods, depriving the local populace of resources.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} The [[NKVD|Soviet secret police]] (NKVD) accompanying the [[Red Army]] routinely arrested and deported Polish citizens, both gentiles and Jews, and spread terror throughout the region.{{sfn|Pinchuk|2003|pp=67\u201368}}\n\nFollowing Germany's [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]] on 22 June 1941, German forces overran the parts of [[Poland]] that had been occupied by the Soviets since 1939. The Nazis distributed antisemitic propaganda, and there were reports that Jews had welcomed the Soviets, which \"strengthened the widely held stereotype of Judaeo-communism which had been promoted by right-wing parties before the war\".{{sfn|Lukowski|Zawadzki|2019|p=334}} In parallel, the [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] organized special ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]'' (\"task forces\") to murder Jews in these areas, and a few massacres were carried out. The guidelines for such massacres were formulated by [[Reinhard Heydrich]],{{sfn|Browning|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=d9Wg4gjtP3cC&pg=PA262 262]}} who ordered his officers to induce anti-Jewish incidents in the territories newly occupied by the German forces, including pogroms. \"Hooliganism set the tone\", according to [[Michael C. Steinlauf]].{{sfn|Steinlauf|1997|p=31}}\n\nThree days into the invasion, six Poles (three ethnic Poles and three Jews) who had collaborators with the Soviets were lynched in Jedwabne. Some accounts say they were first beaten or tortured by the locals, then shot by the Germans. The same day, two wives of Jewish activists for the Soviets who had evacuated with the Red Army committed suicide with their children. Other Jews faced robberies and attacks, which the Germans tolerated. Antisemitic violence broke out in pogroms across the newly German-occupied [[Podlasie]] region.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} In the first days of the occupation of Jedwabne, the Germans set up a Field Gendarmerie (''[[Feldgendarmerie#Operations|Feldgendarmerie]]''), staffed by 8 or 11 military police, according to different testimonies. These established cooperation with a new town council, headed by the brother-in-law of a previous mayor, Marian Karolak. Scholars say it is likely that the Germans consented to the formation of a Polish volunteer [[town guard]]. Some of these may have been resistance fighters during the Soviet occupation who later joined the German auxiliary police, because Polish testimonials refer to them as ''szucman'', from ''[[Schutzmannschaft]]''.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Pogroms===\nPolish villagers participated in massacres of Jews, with varying degrees of German involvement, in 23 localities of the \u0141om\u017ca and Bia\u0142ystok areas of the [[Podlasie]] region after the occupation. Generally smaller massacres took place at [[Bielsk Podlaski]] (the village of Pilki), [[Choroszcz]], [[Czy\u017cew]], [[Goni\u0105dz]], [[Grajewo]], [[Jasion\u00f3wka]], [[Kleszczele]], [[Knyszyn]], [[Kolno]], [[Ku\u017anica, Podlaskie Voivodeship|Ku\u017anica]], [[Narewka]], [[Pi\u0105tnica]], [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w]], [[Rajgr\u00f3d]], [[Soko\u0142y, Wysokie Mazowieckie County|Soko\u0142y]], [[Stawiski]], [[Suchowola]], [[Szczuczyn]], [[Trzcianne]], [[Tykocin]], [[Wasilk\u00f3w]], [[W\u0105sosz]], and [[Wizna]].<ref>[http://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/09/pogrom-in-jedwabne-course-of-events \"Pogrom in Jedwabne: Course of Events]. Polin. Museum of the History of Polish Jews, 9 July 2016; accessed 2 April 2018.</ref> In the days before the Jedwabne massacre, the town's Jewish population increased as refugees arrived from nearby Radzi\u0142\u00f3w and Wizna. In Wizna, the town's Polish \"civil head\" had ordered the Jewish community's expulsion; 230\u2013240 Jews fled to Jedwabne.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=900}} On 7 July 1941, during the [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom]], local Poles are reported to have murdered 800 Jews, 500 of whom were burned in a barn. The murders took place after the Gestapo had arrived in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/09/timeline-of-pogroms-in-the-former-soviet-occupation-zone-summer|title=Timeline of pogroms in the former Soviet occupation zone \u2013 summer of 1941|publisher=POLIN, Museum of the History of Polish Jews}}</ref> When the German occupying forces began establishing their new regime, they gave the Poles of Jedwabne \"a few days to 'self-cleanse' the town of Jews\".{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Jedwabne pogrom==\n===10 July 1941===\n[[File:1941 atrocity in Jedwabne (map).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=diagram|Jedwabne crime scene, compiled from Polish court documents{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}]]\n\nJews were taken to a square in the center of Jedwabne, where they were ordered to weed the area by pulling grass up from between the stones. They were beaten by a group of ethnic Poles.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}} A group of around 40 Jewish men was forced to demolish a statue of [[Vladimir Lenin|Lenin]] that had been put up by the Soviets and carry it out of town on a wooden stretcher while singing Soviet songs. The local [[rabbi]], Awigdor Bia\u0142ostocki, was made to lead the procession, which included the kosher butcher. The group was taken to a barn,<ref name=\"Senat_RP\"/> killed, and buried together with fragments of the statue. There are varying theories about the manner of the killing, and varying witness testimonies as to whether the Germans were present at the barn and whether they took part in escorting the Jews from the square to the barn.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nAfter the men had been killed, most of Jedwabne's remaining Jews, estimated at some 250<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" /> to 300 ([[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]] final findings),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |title=Postanowienie o umorzeniu sledztwa (\"Final findings\") |publisher=Institute of National Remembrance|date=30 June 2001|accessdate=14 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114125013/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |archivedate=14 November 2012 }}</ref> were led to the same barn, locked inside, and burned alive using [[kerosene]] from former Soviet supplies (or, by other accounts, German gasoline). The remains of both groups were buried in two [[mass grave]]s in the barn.<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" /> The victims included women, children, and infants.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\n===Roles===\nThere is general agreement that German secret police officials were seen in Jedwabne on the morning of 10 July 1941 and met with the town authorities. Testimony quoted by Gross (2001) says they were [[Gestapo]] and that there eight of them,{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=18}} while Persak (2011) says they were probably German Security Police or Security Service (''[[Sicherheitspolizei]]'' or ''[[Sicherheitsdienst]]'').{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (IPN) criminal investigation, ''S1/00/Zn'', concluded in 2002 that on the same morning Polish men from nearby villages began arriving in Jedwabne \"with the intention of participating in the premeditated murder of the Jewish inhabitants of the town\". The IPN found that some Jews were alerted by non-Jewish neighbors to what was happening.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nAccording to another account, by historian [[Tomasz Strzembosz]], the men from nearby villages arrived by order of the German-appointed Jedwabne mayor Marian Karolak and the German paramilitaries billeted to the town (''[[Feldgendarmerie#Operations|Feldgendarmerie]]'').{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} a group of Polish men from Jedwabne and neighboring settlements was assembled who, under German supervision, rounded up local Jews and Jews seeking refuge there from nearby towns and villages such as Wizna and [[Kolno]].{{efn|\"A separate problem concerns the townsmen who had been named during the interrogations conducted by the Security Office [''UB''] functionaries. That is because, on this point, the statements were all retracted in court as having been obtained through torture.\" Polish-language original text: \"Osobnym problemem s\u0105 mieszka\u0144cy miasteczka wymieniani podczas zezna\u0144 sk\u0142adanych na r\u0119ce funkcjonariuszy Urz\u0119du Bezpiecze\u0144stwa. A to z tego powodu, \u017ce zeznania te, w\u0142a\u015bnie w tym punkcie, by\u0142y gremialnie odwo\u0142ywane na sali s\u0105dowej jako wymuszone torturami.\"<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\">{{cite news |last=Strzembosz |first=Tomasz |author-link=Tomasz Strzembosz |trans-title=Inny obraz s\u0105siad\u00f3w |title=A different picture of neighbors |url=http://www.rzeczpospolita.pl/gazeta/wydanie_010331/publicystyka/publicystyka_a_2.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010610072611/http://www.rzeczpospolita.pl/gazeta/wydanie_010331/publicystyka/publicystyka_a_2.html |archive-date=10 June 2001 |work =[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]] |date=31 March 2001 |volume=77|access-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Jan Gross]] writes that a leading role in the pogrom was carried out by four men, including Jerzy Lauda\u0144ski and Karol Bardo\u0144, who had earlier collaborated with the Soviet [[NKVD]] and were now trying to recast themselves as zealous collaborators with the Germans.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=75}} He also says: \"At the time, the undisputed bosses over life and death in Jedwabne were the Germans. No sustained organized activity could take place there without their consent. They were the only ones who could decide the fate of the Jews. It was within their power also to stop the murderous pogrom at any time. And they did not choose to intervene. ... But it is also clear that had Jedwabne not been occupied by the Germans, the Jews of Jedwabne would not have been murdered by their neighbors.\"{{sfn|Gross|2001|pp=46\u201347}}\n\nAccording to [[Peter Longerich]], \"closer analysis of the crime\" shows that the pogrom was \"engineered by a unit of the German Security Police\", probably a unit from the [[Zichenau]] [[Gestapo]] office that had been assigned to ''[[Einsatzgruppe B]]'', and which \"had recruited local Poles as auxiliary 'pogrom police'\".{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=196}} Krzysztof Persak writes that the Jedwabne pograom and some 30 others happened at a special time and place: around [[\u0141om\u017ca]] and western [[Bia\u0142ystok]] was one of the few Polish majority areas that had just undergone the cruelty of Soviet occupation since 1939. They therefore saw Germans as liberators when they arrived in 1941; paired with historical antisemitism, the conditions were right for German incitement according to the [[Reich Main Security Office]] directive on \"folk pogroms\" of 29 June.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}<!--primary sources: Several Jewish eyewitnesses reported that the Germans were directly involved in rounding up and abusing Jews in the town square, and that they shot at Jews who tried to escape from the burning barn. According to a diary penned during the war, citing reports by Jews who fled Jedwabne and Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, \"With the help of local farmers, the Germans gathered the Jews of these places, the rabbi and community leaders foremost, in the market square. At first, they beat them cruelly and forced them to wrap themselves in their ''[[tallitot]]'' and to jump and dance, accompanied by singing. All this was done under an unceasing stream of blows from cudgels and rubber whips.  Finally, they pushed all the Jews, beating and kicking them, into a long threshing house and set it on fire with them inside.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHstAQAAIAAJ |title=Deliverance. The diary of Michael Maik: A True Story|last=Maik|first=Michael|last2=Ben-Dov|first2=Avigdor|last3=Ben-Dov|first3=Laia|date=2004|publisher=Avigdor and Laia Ben-Dov|isbn=9789659070107|location=|pages=38\u201339|language=en}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=April 2020}}\n\nAccording to a memorial book first published in Hebrew in 1963, \"The Jews who came from the towns told us terrible things. Rywka Kurc [who had managed to escape from Jedwabne (and is] now in Australia) told us that in Jedwabne, the S.S. enclosed all the Jews in a hayloft\u2014men, women, children and old people, among them her husband and two children. They set fire to the building and everyone was burned alive.\"<ref>Yitzchak Ivri, ed., ''Book of Kehilat Ostrolenka: Yizkor Book of the Jewish Community of Ostrolenka'', Tel Aviv, Irgun Yotzei Ostrolenka in Israel, 2009, p. 384.</ref>  According to another former Jedwabne resident who, shortly after the massacre, met Jews who had fled Jedwabne, they \"told us when the Germans first entered their town, they had herded all the Jews into a barn and set it ablaze. Anyone who tried to get out was cut down by machine-gun fire.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PsAY9uwZkmEC&printsec=frontcover |title=The Warriors: My Life As A Jewish Soviet Partisan|last=Zissman|first=Harold|date=2005|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=9780815608394|language=en}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=April 2020}}-->\n\n===Survivors===\n[[File:Antonina-Boruch-Wyrzykowska_fot_Adam-Hayder.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Antonina Wyrzykowska]] in 2007]]\nSeveral witnesses reported seeing German photographers take pictures of the massacre. There was also speculation that the pogrom was filmed.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nBetween 100 and 125 Jews who had escaped the massacre returned to Jedwabne. They resided in an open ghetto before being transferred to the \u0141om\u017ca ghetto in November 1942. Several escaped to other towns.{{sfn|Chodakiewicz|2005|p=88}} In November 1942, when the Germans began putting ghetto inmates on trains to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] for extermination, seven of them escaped again to the nearby hamlet of [[Janczewko]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} There Polish farmer [[Antonina Wyrzykowska]] and her husband, Aleksander Wyrzykowski, hid them on their farm from November 1942 to January 1945, despite hostility from neighbors and German searches of their property.<ref name=RadioPoland2Dec2011/> The fugitives included Moshe Olszewicz, his wife, Lea, and his brother, Dov; Jacob and Lea Kubran; and J\u00f3zef Gr\u0105dowski; and Szmuel Wasersztajn.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Wasersztajn later provided testimony about the massacre.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}\n\nAfter the war, the Wyrzykowskis were physically assaulted by local people for having helped Jews. The couple eventually moved to [[Milan\u00f3wek]], near Warsaw,<ref name=RadioPoland2Dec2011>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/59542,Woman-who-helped-Jedwabne-Jews-dies | title=Woman who helped Jedwabne Jews dies |publisher=Radio Poland |date=2 December 2011}}</ref> In 1976 they were awarded Israel's [[Righteous Among the Nations|Righteous among the Nations]] medal.<ref>[http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4035463 \"Wyrzykowski Aleksander & Wyrzykowska Antonina (Karwowska)\"]. The Righteous Among Nations database, Yad Vashem.</ref><ref>[http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/59542,Woman-who-helped-Jedwabne-Jews-dies \"Woman who helped Jedwabne Jews dies\"]. ''The News'', Radio Poland, 12 February 2011; accessed 2 April 2018.</ref> Antonina Wyrzykowska was later also decorated with the Commander's Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] by Poland's President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==1949\u20131950 trials==\n{{seealso|People's Republic of Poland}}\n[[File:A-438 Mogi\u0142a-pomnik, na cmentarzu \u017cydowskim, 1941 Jedwabne B&W.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Pogrom memorial in Jedwabne]]\nAfter the war, in 1949 and 1950, 22<!--or 23?--> suspects from the town and vicinity were put on trial in Poland, accused of collaborating with the Germans during the pogrom. None of the defendants had a higher education and three were illiterate.{{sfn|Shore|2005}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Twelve were convicted of [[treason]] against Poland and one was condemned to death.<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\"/>\n\nRecords show that extreme physical torture applied during pre-trial interrogation by the [[Ministry of Public Security (Poland)|Security Office (UB)]] caused some of the men to confess to criminal acts\u2014confessions they later retracted in court. Those who retracted included J\u00f3zef Chrzanowski, Marian \u017byluk, Czes\u0142aw Lauda\u0144ski, Wincenty Go\u015bcicki, Roman and Jan Zawadzki, Aleksander and Franciszek \u0141ojewski, Eugeniusz \u015aliwecki, Stanis\u0142aw Sielawa, and several others, who were pronounced innocent and released by the court.<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\" />{{clarify|date=April 2020}}<!--source doesn't say this: The illegal interrogation methods were confirmed{{when|date=March 2018}} by Minister of Public Security [[Ministry of Public Security of Poland|Stanis\u0142aw Radkiewicz]], who admitted in an internal memo that the \"fixing\" of the investigation had included beatings and the rephrasing of testimony to aid the prosecution.{{sfn|Musial|2003|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=a_49GjK8ovMC&pg=PA306 306]}}-->\n\nNone of the Polish people who had rescued Jews in Jedwabne were contacted, and no attempt was made to establish the names of the victims. There was no search for the mayor, Marian Karolak, who had vanished, and no effort to name the German units present in the town at the time. The courts did confirm that the defendants' participation had been coerced by German police threats and acts of physical violence.<ref>[[Pawe\u0142 Machcewicz|Machcewicz, Pawel]] (2002). ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (\"Jedwabne and Beyond\"). Translated by Christina Manetti. Warsaw: Institute of National Remembrance. {{isbn|978-8389078087}}</ref>{{request quotation|date=April 2020}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}<!--volume number needed-->\n\n==German investigation, 1960\u20131965==\n''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Wolfgang Birkner]] was investigated by prosecutors in West Germany in 1960 on suspicion of involvement in the massacres of Jews in Jedwabne, Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, and W\u0105sosz in 1941. The charges were based on research by [[Szymon Datner]], head of the [[Bia\u0142ystok]] branch of the [[Central Committee of Polish Jews]] (C\u017bKH). The German prosecutors found no hard evidence implicating Birkner, but in the course of their investigation they discovered a new German witness, the former SS ''Kreiskommissar'' of \u0141om\u017ca, who named the paramilitary [[Einsatzgruppe B]] under SS-Obersturmf\u00fchrer [[Hermann Schaper]] as having been deployed in the area at the time of the pogroms. The methods used by Schaper's death squad in the Radzi\u0142\u00f3w massacre were identical to those employed in Jedwabne only three days later, suggesting they had been involved in the second pogrom.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 1963 a monument to the victims was placed in Jedwabne by the Polish communist state's ''[[Society of Fighters for Freedom and Democracy]]''. Its inscription read: \"The place of destruction of the Jewish population. Here Gestapo and Nazi gendarmes burnt alive 1600 people on 10 July 1941.\"{{sfn|Michlic|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} During the subsequent German investigation at [[Ludwigsburg]] in 1964, Hermann Schaper lied to interrogators, claiming that in 1941 he had been a truck driver. Legal proceedings against the accused were terminated on 2 September 1965, but Schaper's case was reopened in 1974. During the second investigation, Count van der Groeben testified that it was indeed Schaper who had conducted mass executions of Jews in his district. In 1976 a court in [[Giessen]] pronounced Schaper guilty of the execution of Poles and Jews by the kommando SS [[Ciechan\u00f3w|Zichenau]]-[[P\u0142ock|Schr\u00f6ttersburg]].{{clarify|date=April 2020}}{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Schaper was sentenced to six years imprisonment, but was soon released for medical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Urban |first1=Thomas |title=Poszukiwany Hermann Schaper |work=[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]] |date=1 September 2001 |url=https://archiwum.rp.pl/artykul/351399-Poszukiwany--Hermann-Schaper.html}}</ref> According to German federal prosecutors, the documentation of his investigation has most likely been destroyed.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''Neighbors'' by Jan T. Gross (2001)==\n{{Main|Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland}}\n[[File:Jan Tomasz Gross.png|thumb|[[Jan T. Gross]], 2019]]\n[[Jan T. Gross]]'s book ''S\u0105siedzi: Historia zag\u0142ady \u017cydowskiego miasteczka'' (\"Neighbors: The Story of the Annihilation of a Jewish Town\") caused a \"moral earthquake\" when it was published in Poland in May 2000, according to [[Piotr Wr\u00f3bel]]. The book appeared in English in April 2001 as ''Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland''.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=387}} Writing that \"one day, in July 1941, half of the population of a small East European town murdered the other half\u2014some 1,600 men, women and children\", Gross concluded that the Jedwabne Jews had been rounded up and killed by a mob of their own Polish neighbors.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=7}} This ran contrary to the official account that they had been killed by Germans.<ref name=Kauffmann19Dec2002>{{cite news|first=Sylvie |last=Kauffmann |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2002/dec/19/highereducation.news |title=Poland faces up to the horror of its own role in the Holocaust|newspaper=The Guardian |date= 19 December 2002}}</ref> \n \nGross recognized that German occupying forces had control of the town: \"At the time, the undisputed bosses over life and death in Jedwabne were the Germans. No sustained organized activity could take place there without their consent.\"{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=47}} He concluded that the massacre was carried out entirely by Poles from Jedwabne and the surrounding area,<!-- insufficient referencing --> and that the Polish perpetrators had not been coerced by the Germans.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=133}}<!-- insufficient referencing --> One of his principal sources was Szmul Wasersztajn, a witness whose testimony had been deposited in 1945 at the [[Jewish Historical Institute]] in Warsaw. Other sources were Stalinist investigation affidavits and records of the 1949\u20131950 trials; a 1980 book, ''Yedwabne: History and Memorial Book''; and interviews from the 1990s conducted by Gross and a filmmaker.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}\n\nWhile several Polish historians praised Gross for having drawn attention to the pogrom, others criticized him for relying too heavily on these accounts, which they argued were not reliable, and\u2014where conflicting accounts existed\u2014for choosing those that showed the Poles in the worst possible light.<ref>{{harvnb|Chodakiewicz|2001}}; {{harvnb|Musial|2003|p=334}}; for not reliable, {{harvnb|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}.</ref>{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\n==IPN investigation, 2000\u20132003==\n===Reasons===\nIn July 2000, following the publication of Gross's book and the ensuing debate, the Polish parliament ordered a new investigation into the pogrom. Parliament charged the [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (''Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej'', or IPN) with transmitting its findings for possible legal action. The IPN had recently been created as an independent successor to the Commission for the Investigation of Nazi Crimes in Poland, formed after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Its major role was the promotion of historical research on topics that had been banned for over 40 years under communist rule (1945\u20131989), including pogroms.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAlthough Gross's book was the catalyst for the investigation, the first scholarly analysis of the pogrom was by [[Szymon Datner]] for the [[Jewish Historical Institute]] in December 1966, and it had reached similar conclusions.<ref name=\"ipn.gov.pl195\"/>{{sfn|Polonsky|Michlic|2003|p=452}}\n\n===Proceedings===\nOver the course of two years, IPN investigators interviewed some 111 witnesses, mainly from Poland, but also from Israel and the United States.<ref name=\"ipn.gov.pl195\">{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=Manslaughter of Jewish Inhabitants of Jedwabne |url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal/en/19/195/Manslaughter_of_Jewish_Inhabitants_of_Jedwabne.html |website= |date=18 November 2003 |publisher=Institute of National Remembrance |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009223428/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal/en/19/195/Manslaughter_of_Jewish_Inhabitants_of_Jedwabne.html |archivedate=9 October 2012 |location=Warsaw |url-status=dead}}</ref> One-third of the IPN witnesses had been eyewitnesses of some part of the pogrom. Since the event had occurred 59 years earlier, when most of the survivors still living today were children, their recollections varied. The IPN also searched for and examined documents in Polish archives in Warsaw, Bia\u0142ystok and \u0141om\u017ca, in German archives, and at Yad Vashem in Israel.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn May\u2013June 2001 the IPN conducted a partial exhumation at the site of the barn, where the largest number of victims died. Based on a similar exhumation at [[Katyn massacre|Katyn]], where Stalin's forces murdered 22,000 Polish prisoners of war in 1940, the IPN's forensic examiner estimated that the burial site in Jedwabne contained the remains of between 300 and 400 victims.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}<ref name=\"jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf\">{{cite web |title=Postanowienie |url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |website=www.ipn.gov.pl|publisher=Institute of National Remembrance (IPN) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114125013/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |archivedate=14 November 2012 |date=30 June 2003 |url-status=live}}</ref> There were charred bodies in two mass graves, and also broken pieces of the bust of Lenin (previously assumed to have been buried at a Jewish cemetery).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} The scope of the exhumation was restricted because of religious objections to disturbing the remains.{{sfn|Gross|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Rabbi Joseph Polak also took issue with the decision, asserting that Jewish law required the bodies to be reinterred in a proper burial ground.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://traditionarchive.org/news/originals/Volume%2035/No.%204/Exhuming%20Their%20Neighbors.pdf|title=Exhuming Their Neighbors: A Halakhic Inquiry|last=Polak|first=Joseph A.|journal=Tradition: A Journal of Orthodox Jewish Thought|volume=35|number=4|date=Winter 2001|pages=23\u201343|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeon Kieres, the President of IPN, met in New York with Rabbi Jacob Baker,<ref>Rabbi Jacob Baker, [http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/J/Baker.html  \"We Trusted Each Other\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051659/http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/J/Baker.html |date=4 March 2016 }} Polish Academic Information Center, University of Buffalo.</ref> formerly Yaakov Eliezer Piekarz, who had emigrated in 1938 from Jedwabne to the United States. In January 2001, during his visit to New York, Kieres said that IPN had accumulated enough evidence to confirm that a group of Poles were the perpetrators of the Jedwabne massacre. The IPN's evidence was presented to the Polish Parliament and in other public statements.<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" />  While the investigation continued for two more years, the finding of Polish involvement in the Jedwabne massacre became public knowledge in Poland in early 2001.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} In June that year, the IPN said ammunition shells recovered from the site were German, prompting speculation that German soldiers had \ufb01red at Jews fleeing the barn. About six months later, the IPN found that the shells were from a different historical period.{{sfn|Michlic|2012|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BfQoxsH9bbwC&pg=PA81 81]}}{{sfn|Wolentarska-Ochman|2006}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===IPN's findings, 2002\u20132003===\n[[File:Le m\u00e9morial du pogrom de Jedwabne.jpg|thumb|upright=1.6|Jedwabne memorial, 2011]]\nOn 9 July 2002 the IPN released the findings of its two-year investigation, \"Findings of Investigation S 1 / 00 / Zn into the Murder of Polish Citizens of Jewish Origin in the Town of Jedwabne on 10 July 1941\".{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.warsawvoice.pl/WVpage/pages/article.php/2968/article |title=Insight Into Tragedy |work=The Warsaw Voice |date=17 July 2003 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303021458/http://www.warsawvoice.pl/WVpage/pages/article.php/2968/article |archivedate=3 March 2011}}</ref> Chief prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew wrote:\n\n* The perpetrators of the crime ''sensu stricto'' were about 40 male \"Polish inhabitants of Jedwabne and its environs\". Responsibility for the crime ''sensu largo'' could be ascribed to the Germans because of the presence of German military policemen at the Jedwabne police station. Their presence, \"though passive, was tantamount to consent to and tolerance of the crime against the Jewish inhabitants of the town\".{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA135 135]}} The IPN found that Poles played a \"decisive role\" in the massacre, but the massacre was \"instigated by the Germans\". The massacre was carried out in full view of the Germans, who were armed and had control of the town, and the Germans did not intervene and halt the killings.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* At least 340 Jewish victims were killed in the pogrom, in two groups of which the first contained 40 to 50 men, and the second about 300 persons. The exact number of victims could not be determined. The previously estimated figure of 1,600 was \"highly unlikely, and was not confirmed in the course of the investigation.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n* \"At least forty (Polish) men\" were perpetrators of the crime. The majority of Jedwabne residents were \"utterly passive,\" the IPN found, and did not participate in the massacre. The IPN wrote: \"On the basis of the evidence gathered in the investigation, it is not possible to determine the reasons for the passivity of most of the town in the face of the crime. In particular, it cannot be determined whether this passivity resulted from acceptance of the crime or from intimidation by the brutality of the perpetrators' acts.\"{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n* A number of witnesses had testified that the Germans drove the group of Jewish victims from Jedwabne's town square to the barn where they were killed (these testimonies are found in the expanded 203-page ''Findings'' published in June 2003). IPN could neither conclusively prove nor disprove these accounts. \"Witness testimonies vary considerably on this question.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* \"A group of Jewish people survived\" the massacre. Several dozen \u2014 according to several sources, about a hundred \u2014 Jews lived in a ghetto in Jedwabne until November 1942, when they were transferred by the Germans to a ghetto in \u0141om\u017ca, and eventually deported to Treblinka, where they were killed. The seven Jews hidden by the Wyrzykowski family were not the only survivors of the Jedwabne massacre.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nA greatly expanded version of the findings, in 203 pages of Polish text, was issued by the IPN on 30 June 2003.  The original version of 9 July 2002 appears as the concluding five pages of this document. Pages 60\u2013160 contain summaries of the testimonies of numerous witnesses interviewed by the IPN. The full 203-page text detailing the government-led investigation was published on the IPN website.<ref name=\"jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf\"/> It was supplemented by two volumes of studies and documents in Polish: ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'', vol. 1: ''Studies'' (525 pages) and vol. 2: ''Documents'' (1,034 pages).<ref name=MachcewiczandPersak2002>Machcewicz, Pawe\u0142; Persak, Krzysztof (2002). ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego''. [https://www.academia.edu/30085727/_Wok%C3%B3%C5%82_Jedwabnego_Jedwabne_and_Beyond_Vol._1_Studia_Studies_eds._Pawe%C5%82_Machcewicz_Krzysztof_Persak_Warszawa_IPN_2002_526_pp Vol. 1: ''Studia'']; Vol. 2: ''Dokumenty''. Warsaw: Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej. {{isbn|978-8389078087}}.</ref>\n\nKieres delivered the IPN report at 27 February 2002 session of the Polish parliament. A small opposition party, the [[League of Polish Families]] (''LPR''), called Kieres a \"servant of the Jews\" and blamed him and President [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] for \"stoning the Polish nation\". LPR MP [[Antoni Macierewicz]] made an official complaint against the IPN's conclusion that ethnic Poles and not the Germans had committed the massacre.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\">{{harvnb|Michlic|2002}}.</ref>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nPolish cultural anthropologist Ludwik Stomma questioned the IPN's downward revision of the number of victims, objected to the IPN's conclusion that the massacre was \"committed directly by Poles but instigated by the Germans\", and said that this formulation was meant to please the political right.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\"/>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n[[Joanna Michlic]] described the activities of the IPN as \"a very professional forensic investigation\". She added: \"Members of the IPN team headed by Leon Kieres had refused to bend to the version of the crime presented in the strongly defensive camp, and thus came under attack in the nationalist press.\"{{sfn|Michlic|2002|p=30}}\n\nAmerican historian [[Jan T. Gross]] praised the conduct of the IPN investigation.<ref name=\"JS\">El\u017cbieta Po\u0142udnik, Andrzej Kaczy\u0144ski, [http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/Pol/jednak_sasiedzi.htm Wyniki \u015bledztwa w sprawie Jedwabnego - Jednak s\u0105siedzi], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 June 2002</ref><ref name=\"gw\">{{cite news | url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,76498,3468035.html | title=Jedwabne i \"Strach\" | work=Gazeta Wyborcza | date=9 July 2006 | accessdate=1 January 2012 | author=J\u0119drysik Mi\u0142ada}}</ref> His findings were incorporated into a Polish secondary-school history text.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\"/>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nOn 30 June 2003 prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew announced that the investigation of \"the mass murder of at least 340 Polish citizens of Jewish nationality in Jedwabne on July 10, 1941\" had discovered no living suspected perpetrators in the Jedwabne atrocity who had not already been brought to justice, and so the IPN investigation was closed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipn.gov.pl/wydzial-prasowy/komunikaty/komunikat-dot.-postanowienia-o-umorzeniu-sledztwa-w-sprawie-zabojstwa-obywateli |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620004217/http://ipn.gov.pl/wydzial-prasowy/komunikaty/komunikat-dot.-postanowienia-o-umorzeniu-sledztwa-w-sprawie-zabojstwa-obywateli |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 June 2013 |trans-title=A communiqu\u00e9 regarding the decision to end the investigation of the murder of Polish citizens of Jewish nationality in Jedwabne on 10 July 1941 |date=30 June 2003 |title=Komunikat dot. postanowienia o umorzeniu \u015bledztwa w sprawie zab\u00f3jstwa obywateli polskich narodowo\u015bci \u017cydowskiej w Jedwabnem w dniu 10 lipca 1941 r. |publisher =Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej (IPN) |language=pl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |trans-title=Judgement to End Investigation |title=Postanowienie o umorzeniu \u015bledztwa | publisher=Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej (IPN) |url=https://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |language=pl}}</ref><!--this needs a scholarly source: After the investigation, new archival evidence confirmed that the Germans employed paid agents to instigate pogroms. Prosecutor Ignatiew stated: \"It is obvious that Poles could not just do whatever they pleased in the German-occupied territories. They could not therefore have organized pogroms. These were organized by the Germans. As the documents show, the Germans readied themselves to organize pogroms of Jews and had advance intelligence (from their agents) as to who among the Poles bore hatred toward Jews because Jews had denounced their relatives to the Soviets, and who was a bandit who would kill if paid money. And it was those people whom they chose to carry out the pogroms, turning them into ordinary criminal gangs.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Agent Gestapo inspirowa\u0142 pogromy w 1941 r. w okolicach \u0141om\u017cy|last=Bia\u0142ous|first=Adam|date= 11\u201312 July 2009|work=Nasz Dziennik|access-date=}}</ref>-->\n\n==Documentaries==\nPolish film-maker [[Agnieszka Arnold]] made two documentary films interviewing witnesses of the Jedwabne massacre.  ''(Gdzie m\u00f3j starszy syn Kain)'' (1999, ''Where is my elder son Cain'')  included interviews with Szmul Wassersztajn, and the daughter of the owner of the barn where the massacre took place. ''(S\u0105siedzi)'' (2001, ''Neighbors'') dealt with the subject in greater depth. Jan Gross wrote a book of the same name, with Arnold's agreement as to title.<ref>[https://www.wilmatheater.org/blog/agnieszka-arnold-documentary-filmmaker-%E2%80%93-part-one Agnieszka Arnold documentary filmmaker], Wilma Theater</ref> \n\nProfessor Jan Tomasz Gross also appears in Haim Hecht's documentary ''Two Barns'' (2014) along other prominent Holocaust historians, Literature Nobel-prize winner [[Wislawa Szymborska]], and Professor [[Shevah Weiss]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/104504131|title=Two Barns - English Version|first=Roy|last=Mandel|date=27 August 2014|via=Vimeo}}</ref>\n\n==Other monographs==\n===''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (2002)===\n''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (\"Jedwabne and Beyond\") is the official two-volume [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (''IPN'') publication of documents produced by the 2000-2003 IPN investigation. Volume 1, ''Studies'' (525 pages) contains historical and legal studies written by historians working for IPN. Volume 2, ''Documents'' (1,034 pages) contains original documents collected by the IPN investigation.<ref name=MachcewiczandPersak2002/> Included are testimonies by Jews on various antisemitic acts committed by Poles, as well as testimonies by non-Jewish Polish schoolteachers deported to Siberia, who reported that Jewish communists had been moved into positions of authority in the Soviet occupation apparatus in eastern Poland.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}{{efn|Volume 2 of ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' includes a Polish translation (from the Hebrew) of a memoir written by Chaya Finkelsztajn of Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, describing conditions under the 1939\u20131941 Soviet occupation and the subsequent 1941 [[Operation Barbarossa]] German invasion. Chaya Finkelsztajn survived the 1941\u20131945 German occupation, under perilous circumstances, after a Polish Catholic priest agreed to baptise her as a Christian. She later emigrated to Israel, where she wrote her memoir.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}}}\n\n===''The Neighbors Respond'' (2003)===\nAn extensive collection of articles from the Polish and international debate, in English translation, was published in 2003 as ''The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland'' by [[Joanna Michlic]] and [[Antony Polonsky]] of [[Brandeis University]]. The book includes articles from Polish and other historians, the IPN's ''Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn into the Murder of Polish Citizens of Jewish Origin in the Town of Jedwabne on 10 July 1941'' (2002), and essays from Polish newspapers such as ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' and ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]''. The collection features archival documents and essays covering the entire 1939\u20131941 period. Contributors include [[Anna Bikont]], [[David Engel]], [[Israel Gutman]], [[Adam Michnik]], [[Bogdan Musial]], [[Dariusz Stola]], and [[Tomasz Strzembosz]].{{sfn|Polonsky|Michlic|2003}}\n\n===''The Massacre in Jedwabne, 10 July 1941'' (2005)===\n[[Marek Jan Chodakiewicz]]'s book ''The Massacre in Jedwabne, 10 July 1941: Before, During, and After'' challenges Gross's interpretation of the events.{{sfn|Holc|2008}} It suggests that four or five truckloads of armed [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] men from [[\u0141om\u017ca]] terrorized the local population before leading Jews and Poles to the crime scene.{{sfn|Chodakiewicz|2005}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} He wrote: \"the killing of between 200 and 400 Jews (not 1,600, as claimed by Gross) was conceived, supervised and executed by German police, with only limited involvement by a very small number of Poles, some of whom were coerced into participating. Even then, the few willing Polish collaborators included ''Volksdeutsche'' (Polish citizens of German origin) and petty criminals.\"{{sfn|Michlic|Polonsky|2008}}<!--add Chodakiewicz-->\n\n[[Piotr Wr\u00f3bel]] wrote that Chodakiewicz's aim, stated in the introduction, was to show that Gross was wrong. \nChodakiewicz argues that all the primary sources are wrong or worthless, including the testimony of Szmul Wassersztajn, the investigation of the 22 suspects for the 1949 trial, and the partial exhumation of the bodies. \"And yet,\" writes Wr\u00f3bel, \"Chodakiewicz is able to present his recreation of the crime. It was well preplanned, initiated by the Germans, and utterly lacked any pogrom-like spontaneity.\" Wr\u00f3bel acknowledged that Chodakiewicz made some good arguments but wrote that they are \"overshadowed by numerous flaws\", lack a sense of proportion, and make selective use of information from sources that support Chodakiewicz's view. According to Wr\u00f3bel, the book has a \"visible political agenda\" and is \"difficult to read, unoriginal, irritating, and unconvincing\".{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006b}}\n\n[[Peter D. Stachura]] described the book positively. \"The important debate about Polish-Jewish relations must continue to develop on the basis of informed, impartial scrutiny, analysis and interpretation, with reference to authenticated, solid evidence, as Professor Chodakiewicz has so ably demonstrated.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In response, [[Joanna Michlic]] and [[Antony Polonsky]] wrote a letter in 2008 to the editor of ''[[History (journal)|History]]'', expressing their strong disagreement with the \"content and tone\" of Stachura's review. According to Michlic and Polonsky, Chodakiewicz's conclusions and Stachura's review were \"very far from those reached by most historians\" who have examined the Jedwabne pogrom, including Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]]. They wrote that Chodakiewicz and Stachura \"uphold a view of the Polish past which seeks to return to an untenable vision of modern Poland as solely victim and hero&nbsp;... It is a matter of considerable regret to us that you have allowed your journal to be used to advance this neo-nationalist agenda.\"{{sfn|Michlic|Polonsky|2008}} Stachura took exception to their letter. ''History'' declined to publish his reply; instead, it was posted on the website of ''Glaukopis'', a Polish journal.{{sfn|Stachura|2008}}\n\n==2001 anniversary==\n[[File:Aleksander Kwasniewski - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Polish president [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] apologized for the massacre in 2001.<ref name=Connolly11July2001/>]]\nIn July 2001, on the 60th anniversary of the pogrom, Polish president [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] attended a ceremony at Jedwabne where he apologized for the massacre: \"We can have no doubt that here in Jedwabne Polish citizens were killed at the hands of fellow citizens&nbsp;... I apologise in my own name, and in the name of those Poles whose conscience is shattered by that crime.\" The ceremony was attended by Catholic and Jewish religious leaders and survivors of the pogrom. Most of the 2,000 locals of Jedwabne, including the town's priest, boycotted the ceremony in protest against the apology.<ref name=Connolly11July2001>{{cite news|first=Kate|last=Connolly |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/jul/11/poland |title=Poland says sorry for slaughter of Jews |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n[[Shevah Weiss]], Israeli Ambassador to Poland, also delivered a speech. \"Living among us also are Holocaust survivors whose lives were saved as a result of the brave actions of their Polish neighbors,\" he said. He praised Poland's research and investigation process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/eng/jedwabne.htm |title=Jedwabne 10 July\u2014Reports and Opinions |publisher=The Canadian Foundation of Polish-Jewish Heritage, Montreal Chapter}}</ref>\n\nNobel Peace Prize recipient and former Polish President [[Lech Walesa]] commented about the apology: \"The Jedwabne crime was a revenge for the cooperation of the Jewish community with the Soviet occupant. The Poles have already apologized many times to the Jews; we are waiting for the apology from the other side because many Jews were scoundrels.\"<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524200234/https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 | url-status=dead | archive-date=24 May 2012 | title=Facing Jedwabne - American Jewish Committee}}</ref>\n\nA March 2001 poll conducted by the Polish daily ''Rzeczpospolita'' found that one-half of Poles were aware of the Jedwabne massacre; among Poles with a higher education the proportion rose to 81 percent. Forty percent of respondents supported Kwa\u015bniewski's decision to apologize. A majority condemned the actions of the Poles involved in the massacre.<ref>[http://archiwum.rp.pl/artykul/328841_Wiemy_i_potepiamy.html  Wiemy i pot\u0119piamy (We know, and we condemn).] Republic of Poland. Archives.</ref>\n\nA monument had been placed in Jedwabne in the 1960s with the inscription: \"Site of the Suffering of the Jewish Population. The Gestapo and the Nazi Gendarmerie Burned Alive 1600 People July 10, 1941.\"<ref name=Rosenfeld>Alvin H. Rosenfeld, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120524200234/https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 'Facing Jedwabne.'] ''American Jewish Committee.'' Retrieved 8 November 2012.</ref> This was replaced by a new monument in July 2001, with inscriptions in Polish, Hebrew and Yiddish: \"To the Memory of Jews from Jedwabne and the Surrounding Area, Men, Women, and Children, Co-inhabitants of this Land, Who Were Murdered and Burned Alive on This Spot on July 10, 1941.\"<ref name=Rosenfeld /> In August 2001 Jedwabne mayor Krzysztof Godlewski, a pioneer for the commemoration of the massacre, resigned in protest at the local council's lack of majority support for it.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/jedwabne-mayor-resigns-over-memorial-to-jews/article4150944/ | title=Jedwabne mayor resigns over memorial to Jews}}</ref> He became a recipient of the [[Jan Karski]] Humanitarian Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/eng/listopad_former_mayor.html|title=The Polish-Jewish Heritage Foundation of Canada, Montreal Chapter - The former Mayor of Jedwabne talks about himself and the anniversary celebrations|website=www.polish-jewish-heritage.org}}</ref><!--\n==Events, 2006\u2013present==\nAt a round-table discussion on 7 July 2006, [[Jan T. Gross]] said, \"I repeat three times in the book (''[[Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland|Neighbors]]'') that the murder happened by order of the Germans\" (''\"mord by\u0142 z rozkazu Niemc\u00f3w\"'').<ref name=\"gw\"/>\n\nIn 2009 Polish politician [[Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski]] was criticized by Britain's [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and some British journalists for having in 2001 opposed a Polish national apology for the Jedwabne massacre. The criticism came after Kaminski was made chairperson of the [[European Parliament]]'s group of [[European Conservatives and Reformists]].<ref name=\"thejc\"/> Kami\u0144ski denied that his opposition to an apology stemmed from antisemitism. He was defended by the Conservatives and some journalists, including the editor of the ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'', Stephen Pollard.<ref name=\"thejc6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/20818/analysis-kaminski-our-friend-a-smear-campaign |title=Analysis: Kaminski is our friend \u2013 this is a smear campaign |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=8 November 2010.</ref><ref>Hannan, Daniel. [http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/danielhannan/100005218/accusing-euro-sceptics-of-anti-semitism-is-the-most-shameful-tactic-yet/ Accusing Euro-sceptics of anti-Semitism is the most shameful tactic yet]. ''The Daily Telegraph''.</ref>\n\nA 2009 play ''Our Class'' by Polish [[playwright]] Tadeusz S\u0142obodzianek, performed in Britain,<ref>Nathan, John (11 September 2009). [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article6830524.ece \"Our Class and the bloody history of Poland that refuses to die\"]. ''The Times''.</ref> deals with a massacre of Jews by Poles in a small town during the Holocaust. A review in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' argued that the play misrepresented Poles as \"just itching for the German invasion as the excuse to give violent vent to their deep-rooted anti-Semitism\" and \"too often [...] looked like an object lesson in gross simplification.\"<ref>Cavendish, Dominic (9 November 2009). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/6530381/Is-Our-Class-at-the-National-Theatre-really-such-a-reliable-history-lesson.html \"Is Our Class at the National Theatre really such a reliable history lesson?\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph''.</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2011 Poland's President [[Bronis\u0142aw Komorowski]] asked for forgiveness at a ceremony marking the 70th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/poland-asks-jews-for-forgiveness-on-70th-anniversary-of-yedvabne-massacre-1.372579 | work=Haaretz| title=Poland asks Jews for forgiveness on 70th anniversary of Yedvabne massacre  | date=11 July 2011 | accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"jta\">{{cite news| url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/07/11/3088484/polands-president-asks-jewish-forgiveness-at-memorial-ceremony| work=JTA| title=Poland's president asks for forgiveness at Jedwabne memorial| date=11 July 2011| accessdate=11 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713104934/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/07/11/3088484/polands-president-asks-jewish-forgiveness-at-memorial-ceremony| archive-date=13 July 2011| url-status=dead}}</ref> It was reported on 1 September 2011 that the Jedwabne memorial had been defaced with a swastika and graffiti that read \"They were flammable\" and \"I don't apologize for Jedwabne.\"<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news|last=Andrusz |first=Katya |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-02/polish-president-condemns-vandalism-of-jewish-massacre-memorial.html |title=Polish President Condemns Vandalism of Jewish Massacre Memorial |publisher=Bloomberg |date= 2 September 2011|accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/09/01/3089197/memorial-to-jedwabne-pogrom-vandalized-in-poland \"Memorial to Jedwabne pogrom vandalized\"]. ''Jewish Telegraphic Agency'', 1 September 2011. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929223813/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/09/01/3089197/memorial-to-jedwabne-pogrom-vandalized-in-poland |date=29 September 2012 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/world/article/memorial_to_jedwabne_pogrom_vandalized_in_poland_20110901/|title=Vandal defaced monument|date=1 September 2011|publisher=JewishJournal.com|location=Los Angeles|access-date=1 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404050511/http://www.jewishjournal.com/world/article/memorial_to_jedwabne_pogrom_vandalized_in_poland_20110901/|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Poland launched an anti-hate crime investigation involving the country's domestic [[intelligence agency]], the [[Agencja Bezpiecze\u0144stwa Wewn\u0119trznego|ABW]].<ref name=\"www8\">{{cite web|author=Rp.pl |url=http://www.rp.pl/artykul/17,710609-ABW-szuka-wandali--ktorzy-zniszczyli-pomnik-w-Jedwabnem.html |title=ABW szuka wandali, kt\u00f3rzy zniszczyli pomnik w Jedwabnem |publisher=rp.pl |date= |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"PAP\">{{cite web | url=http://www.deon.pl/wiadomosci/polska/art,9442,pomnik-w-jedwabnem-i-usuwanie-zniszczen.html | title=Pomnik w Jedwabnem i usuwanie zniszcze\u0144 (''Memorial in Jedwabne, cleaning of damage'') | publisher=DEON.pl after [[Polska Agencja Prasowa]] | date=1 September 2011 | accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 television interview, Polish education minister [[Anna Zalewska]] expressed doubt regarding whether Poles had participated in the pogrom.<ref name=Aderet>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/1.731391 |title=Two Senior Polish Ministers Deny Poles' Involvement in Massacres of Jews |work=[[Haaretz]] |first=Ofer |last=Aderet |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=30 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/polish-education-minister-says-massacres-of-jews-an-opinion/ |title=Polish education minister says massacres of Jews an 'opinion' |work= [[The Times of Israel]] |first=Vanessa |last=Gera |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name=Wprost/> When the interviewer asked whether Poles had killed their Jewish neighbors, Zalewska described that as one viewpoint and said other researchers had reached other conclusions.<ref name=Aderet/><ref name=Wprost/> In a radio interview two months later, she said that Poles shared responsibility for the massacre, while adding that the country was under [[German occupation of Poland|Nazi German occupation]] and that the [[Polish Underground State|continuity Polish resistance state]] punished the murder of Jews.<ref name=Wprost>{{cite web |url=https://www.wprost.pl/kraj/10022256/Minister-zmienila-zdanie-Polacy-wspolodpowiedzialni-za-pogrom-w-Jedwabnem.html |title=Minister zmieni\u0142a zdanie. 'Polacy wsp\u00f3\u0142odpowiedzialni za pogrom w Jedwabnem' |trans-title=The minister changed her mind. 'Poles are jointly responsible for the pogrom in Jedwabne' |work=[[Wprost]] |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref>-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Aftermath (2012 film)|''Aftermath'' (2012 film)]]\n* [[Anti-Jewish violence in Poland, 1944\u20131946]]\n* [[The Holocaust in Poland]]\n* [[Kielce pogrom]]\n* [[List of anti-Jewish pogroms in Poland during World War II]]\n* [[Polish Righteous Among the Nations]]\n* [[Kaunas pogrom]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|26em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|26em|refs=\n<!--<ref name=\"Ignatiew-1\"> These are the official findings of the Institute of National Remembrance, \"confirmed by the number of victims in the two graves, according to the estimate of the archeological and anthropological team participating in the exhumation,\" wrote prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew in [https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 ''The neighbors respond: the controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland'' By Antony Polonsky, Joanna B. Michlic. Page 134] [[Princeton University Press]], 2004. {{ISBN|0-691-11306-8}}</ref>-->\n<!-- <ref name=\"JS\">El\u017cbieta Po\u0142udnik, Andrzej Kaczy\u0144ski, [http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/Pol/jednak_sasiedzi.htm Wyniki \u015bledztwa w sprawie Jedwabnego - Jednak s\u0105siedzi], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 June 2002</ref> -->\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n{{refbegin|26em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Baker |first1=Julius |last2=Tzinovitz |first2=Moshe |title=Yedwabne: History and Memorial Book |date=1980 |editor1-last=Baker |editor1-first=Julius| editor2-last=Baker |editor2-first=Jacob |publisher=The Yedwabner Societies in Israel and the United States of America |location=Jerusalem and New York |url=https://www.jewishgen.org/Yizkor/Jedwabne/yed001.html#5 |ref=harv |chapter=My Hometown Yedwabne, Province of Lomza, Poland}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bikont |first1=Anna |author-link=Anna Bikont |translator = Alissa Valles |title=The Crime and the Silence: Confronting the Massacre of Jews in Wartime Jedwabne |date=2015 |orig-year=2004 |publisher=Farrar, Strauss and Giroux |location=New York |isbn=978-0-374-17879-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Browning | first = Christopher R. | authorlink = Christopher Browning | title = The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939 \u2013 March 1942 | year = 2004 | publisher = University of Nebraska Press and Yad Vashem| location = Lincoln and Jerusalem | isbn = 0-8032-1327-1 | ref = harv | url = https://archive.org/details/originsoffinalso00brow}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cesarani |first1=David |authorlink1=David Cesarani |title=Final Solution: The Fate of the Jews 1933\u20131949 |date=2016 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Chodakiewicz |first1=Marek Jan |authorlink = Marek Jan Chodakiewicz |title=Research Before Conclusion: The Problems of Shock Therapy in Jedwabne |journal=Glaukopis |location= |date=2001 |volume= |issue=|pages= |doi= |url=https://www.iwp.edu/wp-content/uploads/2002/01/MJ-Chodakiewicz-Shock-Therapy-Jedwabne-Feb-2001.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| first = Marek Jan | last = Chodakiewicz | authorlink = | title=The Massacre in Jedwabne, July 10, 1941: Before, During, After | publisher=East European Monographs, distributed by Columbia University Press |location=Boulder, CO| year=2005 | isbn=978-0-88033-554-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Crago |first1=Laura |editor1-last=Megargee | editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=Dean |editor2-first=Martin |title=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945 |title-link=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945 | date=2012 |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |location=Bloomington and Indianapolis |volume=IIA |isbn= 978-0-253-35328-3 |pages=899\u2013902 |ref=harv |chapter=Jedwabne}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gross | first = Jan T. | authorlink = Jan Tomasz Gross | title = Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland | url = https://archive.org/details/neighbors00jant | url-access = registration | publisher = Princeton University Press| location = Princeton and Oxford |year = 2001 | isbn = 978-0-14-200240-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Gross |first1=Jan T. |title=A Response |journal=Slavic Review |date=Autumn 2002 |volume=61 |issue=3 |pages=483\u2013489 |jstor=3090298 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Holc |first1=Janine P. |title=Working through Jan Gross's ''Neighbors'' |journal=Slavic Review |date=Autumn 2002 |volume=61 |issue=3 |page=454 |jstor=3090294 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Holc |first1=Janine P. |title=''The Massacre in Jedwabne, July 10, 1941: Before, During, After''. By Marek Jan Chodakiewicz |journal=Slavic Review |date=Spring 2008 |volume=67 |issue=1 |pages=202\u2013203 |doi=10.2307/27652785 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=Institute of National Remembrance |editor1-last=Polonsky |editor1-first=Antony |editor2-last=Michlic |editor2-first=Joanna B. |title=The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland |publisher = Princeton University Press | location=Princeton |isbn = 978-0-691-11306-7 | pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA133 133\u2013136] | year = 2003 |chapter=Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn into the Murder of Polish Citizens of Jewish Origin in the Town of Jedwabne on 10 July 1941, pursuant to Article 1 Point 1 of the Decree of 31 August 1944 |ref={{sfnref|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002}}}}\n* {{cite book |title=A World in Flames: A Short History of the Second World War |last=Kitchen |first=Martin |year=1990 |publisher=Longman |location= |isbn=978-0-582-03408-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Longerich |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Longerich |year=2010 |title=Holocaust: The Nazi Persecution and Murder of the Jews |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-280436-5 |location=Oxford |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Lukowski |first1=Jerzy |last2=Zawadzki|first2=Hubert |year=2019 |title=A Concise History of Poland |publisher=Cambridge University Press |edition=Third |location=Cambridge|isbn=978-1-108-42436-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Michlic |first1=Joanna B. |author1-link=Joanna Michlic |title=Coming to Terms with the 'Dark Past': The Polish Debate about the Jedwabne Massacre |journal=Vidal Sassoon International Center for the Study of Antisemitism, The Hebrew University of Jerusalem |location=Jerusalem |date=2002 |volume= |issue=|pages= |doi= |url=https://archive.jpr.org.uk/object-879 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Michlic|first1=Joanna B.|author1-link=|last2=Polonsky|first2=Antony|title=Letter to the Editor|journal=History|date=January 2008|volume=93|issue=309|pages=154\u2013158|doi=10.1111/j.1468-229x.2008.00415.x|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Michlic|first1=Joanna |authorlink1= |editor1-last=Wistrich |editor1-first=Robert|editor1-link=Robert Wistrich |title=Holocaust Denial: The Politics of Perfidy |date=2012 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter and Hebrew University Magnes Press |location=Berlin, Boston and Jerusalem |isbn=978-3-11-028814-8 |pages=67\u201384 |ref=harv |chapter=The Jedwabne Debate: Reshaping Polish National Mythology}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Musial |first1=Bogdan |authorlink1=Bogdan Musial |editor1-last=Polonsky |editor1-first=Antony |editor2-last=Michlic |editor2-first=Joanna B. |editor1-link=Antony Polonsky |editor2-link= |title=The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland |date=2003 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton and Oxford |isbn=0-691-11306-8 |pages=304\u2013343 |chapter=The Pogrom in Jedwabne: Critical Remarks about Jan T. Gross's ''Neighbors'' |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Persak |first1=Krzysztof |title=Jedwabne before the Court: Poland's Justice and the Jedwabne Massacre\u2014Investigations and Court Proceedings, 1947\u20131974 |journal=East European Politics and Societies |date=August 2011 |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=410\u2013432 |doi=10.1177/0888325411398915 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/241646847_Jedwabne_before_the_CourtPoland's_Justice_and_the_Jedwabne_Massacre-Investigations_and_Court_Proceedings_1947-1974 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Pinchuk |first1=Ben-Cion |editor1-last=Zimmerman |editor1-first=Joshua D. |editor1-link=Joshua D. Zimmerman |title=Contested Memories: Poles and Jews during the Holocaust and Its Aftermath |date=2003 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick |isbn=978-0813531588 |pages=61\u201368 |ref=harv |chapter=Facing Hitler and Stalin: On the Subject of Jewish 'Collaboration' in Soviet-Occupied Eastern Poland, 1939\u20131941}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-first=Antony |editor1-last=Polonsky |editor1-link=Antony Polonsky |editor2-last=Michlic |editor2-first=Joanna B. |editor2-link=Joanna Michlic |title=The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland |date=2003 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton and Oxford |isbn=0-691-11306-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Polonsky |editor1-first=Antony |editor2-last=Michlic |editor2-first=Joanna B. |editor1-link=Antony Polonsky |editor2-link= |title=The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland |date=2003 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton and Oxford |isbn=0-691-11306-8 |pages=451\u2013458 |chapter=Chronology |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Raack |first=Richard |title=Stalin's Drive to the West, 1938\u20131945: The Origins of the Cold War |year=1995 |publisher=Stanford University Press |location=Stanford |isbn=978-0-8047-2415-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal | last1=Shore| first1=Marci |doi=10.1353/kri.2005.0027| title=Conversing with Ghosts: Jedwabne, Zydokomuna, and Totalitarianism| journal=Kritika: Explorations in Russian and Eurasian History| volume=6| issue=2| pages=345\u2013374| year=2005| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|last=Stachura |first=Peter |author-link=Peter D. Stachura |title=Jedwabne: A reply to Antony Polonsky & Joanna Michlic |url=http://www.glaukopis.pl/images/artykuly-obcojezyczne/Peter-d-Stachura-JedwabneReplyToAntonyPolonsky.pdf|work=Glaukopis|date=6 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510073743/http://www.glaukopis.pl/images/artykuly-obcojezyczne/Peter-d-Stachura-JedwabneReplyToAntonyPolonsky.pdf|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=dead|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Steinlauf |first=Michael C. |author-link=Michael C. Steinlauf |title=Bondage to the Dead: Poland and the Memory of the Holocaust |year=1997 |publisher=Syracuse University Press |location=Syracuse|isbn=0-8156-2729-7 |ref=harv}}\n* [[Dariusz Stola|Stola, Dariusz]]. (2003). \"Jedwabne: Revisiting the Evidence and Nature of the Crime\". ''[[Holocaust and Genocide Studies]]''. 17 (1):139\u2013152.\n* {{cite journal |last=Strzembosz |first=Tomasz |journal=Yad Vashem Studies |volume=XXX |year=2002 |pages=7\u201320 |url=http://www.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/Microsoft%20Word%20-%205416.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805073550/http://www.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/Microsoft%20Word%20-%205416.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 August 2011 |title=Thoughts on Professors Gutman's Diary|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Tec |first=Nechama |author-link=Nechama Tec |title=Defiance: The Bielski Partisans | year=1993| publisher=Oxford University Press | location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-509390-2 |ref=harv}}\n* Weinbaum, Laurence (2002). Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs, [http://www.jcpa.org/phas/phas-weinbaum-f02.htm  Penitence and Prejudice: The Roman Catholic Church and Jedwabne] ''Jewish Political Studies Review'' 14:3-4. Fall 2002.\n* {{cite book |last=Wierzbicki |first=Marek |editor1-first=Elazar |editor1-last=Barkan |editor2-first=Elizabeth A. |editor2-last=Cole |editor3-first=Kai |editor3-last=Struve |title=Shared History, Divided Memory: Jews and Others in Soviet-occupied Poland, 1939\u20131941 |isbn=978-3865832405 |pages= |year=2007 |publisher=Leipziger Universit\u00e4tsverlag |chapter=Western Belarus in September 1939: Revisiting Polish-Jewish Relations in the ''kresy''|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Wolentarska-Ochman|first=Ewa|date=2006|title=Collective Remembrance in Jedwabne: Unsettled Memory of World War II in Postcommunist Poland|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/10.2979/his.2006.18.1.152.pdf |journal=History and Memory|volume=18|issue=1|pages=152\u2013178|doi=10.2979/his.2006.18.1.152|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wr\u00f3bel |first1=Piotr |author-link=Piotr Wr\u00f3bel |editor1-last=Hayes |editor1-first=Peter |editor2-last=Herzog |editor2-first=Dagmar |editor1-link=Peter Hayes (historian) |editor2-link=Dagmar Herzog |title=Lessons and Legacies: The Holocaust in International Perspective, Volume VII |date=2006a |publisher=Northwestern University Press |location=Evanston |isbn=0-8101-2370-3 |pages=387 |ref=harv |chapter=Polish-Jewish Relations and ''Neighbors'' by Jan T. Gross: Politics, Public Opinion and Historical Methodology}}\n* {{cite journal | last1=Wr\u00f3bel| first1=Piotr | title=The Massacre in Jedwabne, July 10, 1941: Before, During, and After| journal=The Sarmatian Review| volume=26| issue=3| url=http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~sarmatia/906/263wrobel.html |pages=1238\u20131241| year=2006b| ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* {{cite book | first = Jan T. | last = Gross | title = S\u0105siedzi: Historia zag\u0142ady \u017cydowskiego miasteczka | language = Polish | year = 2000 | publisher = Pogranicze | location = Sejny | isbn = 978-83-86872-13-8 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Gross | first = Jan T. | authorlink =| title = Wok\u00f3\u0142 S\u0105siad\u00f3w. Polemiki i wyja\u015bnienia | publisher = Pogranicze | language = Polish | location = Sejny | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-83-86872-48-0 }}\n* Gr\u00fcnberg, Slawomir (2005). ''The Legacy of Jedwabne''. Spencer, New York: LogTV (documentary)\n* {{cite book |title=Poland 1939\u20131945. Casualties and the Victims of Repressions under the Nazi and the Soviet Occupations |trans-title=Polska 1939\u20131945. Straty osobowe i ofiary represji pod dwiema okupacjami |last1=Materski |first1=Wojciech |last2=Szarota |first2=Tomasz |author-link2=Tomasz Szarota |year=2009 |publisher=[[Institute of National Remembrance]] |isbn=978-83-7629-067-6}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}}\n{{Massacres or pogroms against Jews}}\n{{Coord|53.288792|N|22.309542|E|source:plwiki_region:PL|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jedwabne pogrom}}\n[[Category:1941 in Judaism]]\n[[Category:1941 in Poland]]\n[[Category:Controversies in Poland]]\n[[Category:Holocaust massacres and pogroms in Poland]]\n[[Category:July 1941 events]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1941]]\n[[Category:Poland in World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II crimes in Poland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1941 massacre of Jews in Poland}}\n[[File:Pogrom w Jedwabnem Muzeum Historii \u017byd\u00f3w Polskich.JPG|thumb|upright=1.3|Jedwabne memorial, [[POLIN Museum of the History of Polish Jews]], Warsaw]]\n\nThe '''Jedwabne pogrom''' ({{lang-pl|Pogrom w Jedwabnem}}, {{IPA-pl|j\u025bd\u02c8vabn\u025b|pron}}) was a massacre of [[Polish Jews]] in the town of [[Jedwabne]], [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German-occupied Poland]], on 10 July 1941, during [[World War II]].{{sfn|Cesarani|2016|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=mimNBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA371 371]}}\n\nAt least 340 men, women and children were murdered, some 300 of whom were locked in a barn that was set on fire.<ref>For 300, see {{harvnb|Musial|2003|p=300}}.</ref> About 40 ethnic Poles were implicated in the murders.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=229}} German police were present in the town.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=229}}{{efn|[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]]: \"On July 10, 1941, Polish residents of Jedwabne, a small town located in Bialystok District of first Soviet-occupied and then German-occupied Poland, participated in the murder of hundreds of their Jewish neighbors. Although responsibility for instigating this 'pogrom' has not been fully established, scholars have documented at least a German police presence in the town at the time of the killings.\"<ref>[https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005183 \"Pogroms\"]. ''Holocaust Encyclopedia''. United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n===Jedwabne===\n[[File:Jedwabne Synagogue.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Jedwabne Synagogue]] before 1913]]\nThe Jewish community in [[Jedwabne]] was established in the 17th or 18th century.{{sfn|Baker|Tzinovitz|1980|p=5}} There were approximately 1,500 Jews out of a population of 2,167 in Jedwabne in the 1930s.<ref>[http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/printarticle.aspx?id=466 \"Jedwabne\"]. YIVO Encyclopedia.</ref> It was a typical [[shtetl]], a small town with a majority Jewish community coexistent with its Polish minority and surrounded by majority Polish countryside, one of many such towns in [[Second Polish Republic|prewar Poland]]. The region politically supported the right-wing [[National Democracy|National Democrats]],{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=18}} who sought to counter what they said was Jewish economic competition against Catholic Poles, and opposed the Polish socialist government of [[J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski]] and his successors. Nevertheless, there were good prewar Polish-Jewish relations in the town, possibly better than elsewhere in the country. At their most tense, a 1934 rumor that drew a connection between the killing of a Jewish woman and the killing of a Catholic man was quashed by a priest and a rabbi addressing the matter together, before it escalated.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=19}}\n\nResidents of Jedwabne had memory of the nearby [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom#Background|Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom]] of 1933, organized by [[National Democracy]]'s far-right faction, the [[Camp of Great Poland]] (OWP). The organization referred to the violence as a \"revolution\" against the Polish state, which it saw as a protector of Jews. One Jew was killed by the pogromists and four pogromists were killed by the Polish police; the OWP was then banned by Poland in 1934 for anti-state and racist activities.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|p=9}}\n\nAccording to [[Anna Bikont]], archival documents show Poland's government at this time was hostile to the Polish nationalist movement, because of the latter's attacks on Jews as well as its opposition to the Polish state; the government felt responsible for Jews and tried to protect them (arresting violent nationalists) and it perceived Jews as trying to show loyalty to the Polish state.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|p=31}} \n\n===World War II===\nThe start of [[European Theatre of World War II|World War II in Europe]] began with the [[Invasion of Poland (1939)|invasion of Poland]] by [[Nazi Germany]] on 1 September 1939. Later in the same month, on 17 September, the Soviet [[Red Army]] [[Soviet invasion of Poland (1939)|invaded]] the [[Kresy|eastern regions of Poland]] under the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]].{{sfn|Kitchen|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QAStAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA74 74]}} {{efn|\"The generals of the two invading armies went over the details of the prearranged line that would mark the two zones of conquest for Germany and Soviet Russia, subsequently to be rearranged one more time in Moscow. The military parade that followed was recorded by Nazi cameras and celebrated in the German newsreel: German and Soviet generals cheek by jowl in military homage to each other's armies and victories.\"{{sfn|Raack|1995|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=pAdZMaWn8cIC&pg=PA58 58]}}}} The area of Jedwabne was originally occupied by the Germans, who crushed local resistance and burned the synagogue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,76842,173800.html|title=Dokumenty, o\u015bwiadczenia, wyst\u0105pienia publiczne dotycz\u0105ce mordu w Jedwabnem|last=|first=|date=8 March 2001|work=Gazeta Wyborcza}}</ref> Jedwabne was then transferred to the Soviets in accordance with the [[German\u2013Soviet Boundary and Friendship Treaty|German\u2013Soviet Boundary Treaty]] of 28 September 1939. At first, many [[Polish Jews]] were relieved to learn that the Soviets, rather than the Nazis, were to occupy their town. Unlike most ethnic Poles, some Jews prominently welcomed the [[Red Army]] as protectors from Nazism, as did other ethnic groups in the ''[[Kresy]]'' (Polish borderlands), particularly [[Belarusians]].{{sfn|Tec|1993}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} In what [[Jan Gross]] has termed \"the institutionalization of resentment\", the occupiers used privileges and punishments to accommodate and encourage ethnic and religious differences among the local population.{{sfn|Holc|2002|p=454}}\n\nAccording to Anna Bikont, the Soviets brought in Russian and atheistic anti-religious policies: Poland's Hebrew schools were shut by the Soviets, who banned holy days that Poland had recognized, such as [[Yom Kippur]], and appropriated shops and businesses, which were mostly Jewish.{{sfn|Bikont|2015|pp=146\u2013148}} Some Jews and Belarusians formed militias (known as ''\"opaskowcy\"'' for their red armbands).{{sfn|Wierzbicki|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_BbvQbiaqAEC&pg=PA151 151]}} Local people said Jews had helped the [[NKVD]] compile lists of Poles to be sent to the \"Soviet interior\".{{sfn|Strzembosz|2002|p=6}} A total of 22,353 Poles (entire families) were deported from the vicinity.{{efn|\"Following his detailed Report of the Jedwabne Investigation, [[Leon Kieres]] responds to questions from the Senate. Statement by Senator Jadwiga Stokarska (translation): 'With the Soviet arrival, Poles were laid off immediately, and all administrative offices, including municipal, were staffed by Jews who were also handed out weapons and formed the local militia. Many joined the [[NKVD]], the [[Komsomol]] and the Bolshevik Party, compiled the list of Poles to be sent to Siberia, and performed their deportations directly.' Original: 'Po wej\u015bciu Rosjan natychmiast z urz\u0119d\u00f3w zwolniono Polak\u00f3w i wszystkie urz\u0119dy, \u0142\u0105cznie z miejskim, obsadzili \u017bydzi. Otrzymali oni od Rosjan bro\u0144 i utworzyli miejscow\u0105 milicj\u0119. Sporo m\u0142odych \u017byd\u00f3w wst\u0105pi\u0142o do NKWD, do Komsomo\u0142u, do partii bolszewickiej. W Jedwabnem \u017bydzi utworzyli list\u0119 Polak\u00f3w do wyw\u00f3zki na Sybir i bezpo\u015brednio j\u0105 nadzorowali.'<ref name=\"Senat_RP\">{{cite web |last=Stokarska |first=Jadwiga |title=90. posiedzenie Senatu RP [90th session of the Senate of the Republic of Poland] |language=pl |url=http://ww2.senat.pl/k4/dok/sten/090/22.HTM |publisher=The Senate of the Republic of Poland |website=ww2.senat.pl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018225107/http://ww2.senat.pl/k4/dok/sten/090/22.HTM |url-status=live |date=23 April 2008 |archive-date=18 October 2014}}</ref>}} Red Army troops requisitioned food and other goods, depriving the local populace of resources.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} The [[NKVD|Soviet secret police]] (NKVD) accompanying the [[Red Army]] routinely arrested and deported Polish citizens, both gentiles and Jews, and spread terror throughout the region.{{sfn|Pinchuk|2003|pp=67\u201368}}\n\nFollowing Germany's [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]] on 22 June 1941, German forces overran the parts of [[Poland]] that had been occupied by the Soviets since 1939. The Nazis distributed antisemitic propaganda, and there were reports that Jews had welcomed the Soviets, which \"strengthened the widely held stereotype of Judaeo-communism which had been promoted by right-wing parties before the war\".{{sfn|Lukowski|Zawadzki|2019|p=334}} In parallel, the [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] organized special ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]'' (\"task forces\") to murder Jews in these areas, and a few massacres were carried out. The guidelines for such massacres were formulated by [[Reinhard Heydrich]],{{sfn|Browning|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=d9Wg4gjtP3cC&pg=PA262 262]}} who ordered his officers to induce anti-Jewish incidents in the territories newly occupied by the German forces, including pogroms. \"Hooliganism set the tone\", according to [[Michael C. Steinlauf]].{{sfn|Steinlauf|1997|p=31}}\n\nThree days into the invasion, six Poles (three ethnic Poles and three Jews) who had collaborators with the Soviets were lynched in Jedwabne. Some accounts say they were first beaten or tortured by the locals, then shot by the Germans. The same day, two wives of Jewish activists for the Soviets who had evacuated with the Red Army committed suicide with their children. Other Jews faced robberies and attacks, which the Germans tolerated. Antisemitic violence broke out in pogroms across the newly German-occupied [[Podlasie]] region.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} In the first days of the occupation of Jedwabne, the Germans set up a Field Gendarmerie (''[[Feldgendarmerie#Operations|Feldgendarmerie]]''), staffed by 8 or 11 military police, according to different testimonies. These established cooperation with a new town council, headed by the brother-in-law of a previous mayor, Marian Karolak. Scholars say it is likely that the Germans consented to the formation of a Polish volunteer [[town guard]]. Some of these may have been resistance fighters during the Soviet occupation who later joined the German auxiliary police, because Polish testimonials refer to them as ''szucman'', from ''[[Schutzmannschaft]]''.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Pogroms===\nPolish villagers participated in massacres of Jews, with varying degrees of German involvement, in 23 localities of the \u0141om\u017ca and Bia\u0142ystok areas of the [[Podlasie]] region after the occupation. Generally smaller massacres took place at [[Bielsk Podlaski]] (the village of Pilki), [[Choroszcz]], [[Czy\u017cew]], [[Goni\u0105dz]], [[Grajewo]], [[Jasion\u00f3wka]], [[Kleszczele]], [[Knyszyn]], [[Kolno]], [[Ku\u017anica, Podlaskie Voivodeship|Ku\u017anica]], [[Narewka]], [[Pi\u0105tnica]], [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w]], [[Rajgr\u00f3d]], [[Soko\u0142y, Wysokie Mazowieckie County|Soko\u0142y]], [[Stawiski]], [[Suchowola]], [[Szczuczyn]], [[Trzcianne]], [[Tykocin]], [[Wasilk\u00f3w]], [[W\u0105sosz]], and [[Wizna]].<ref>[http://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/09/pogrom-in-jedwabne-course-of-events \"Pogrom in Jedwabne: Course of Events]. Polin. Museum of the History of Polish Jews, 9 July 2016; accessed 2 April 2018.</ref> In the days before the Jedwabne massacre, the town's Jewish population increased as refugees arrived from nearby Radzi\u0142\u00f3w and Wizna. In Wizna, the town's Polish \"civil head\" had ordered the Jewish community's expulsion; 230\u2013240 Jews fled to Jedwabne.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=900}} On 7 July 1941, during the [[Radzi\u0142\u00f3w pogrom]], local Poles are reported to have murdered 800 Jews, 500 of whom were burned in a barn. The murders took place after the Gestapo had arrived in the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/09/timeline-of-pogroms-in-the-former-soviet-occupation-zone-summer|title=Timeline of pogroms in the former Soviet occupation zone \u2013 summer of 1941|publisher=POLIN, Museum of the History of Polish Jews}}</ref> When the German occupying forces began establishing their new regime, they gave the Poles of Jedwabne \"a few days to 'self-cleanse' the town of Jews\".{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Jedwabne pogrom==\n===10 July 1941===\n[[File:1941 atrocity in Jedwabne (map).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=diagram|Jedwabne crime scene, compiled from Polish court documents{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}]]\n\nJews were taken to a square in the center of Jedwabne, where they were ordered to weed the area by pulling grass up from between the stones. They were beaten by a group of ethnic Poles.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}} A group of around 40 Jewish men was forced to demolish a statue of [[Vladimir Lenin|Lenin]] that had been put up by the Soviets and carry it out of town on a wooden stretcher while singing Soviet songs. The local [[rabbi]], Awigdor Bia\u0142ostocki, was made to lead the procession, which included the kosher butcher. The group was taken to a barn,<ref name=\"Senat_RP\"/> killed, and buried together with fragments of the statue. There are varying theories about the manner of the killing, and varying witness testimonies as to whether the Germans were present at the barn and whether they took part in escorting the Jews from the square to the barn.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nAfter the men had been killed, most of Jedwabne's remaining Jews, estimated at some 250<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" /> to 300 ([[Institute of National Remembrance|IPN]] final findings),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |title=Postanowienie o umorzeniu sledztwa (\"Final findings\") |publisher=Institute of National Remembrance|date=30 June 2001|accessdate=14 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114125013/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |archivedate=14 November 2012 }}</ref> were led to the same barn, locked inside, and burned alive using [[kerosene]] from former Soviet supplies (or, by other accounts, German gasoline). The remains of both groups were buried in two [[mass grave]]s in the barn.<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" /> The victims included women, children, and infants.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\n===Roles===\nThere is general agreement that German secret police officials were seen in Jedwabne on the morning of 10 July 1941 and met with the town authorities. Testimony quoted by Gross (2001) says they were [[Gestapo]] and that there eight of them,{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=18}} while Persak (2011) says they were probably German Security Police or Security Service (''[[Sicherheitspolizei]]'' or ''[[Sicherheitsdienst]]'').{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (IPN) criminal investigation, ''S1/00/Zn'', concluded in 2002 that on the same morning Polish men from nearby villages began arriving in Jedwabne \"with the intention of participating in the premeditated murder of the Jewish inhabitants of the town\". The IPN found that some Jews were alerted by non-Jewish neighbors to what was happening.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nAccording to another account, by historian [[Tomasz Strzembosz]], the men from nearby villages arrived by order of the German-appointed Jedwabne mayor Marian Karolak and the German paramilitaries billeted to the town (''[[Feldgendarmerie#Operations|Feldgendarmerie]]'').{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} a group of Polish men from Jedwabne and neighboring settlements was assembled who, under German supervision, rounded up local Jews and Jews seeking refuge there from nearby towns and villages such as Wizna and [[Kolno]].{{efn|\"A separate problem concerns the townsmen who had been named during the interrogations conducted by the Security Office [''UB''] functionaries. That is because, on this point, the statements were all retracted in court as having been obtained through torture.\" Polish-language original text: \"Osobnym problemem s\u0105 mieszka\u0144cy miasteczka wymieniani podczas zezna\u0144 sk\u0142adanych na r\u0119ce funkcjonariuszy Urz\u0119du Bezpiecze\u0144stwa. A to z tego powodu, \u017ce zeznania te, w\u0142a\u015bnie w tym punkcie, by\u0142y gremialnie odwo\u0142ywane na sali s\u0105dowej jako wymuszone torturami.\"<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\">{{cite news |last=Strzembosz |first=Tomasz |author-link=Tomasz Strzembosz |trans-title=Inny obraz s\u0105siad\u00f3w |title=A different picture of neighbors |url=http://www.rzeczpospolita.pl/gazeta/wydanie_010331/publicystyka/publicystyka_a_2.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010610072611/http://www.rzeczpospolita.pl/gazeta/wydanie_010331/publicystyka/publicystyka_a_2.html |archive-date=10 June 2001 |work =[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]] |date=31 March 2001 |volume=77|access-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Jan Gross]] writes that a leading role in the pogrom was carried out by four men, including Jerzy Lauda\u0144ski and Karol Bardo\u0144, who had earlier collaborated with the Soviet [[NKVD]] and were now trying to recast themselves as zealous collaborators with the Germans.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=75}} He also says: \"At the time, the undisputed bosses over life and death in Jedwabne were the Germans. No sustained organized activity could take place there without their consent. They were the only ones who could decide the fate of the Jews. It was within their power also to stop the murderous pogrom at any time. And they did not choose to intervene. ... But it is also clear that had Jedwabne not been occupied by the Germans, the Jews of Jedwabne would not have been murdered by their neighbors.\"{{sfn|Gross|2001|pp=46\u201347}}\n\nAccording to [[Peter Longerich]], \"closer analysis of the crime\" shows that the pogrom was \"engineered by a unit of the German Security Police\", probably a unit from the [[Zichenau]] [[Gestapo]] office that had been assigned to ''[[Einsatzgruppe B]]'', and which \"had recruited local Poles as auxiliary 'pogrom police'\".{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=196}} Krzysztof Persak writes that the Jedwabne pograom and some 30 others happened at a special time and place: around [[\u0141om\u017ca]] and western [[Bia\u0142ystok]] was one of the few Polish majority areas that had just undergone the cruelty of Soviet occupation since 1939. They therefore saw Germans as liberators when they arrived in 1941; paired with historical antisemitism, the conditions were right for German incitement according to the [[Reich Main Security Office]] directive on \"folk pogroms\" of 29 June.{{sfn|Persak|2011}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}<!--primary sources: Several Jewish eyewitnesses reported that the Germans were directly involved in rounding up and abusing Jews in the town square, and that they shot at Jews who tried to escape from the burning barn. According to a diary penned during the war, citing reports by Jews who fled Jedwabne and Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, \"With the help of local farmers, the Germans gathered the Jews of these places, the rabbi and community leaders foremost, in the market square. At first, they beat them cruelly and forced them to wrap themselves in their ''[[tallitot]]'' and to jump and dance, accompanied by singing. All this was done under an unceasing stream of blows from cudgels and rubber whips.  Finally, they pushed all the Jews, beating and kicking them, into a long threshing house and set it on fire with them inside.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HHstAQAAIAAJ |title=Deliverance. The diary of Michael Maik: A True Story|last=Maik|first=Michael|last2=Ben-Dov|first2=Avigdor|last3=Ben-Dov|first3=Laia|date=2004|publisher=Avigdor and Laia Ben-Dov|isbn=9789659070107|location=|pages=38\u201339|language=en}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=April 2020}}\n\nAccording to a memorial book first published in Hebrew in 1963, \"The Jews who came from the towns told us terrible things. Rywka Kurc [who had managed to escape from Jedwabne (and is] now in Australia) told us that in Jedwabne, the S.S. enclosed all the Jews in a hayloft\u2014men, women, children and old people, among them her husband and two children. They set fire to the building and everyone was burned alive.\"<ref>Yitzchak Ivri, ed., ''Book of Kehilat Ostrolenka: Yizkor Book of the Jewish Community of Ostrolenka'', Tel Aviv, Irgun Yotzei Ostrolenka in Israel, 2009, p. 384.</ref>  According to another former Jedwabne resident who, shortly after the massacre, met Jews who had fled Jedwabne, they \"told us when the Germans first entered their town, they had herded all the Jews into a barn and set it ablaze. Anyone who tried to get out was cut down by machine-gun fire.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PsAY9uwZkmEC&printsec=frontcover |title=The Warriors: My Life As A Jewish Soviet Partisan|last=Zissman|first=Harold|date=2005|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=9780815608394|language=en}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=April 2020}}-->\n\n===Survivors===\n[[File:Antonina-Boruch-Wyrzykowska_fot_Adam-Hayder.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Antonina Wyrzykowska]] in 2007]]\nSeveral witnesses reported seeing German photographers take pictures of the massacre. There was also speculation that the pogrom was filmed.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\nBetween 100 and 125 Jews who had escaped the massacre returned to Jedwabne. They resided in an open ghetto before being transferred to the \u0141om\u017ca ghetto in November 1942. Several escaped to other towns.{{sfn|Chodakiewicz|2005|p=88}} In November 1942, when the Germans began putting ghetto inmates on trains to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] for extermination, seven of them escaped again to the nearby hamlet of [[Janczewko]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} There Polish farmer [[Antonina Wyrzykowska]] and her husband, Aleksander Wyrzykowski, hid them on their farm from November 1942 to January 1945, despite hostility from neighbors and German searches of their property.<ref name=RadioPoland2Dec2011/> The fugitives included Moshe Olszewicz, his wife, Lea, and his brother, Dov; Jacob and Lea Kubran; and J\u00f3zef Gr\u0105dowski; and Szmuel Wasersztajn.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Wasersztajn later provided testimony about the massacre.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}\n\nAfter the war, the Wyrzykowskis were physically assaulted by local people for having helped Jews. The couple eventually moved to [[Milan\u00f3wek]], near Warsaw,<ref name=RadioPoland2Dec2011>{{Cite web | url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/59542,Woman-who-helped-Jedwabne-Jews-dies | title=Woman who helped Jedwabne Jews dies |publisher=Radio Poland |date=2 December 2011}}</ref> In 1976 they were awarded Israel's [[Righteous Among the Nations|Righteous among the Nations]] medal.<ref>[http://db.yadvashem.org/righteous/family.html?language=en&itemId=4035463 \"Wyrzykowski Aleksander & Wyrzykowska Antonina (Karwowska)\"]. The Righteous Among Nations database, Yad Vashem.</ref><ref>[http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/59542,Woman-who-helped-Jedwabne-Jews-dies \"Woman who helped Jedwabne Jews dies\"]. ''The News'', Radio Poland, 12 February 2011; accessed 2 April 2018.</ref> Antonina Wyrzykowska was later also decorated with the Commander's Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] by Poland's President [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==1949\u20131950 trials==\n{{seealso|People's Republic of Poland}}\n[[File:A-438 Mogi\u0142a-pomnik, na cmentarzu \u017cydowskim, 1941 Jedwabne B&W.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Pogrom memorial in Jedwabne]]\nAfter the war, in 1949 and 1950, 22<!--or 23?--> suspects from the town and vicinity were put on trial in Poland, accused of collaborating with the Germans during the pogrom. None of the defendants had a higher education and three were illiterate.{{sfn|Shore|2005}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Twelve were convicted of [[treason]] against Poland and one was condemned to death.<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\"/>\n\nRecords show that extreme physical torture applied during pre-trial interrogation by the [[Ministry of Public Security (Poland)|Security Office (UB)]] caused some of the men to confess to criminal acts\u2014confessions they later retracted in court. Those who retracted included J\u00f3zef Chrzanowski, Marian \u017byluk, Czes\u0142aw Lauda\u0144ski, Wincenty Go\u015bcicki, Roman and Jan Zawadzki, Aleksander and Franciszek \u0141ojewski, Eugeniusz \u015aliwecki, Stanis\u0142aw Sielawa, and several others, who were pronounced innocent and released by the court.<ref name=\"Tomasz Strzembosz\" />{{clarify|date=April 2020}}<!--source doesn't say this: The illegal interrogation methods were confirmed{{when|date=March 2018}} by Minister of Public Security [[Ministry of Public Security of Poland|Stanis\u0142aw Radkiewicz]], who admitted in an internal memo that the \"fixing\" of the investigation had included beatings and the rephrasing of testimony to aid the prosecution.{{sfn|Musial|2003|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=a_49GjK8ovMC&pg=PA306 306]}}-->\n\nNone of the Polish people who had rescued Jews in Jedwabne were contacted, and no attempt was made to establish the names of the victims. There was no search for the mayor, Marian Karolak, who had vanished, and no effort to name the German units present in the town at the time. The courts did confirm that the defendants' participation had been coerced by German police threats and acts of physical violence.<ref>[[Pawe\u0142 Machcewicz|Machcewicz, Pawel]] (2002). ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (\"Jedwabne and Beyond\"). Translated by Christina Manetti. Warsaw: Institute of National Remembrance. {{isbn|978-8389078087}}</ref>{{request quotation|date=April 2020}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}<!--volume number needed-->\n\n==German investigation, 1960\u20131965==\n''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Wolfgang Birkner]] was investigated by prosecutors in West Germany in 1960 on suspicion of involvement in the massacres of Jews in Jedwabne, Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, and W\u0105sosz in 1941. The charges were based on research by [[Szymon Datner]], head of the [[Bia\u0142ystok]] branch of the [[Central Committee of Polish Jews]] (C\u017bKH). The German prosecutors found no hard evidence implicating Birkner, but in the course of their investigation they discovered a new German witness, the former SS ''Kreiskommissar'' of \u0141om\u017ca, who named the paramilitary [[Einsatzgruppe B]] under SS-Obersturmf\u00fchrer [[Hermann Schaper]] as having been deployed in the area at the time of the pogroms. The methods used by Schaper's death squad in the Radzi\u0142\u00f3w massacre were identical to those employed in Jedwabne only three days later, suggesting they had been involved in the second pogrom.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn 1963 a monument to the victims was placed in Jedwabne by the Polish communist state's ''[[Society of Fighters for Freedom and Democracy]]''. Its inscription read: \"The place of destruction of the Jewish population. Here Gestapo and Nazi gendarmes burnt alive 1600 people on 10 July 1941.\"{{sfn|Michlic|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} During the subsequent German investigation at [[Ludwigsburg]] in 1964, Hermann Schaper lied to interrogators, claiming that in 1941 he had been a truck driver. Legal proceedings against the accused were terminated on 2 September 1965, but Schaper's case was reopened in 1974. During the second investigation, Count van der Groeben testified that it was indeed Schaper who had conducted mass executions of Jews in his district. In 1976 a court in [[Giessen]] pronounced Schaper guilty of the execution of Poles and Jews by the kommando SS [[Ciechan\u00f3w|Zichenau]]-[[P\u0142ock|Schr\u00f6ttersburg]].{{clarify|date=April 2020}}{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} Schaper was sentenced to six years imprisonment, but was soon released for medical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Urban |first1=Thomas |title=Poszukiwany Hermann Schaper |work=[[Rzeczpospolita (newspaper)|Rzeczpospolita]] |date=1 September 2001 |url=https://archiwum.rp.pl/artykul/351399-Poszukiwany--Hermann-Schaper.html}}</ref> According to German federal prosecutors, the documentation of his investigation has most likely been destroyed.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''Neighbors'' by Jan T. Gross (2001)==\n{{Main|Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland}}\n[[File:Jan Tomasz Gross.png|thumb|[[Jan T. Gross]], 2019]]\n[[Jan T. Gross]]'s book ''S\u0105siedzi: Historia zag\u0142ady \u017cydowskiego miasteczka'' (\"Neighbors: The Story of the Annihilation of a Jewish Town\") caused a \"moral earthquake\" when it was published in Poland in May 2000, according to [[Piotr Wr\u00f3bel]]. The book appeared in English in April 2001 as ''Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland''.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=387}} Writing that \"one day, in July 1941, half of the population of a small East European town murdered the other half\u2014some 1,600 men, women and children\", Gross concluded that the Jedwabne Jews had been rounded up and killed by a mob of their own Polish neighbors.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=7}} This ran contrary to the official account that they had been killed by Germans.<ref name=Kauffmann19Dec2002>{{cite news|first=Sylvie |last=Kauffmann |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2002/dec/19/highereducation.news |title=Poland faces up to the horror of its own role in the Holocaust|newspaper=The Guardian |date= 19 December 2002}}</ref> \n \nGross recognized that German occupying forces had control of the town: \"At the time, the undisputed bosses over life and death in Jedwabne were the Germans. No sustained organized activity could take place there without their consent.\"{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=47}} He concluded that the massacre was carried out entirely by Poles from Jedwabne and the surrounding area,<!-- insufficient referencing --> and that the Polish perpetrators had not been coerced by the Germans.{{sfn|Gross|2001|p=133}}<!-- insufficient referencing --> One of his principal sources was Szmul Wasersztajn, a witness whose testimony had been deposited in 1945 at the [[Jewish Historical Institute]] in Warsaw. Other sources were Stalinist investigation affidavits and records of the 1949\u20131950 trials; a 1980 book, ''Yedwabne: History and Memorial Book''; and interviews from the 1990s conducted by Gross and a filmmaker.{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}\n\nWhile several Polish historians praised Gross for having drawn attention to the pogrom, others criticized him for relying too heavily on these accounts, which they argued were not reliable, and\u2014where conflicting accounts existed\u2014for choosing those that showed the Poles in the worst possible light.<ref>{{harvnb|Chodakiewicz|2001}}; {{harvnb|Musial|2003|p=334}}; for not reliable, {{harvnb|Wr\u00f3bel|2006a|p=391}}.</ref>{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n\n==IPN investigation, 2000\u20132003==\n===Reasons===\nIn July 2000, following the publication of Gross's book and the ensuing debate, the Polish parliament ordered a new investigation into the pogrom. Parliament charged the [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (''Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej'', or IPN) with transmitting its findings for possible legal action. The IPN had recently been created as an independent successor to the Commission for the Investigation of Nazi Crimes in Poland, formed after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Its major role was the promotion of historical research on topics that had been banned for over 40 years under communist rule (1945\u20131989), including pogroms.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAlthough Gross's book was the catalyst for the investigation, the first scholarly analysis of the pogrom was by [[Szymon Datner]] for the [[Jewish Historical Institute]] in December 1966, and it had reached similar conclusions.<ref name=\"ipn.gov.pl195\"/>{{sfn|Polonsky|Michlic|2003|p=452}}\n\n===Proceedings===\nOver the course of two years, IPN investigators interviewed some 111 witnesses, mainly from Poland, but also from Israel and the United States.<ref name=\"ipn.gov.pl195\">{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=Manslaughter of Jewish Inhabitants of Jedwabne |url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal/en/19/195/Manslaughter_of_Jewish_Inhabitants_of_Jedwabne.html |website= |date=18 November 2003 |publisher=Institute of National Remembrance |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009223428/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal/en/19/195/Manslaughter_of_Jewish_Inhabitants_of_Jedwabne.html |archivedate=9 October 2012 |location=Warsaw |url-status=dead}}</ref> One-third of the IPN witnesses had been eyewitnesses of some part of the pogrom. Since the event had occurred 59 years earlier, when most of the survivors still living today were children, their recollections varied. The IPN also searched for and examined documents in Polish archives in Warsaw, Bia\u0142ystok and \u0141om\u017ca, in German archives, and at Yad Vashem in Israel.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nIn May\u2013June 2001 the IPN conducted a partial exhumation at the site of the barn, where the largest number of victims died. Based on a similar exhumation at [[Katyn massacre|Katyn]], where Stalin's forces murdered 22,000 Polish prisoners of war in 1940, the IPN's forensic examiner estimated that the burial site in Jedwabne contained the remains of between 300 and 400 victims.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}<ref name=\"jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf\">{{cite web |title=Postanowienie |url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |website=www.ipn.gov.pl|publisher=Institute of National Remembrance (IPN) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114125013/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |archivedate=14 November 2012 |date=30 June 2003 |url-status=live}}</ref> There were charred bodies in two mass graves, and also broken pieces of the bust of Lenin (previously assumed to have been buried at a Jewish cemetery).{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} The scope of the exhumation was restricted because of religious objections to disturbing the remains.{{sfn|Gross|2002}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} Rabbi Joseph Polak also took issue with the decision, asserting that Jewish law required the bodies to be reinterred in a proper burial ground.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://traditionarchive.org/news/originals/Volume%2035/No.%204/Exhuming%20Their%20Neighbors.pdf|title=Exhuming Their Neighbors: A Halakhic Inquiry|last=Polak|first=Joseph A.|journal=Tradition: A Journal of Orthodox Jewish Thought|volume=35|number=4|date=Winter 2001|pages=23\u201343|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeon Kieres, the President of IPN, met in New York with Rabbi Jacob Baker,<ref>Rabbi Jacob Baker, [http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/J/Baker.html  \"We Trusted Each Other\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051659/http://info-poland.buffalo.edu/classroom/J/Baker.html |date=4 March 2016 }} Polish Academic Information Center, University of Buffalo.</ref> formerly Yaakov Eliezer Piekarz, who had emigrated in 1938 from Jedwabne to the United States. In January 2001, during his visit to New York, Kieres said that IPN had accumulated enough evidence to confirm that a group of Poles were the perpetrators of the Jedwabne massacre. The IPN's evidence was presented to the Polish Parliament and in other public statements.<ref name=\"Senat_RP\" />  While the investigation continued for two more years, the finding of Polish involvement in the Jedwabne massacre became public knowledge in Poland in early 2001.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} In June that year, the IPN said ammunition shells recovered from the site were German, prompting speculation that German soldiers had \ufb01red at Jews fleeing the barn. About six months later, the IPN found that the shells were from a different historical period.{{sfn|Michlic|2012|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BfQoxsH9bbwC&pg=PA81 81]}}{{sfn|Wolentarska-Ochman|2006}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===IPN's findings, 2002\u20132003===\n[[File:Le m\u00e9morial du pogrom de Jedwabne.jpg|thumb|upright=1.6|Jedwabne memorial, 2011]]\nOn 9 July 2002 the IPN released the findings of its two-year investigation, \"Findings of Investigation S 1 / 00 / Zn into the Murder of Polish Citizens of Jewish Origin in the Town of Jedwabne on 10 July 1941\".{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.warsawvoice.pl/WVpage/pages/article.php/2968/article |title=Insight Into Tragedy |work=The Warsaw Voice |date=17 July 2003 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303021458/http://www.warsawvoice.pl/WVpage/pages/article.php/2968/article |archivedate=3 March 2011}}</ref> Chief prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew wrote:\n\n* The perpetrators of the crime ''sensu stricto'' were about 40 male \"Polish inhabitants of Jedwabne and its environs\". Responsibility for the crime ''sensu largo'' could be ascribed to the Germans because of the presence of German military policemen at the Jedwabne police station. Their presence, \"though passive, was tantamount to consent to and tolerance of the crime against the Jewish inhabitants of the town\".{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA135 135]}} The IPN found that Poles played a \"decisive role\" in the massacre, but the massacre was \"instigated by the Germans\". The massacre was carried out in full view of the Germans, who were armed and had control of the town, and the Germans did not intervene and halt the killings.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* At least 340 Jewish victims were killed in the pogrom, in two groups of which the first contained 40 to 50 men, and the second about 300 persons. The exact number of victims could not be determined. The previously estimated figure of 1,600 was \"highly unlikely, and was not confirmed in the course of the investigation.{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n* \"At least forty (Polish) men\" were perpetrators of the crime. The majority of Jedwabne residents were \"utterly passive,\" the IPN found, and did not participate in the massacre. The IPN wrote: \"On the basis of the evidence gathered in the investigation, it is not possible to determine the reasons for the passivity of most of the town in the face of the crime. In particular, it cannot be determined whether this passivity resulted from acceptance of the crime or from intimidation by the brutality of the perpetrators' acts.\"{{sfn|Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 134]}}\n* A number of witnesses had testified that the Germans drove the group of Jewish victims from Jedwabne's town square to the barn where they were killed (these testimonies are found in the expanded 203-page ''Findings'' published in June 2003). IPN could neither conclusively prove nor disprove these accounts. \"Witness testimonies vary considerably on this question.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* \"A group of Jewish people survived\" the massacre. Several dozen \u2014 according to several sources, about a hundred \u2014 Jews lived in a ghetto in Jedwabne until November 1942, when they were transferred by the Germans to a ghetto in \u0141om\u017ca, and eventually deported to Treblinka, where they were killed. The seven Jews hidden by the Wyrzykowski family were not the only survivors of the Jedwabne massacre.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nA greatly expanded version of the findings, in 203 pages of Polish text, was issued by the IPN on 30 June 2003.  The original version of 9 July 2002 appears as the concluding five pages of this document. Pages 60\u2013160 contain summaries of the testimonies of numerous witnesses interviewed by the IPN. The full 203-page text detailing the government-led investigation was published on the IPN website.<ref name=\"jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf\"/> It was supplemented by two volumes of studies and documents in Polish: ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'', vol. 1: ''Studies'' (525 pages) and vol. 2: ''Documents'' (1,034 pages).<ref name=MachcewiczandPersak2002>Machcewicz, Pawe\u0142; Persak, Krzysztof (2002). ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego''. [https://www.academia.edu/30085727/_Wok%C3%B3%C5%82_Jedwabnego_Jedwabne_and_Beyond_Vol._1_Studia_Studies_eds._Pawe%C5%82_Machcewicz_Krzysztof_Persak_Warszawa_IPN_2002_526_pp Vol. 1: ''Studia'']; Vol. 2: ''Dokumenty''. Warsaw: Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej. {{isbn|978-8389078087}}.</ref>\n\nKieres delivered the IPN report at 27 February 2002 session of the Polish parliament. A small opposition party, the [[League of Polish Families]] (''LPR''), called Kieres a \"servant of the Jews\" and blamed him and President [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] for \"stoning the Polish nation\". LPR MP [[Antoni Macierewicz]] made an official complaint against the IPN's conclusion that ethnic Poles and not the Germans had committed the massacre.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\">{{harvnb|Michlic|2002}}.</ref>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nPolish cultural anthropologist Ludwik Stomma questioned the IPN's downward revision of the number of victims, objected to the IPN's conclusion that the massacre was \"committed directly by Poles but instigated by the Germans\", and said that this formulation was meant to please the political right.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\"/>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n[[Joanna Michlic]] described the activities of the IPN as \"a very professional forensic investigation\". She added: \"Members of the IPN team headed by Leon Kieres had refused to bend to the version of the crime presented in the strongly defensive camp, and thus came under attack in the nationalist press.\"{{sfn|Michlic|2002|p=30}}\n\nAmerican historian [[Jan T. Gross]] praised the conduct of the IPN investigation.<ref name=\"JS\">El\u017cbieta Po\u0142udnik, Andrzej Kaczy\u0144ski, [http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/Pol/jednak_sasiedzi.htm Wyniki \u015bledztwa w sprawie Jedwabnego - Jednak s\u0105siedzi], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 June 2002</ref><ref name=\"gw\">{{cite news | url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,76498,3468035.html | title=Jedwabne i \"Strach\" | work=Gazeta Wyborcza | date=9 July 2006 | accessdate=1 January 2012 | author=J\u0119drysik Mi\u0142ada}}</ref> His findings were incorporated into a Polish secondary-school history text.<ref name=\"Michlic 2002\"/>{{page needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nOn 30 June 2003 prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew announced that the investigation of \"the mass murder of at least 340 Polish citizens of Jewish nationality in Jedwabne on July 10, 1941\" had discovered no living suspected perpetrators in the Jedwabne atrocity who had not already been brought to justice, and so the IPN investigation was closed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ipn.gov.pl/wydzial-prasowy/komunikaty/komunikat-dot.-postanowienia-o-umorzeniu-sledztwa-w-sprawie-zabojstwa-obywateli |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620004217/http://ipn.gov.pl/wydzial-prasowy/komunikaty/komunikat-dot.-postanowienia-o-umorzeniu-sledztwa-w-sprawie-zabojstwa-obywateli |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 June 2013 |trans-title=A communiqu\u00e9 regarding the decision to end the investigation of the murder of Polish citizens of Jewish nationality in Jedwabne on 10 July 1941 |date=30 June 2003 |title=Komunikat dot. postanowienia o umorzeniu \u015bledztwa w sprawie zab\u00f3jstwa obywateli polskich narodowo\u015bci \u017cydowskiej w Jedwabnem w dniu 10 lipca 1941 r. |publisher =Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej (IPN) |language=pl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |trans-title=Judgement to End Investigation |title=Postanowienie o umorzeniu \u015bledztwa | publisher=Instytut Pami\u0119ci Narodowej (IPN) |url=https://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/pdf/jedwabne_postanowienie.pdf |language=pl}}</ref><!--this needs a scholarly source: After the investigation, new archival evidence confirmed that the Germans employed paid agents to instigate pogroms. Prosecutor Ignatiew stated: \"It is obvious that Poles could not just do whatever they pleased in the German-occupied territories. They could not therefore have organized pogroms. These were organized by the Germans. As the documents show, the Germans readied themselves to organize pogroms of Jews and had advance intelligence (from their agents) as to who among the Poles bore hatred toward Jews because Jews had denounced their relatives to the Soviets, and who was a bandit who would kill if paid money. And it was those people whom they chose to carry out the pogroms, turning them into ordinary criminal gangs.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Agent Gestapo inspirowa\u0142 pogromy w 1941 r. w okolicach \u0141om\u017cy|last=Bia\u0142ous|first=Adam|date= 11\u201312 July 2009|work=Nasz Dziennik|access-date=}}</ref>-->\n\n==Documentaries==\nPolish film-maker [[Agnieszka Arnold]] made two documentary films interviewing witnesses of the Jedwabne massacre.  ''(Gdzie m\u00f3j starszy syn Kain)'' (1999, ''Where is my elder son Cain'')  included interviews with Szmul Wassersztajn, and the daughter of the owner of the barn where the massacre took place. ''(S\u0105siedzi)'' (2001, ''Neighbors'') dealt with the subject in greater depth. Jan Gross wrote a book of the same name, with Arnold's agreement as to title.<ref>[https://www.wilmatheater.org/blog/agnieszka-arnold-documentary-filmmaker-%E2%80%93-part-one Agnieszka Arnold documentary filmmaker], Wilma Theater</ref> \n\nProfessor Jan Tomasz Gross also appears in Haim Hecht's documentary ''Two Barns'' (2014) along other prominent Holocaust historians, Literature Nobel-prize winner [[Wislawa Szymborska]], and Professor [[Shevah Weiss]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/104504131|title=Two Barns - English Version|first=Roy|last=Mandel|date=27 August 2014|via=Vimeo}}</ref>\n\n==Other monographs==\n===''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (2002)===\n''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' (\"Jedwabne and Beyond\") is the official two-volume [[Institute of National Remembrance]] (''IPN'') publication of documents produced by the 2000-2003 IPN investigation. Volume 1, ''Studies'' (525 pages) contains historical and legal studies written by historians working for IPN. Volume 2, ''Documents'' (1,034 pages) contains original documents collected by the IPN investigation.<ref name=MachcewiczandPersak2002/> Included are testimonies by Jews on various antisemitic acts committed by Poles, as well as testimonies by non-Jewish Polish schoolteachers deported to Siberia, who reported that Jewish communists had been moved into positions of authority in the Soviet occupation apparatus in eastern Poland.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}{{efn|Volume 2 of ''Wok\u00f3\u0142 Jedwabnego'' includes a Polish translation (from the Hebrew) of a memoir written by Chaya Finkelsztajn of Radzi\u0142\u00f3w, describing conditions under the 1939\u20131941 Soviet occupation and the subsequent 1941 [[Operation Barbarossa]] German invasion. Chaya Finkelsztajn survived the 1941\u20131945 German occupation, under perilous circumstances, after a Polish Catholic priest agreed to baptise her as a Christian. She later emigrated to Israel, where she wrote her memoir.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}}}\n\n===''The Neighbors Respond'' (2003)===\nAn extensive collection of articles from the Polish and international debate, in English translation, was published in 2003 as ''The Neighbors Respond: The Controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland'' by [[Joanna Michlic]] and [[Antony Polonsky]] of [[Brandeis University]]. The book includes articles from Polish and other historians, the IPN's ''Findings of Investigation S1/00/Zn into the Murder of Polish Citizens of Jewish Origin in the Town of Jedwabne on 10 July 1941'' (2002), and essays from Polish newspapers such as ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'' and ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]''. The collection features archival documents and essays covering the entire 1939\u20131941 period. Contributors include [[Anna Bikont]], [[David Engel]], [[Israel Gutman]], [[Adam Michnik]], [[Bogdan Musial]], [[Dariusz Stola]], and [[Tomasz Strzembosz]].{{sfn|Polonsky|Michlic|2003}}\n\n===''The Massacre in Jedwabne, 10 July 1941'' (2005)===\n[[Marek Jan Chodakiewicz]]'s book ''The Massacre in Jedwabne, 10 July 1941: Before, During, and After'' challenges Gross's interpretation of the events.{{sfn|Holc|2008}} It suggests that four or five truckloads of armed [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] men from [[\u0141om\u017ca]] terrorized the local population before leading Jews and Poles to the crime scene.{{sfn|Chodakiewicz|2005}}{{page needed|date=April 2020}} He wrote: \"the killing of between 200 and 400 Jews (not 1,600, as claimed by Gross) was conceived, supervised and executed by German police, with only limited involvement by a very small number of Poles, some of whom were coerced into participating. Even then, the few willing Polish collaborators included ''Volksdeutsche'' (Polish citizens of German origin) and petty criminals.\"{{sfn|Michlic|Polonsky|2008}}<!--add Chodakiewicz-->\n\n[[Piotr Wr\u00f3bel]] wrote that Chodakiewicz's aim, stated in the introduction, was to show that Gross was wrong. \nChodakiewicz argues that all the primary sources are wrong or worthless, including the testimony of Szmul Wassersztajn, the investigation of the 22 suspects for the 1949 trial, and the partial exhumation of the bodies. \"And yet,\" writes Wr\u00f3bel, \"Chodakiewicz is able to present his recreation of the crime. It was well preplanned, initiated by the Germans, and utterly lacked any pogrom-like spontaneity.\" Wr\u00f3bel acknowledged that Chodakiewicz made some good arguments but wrote that they are \"overshadowed by numerous flaws\", lack a sense of proportion, and make selective use of information from sources that support Chodakiewicz's view. According to Wr\u00f3bel, the book has a \"visible political agenda\" and is \"difficult to read, unoriginal, irritating, and unconvincing\".{{sfn|Wr\u00f3bel|2006b}}\n\n[[Peter D. Stachura]] described the book positively. \"The important debate about Polish-Jewish relations must continue to develop on the basis of informed, impartial scrutiny, analysis and interpretation, with reference to authenticated, solid evidence, as Professor Chodakiewicz has so ably demonstrated.\"{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In response, [[Joanna Michlic]] and [[Antony Polonsky]] wrote a letter in 2008 to the editor of ''[[History (journal)|History]]'', expressing their strong disagreement with the \"content and tone\" of Stachura's review. According to Michlic and Polonsky, Chodakiewicz's conclusions and Stachura's review were \"very far from those reached by most historians\" who have examined the Jedwabne pogrom, including Poland's [[Institute of National Remembrance]]. They wrote that Chodakiewicz and Stachura \"uphold a view of the Polish past which seeks to return to an untenable vision of modern Poland as solely victim and hero&nbsp;... It is a matter of considerable regret to us that you have allowed your journal to be used to advance this neo-nationalist agenda.\"{{sfn|Michlic|Polonsky|2008}} Stachura took exception to their letter. ''History'' declined to publish his reply; instead, it was posted on the website of ''Glaukopis'', a Polish journal.{{sfn|Stachura|2008}}\n\n==2001 anniversary==\n[[File:Aleksander Kwasniewski - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Polish president [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] apologized for the massacre in 2001.<ref name=Connolly11July2001/>]]\nIn July 2001, on the 60th anniversary of the pogrom, Polish president [[Aleksander Kwa\u015bniewski]] attended a ceremony at Jedwabne where he apologized for the massacre: \"We can have no doubt that here in Jedwabne Polish citizens were killed at the hands of fellow citizens&nbsp;... I apologise in my own name, and in the name of those Poles whose conscience is shattered by that crime.\" The ceremony was attended by Catholic and Jewish religious leaders and survivors of the pogrom. Most of the 2,000 locals of Jedwabne, including the town's priest, boycotted the ceremony in protest against the apology.<ref name=Connolly11July2001>{{cite news|first=Kate|last=Connolly |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/jul/11/poland |title=Poland says sorry for slaughter of Jews |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 July 2001}}</ref>\n\n[[Shevah Weiss]], Israeli Ambassador to Poland, also delivered a speech. \"Living among us also are Holocaust survivors whose lives were saved as a result of the brave actions of their Polish neighbors,\" he said. He praised Poland's research and investigation process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/eng/jedwabne.htm |title=Jedwabne 10 July\u2014Reports and Opinions |publisher=The Canadian Foundation of Polish-Jewish Heritage, Montreal Chapter}}</ref>\n\nNobel Peace Prize recipient and former Polish President [[Lech Walesa]] commented about the apology: \"The Jedwabne crime was a revenge for the cooperation of the Jewish community with the Soviet occupant. The Poles have already apologized many times to the Jews; we are waiting for the apology from the other side because many Jews were scoundrels.\"<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524200234/https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 | url-status=dead | archive-date=24 May 2012 | title=Facing Jedwabne - American Jewish Committee}}</ref>\n\nA March 2001 poll conducted by the Polish daily ''Rzeczpospolita'' found that one-half of Poles were aware of the Jedwabne massacre; among Poles with a higher education the proportion rose to 81 percent. Forty percent of respondents supported Kwa\u015bniewski's decision to apologize. A majority condemned the actions of the Poles involved in the massacre.<ref>[http://archiwum.rp.pl/artykul/328841_Wiemy_i_potepiamy.html  Wiemy i pot\u0119piamy (We know, and we condemn).] Republic of Poland. Archives.</ref>\n\nA monument had been placed in Jedwabne in the 1960s with the inscription: \"Site of the Suffering of the Jewish Population. The Gestapo and the Nazi Gendarmerie Burned Alive 1600 People July 10, 1941.\"<ref name=Rosenfeld>Alvin H. Rosenfeld, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120524200234/https://www.ajc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=ijITI2PHKoG&b=846743&ct=1093355 'Facing Jedwabne.'] ''American Jewish Committee.'' Retrieved 8 November 2012.</ref> This was replaced by a new monument in July 2001, with inscriptions in Polish, Hebrew and Yiddish: \"To the Memory of Jews from Jedwabne and the Surrounding Area, Men, Women, and Children, Co-inhabitants of this Land, Who Were Murdered and Burned Alive on This Spot on July 10, 1941.\"<ref name=Rosenfeld /> In August 2001 Jedwabne mayor Krzysztof Godlewski, a pioneer for the commemoration of the massacre, resigned in protest at the local council's lack of majority support for it.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/jedwabne-mayor-resigns-over-memorial-to-jews/article4150944/ | title=Jedwabne mayor resigns over memorial to Jews}}</ref> He became a recipient of the [[Jan Karski]] Humanitarian Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/eng/listopad_former_mayor.html|title=The Polish-Jewish Heritage Foundation of Canada, Montreal Chapter - The former Mayor of Jedwabne talks about himself and the anniversary celebrations|website=www.polish-jewish-heritage.org}}</ref><!--\n==Events, 2006\u2013present==\nAt a round-table discussion on 7 July 2006, [[Jan T. Gross]] said, \"I repeat three times in the book (''[[Neighbors: The Destruction of the Jewish Community in Jedwabne, Poland|Neighbors]]'') that the murder happened by order of the Germans\" (''\"mord by\u0142 z rozkazu Niemc\u00f3w\"'').<ref name=\"gw\"/>\n\nIn 2009 Polish politician [[Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski]] was criticized by Britain's [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and some British journalists for having in 2001 opposed a Polish national apology for the Jedwabne massacre. The criticism came after Kaminski was made chairperson of the [[European Parliament]]'s group of [[European Conservatives and Reformists]].<ref name=\"thejc\"/> Kami\u0144ski denied that his opposition to an apology stemmed from antisemitism. He was defended by the Conservatives and some journalists, including the editor of the ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'', Stephen Pollard.<ref name=\"thejc6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/comment/analysis/20818/analysis-kaminski-our-friend-a-smear-campaign |title=Analysis: Kaminski is our friend \u2013 this is a smear campaign |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=8 November 2010.</ref><ref>Hannan, Daniel. [http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/danielhannan/100005218/accusing-euro-sceptics-of-anti-semitism-is-the-most-shameful-tactic-yet/ Accusing Euro-sceptics of anti-Semitism is the most shameful tactic yet]. ''The Daily Telegraph''.</ref>\n\nA 2009 play ''Our Class'' by Polish [[playwright]] Tadeusz S\u0142obodzianek, performed in Britain,<ref>Nathan, John (11 September 2009). [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article6830524.ece \"Our Class and the bloody history of Poland that refuses to die\"]. ''The Times''.</ref> deals with a massacre of Jews by Poles in a small town during the Holocaust. A review in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' argued that the play misrepresented Poles as \"just itching for the German invasion as the excuse to give violent vent to their deep-rooted anti-Semitism\" and \"too often [...] looked like an object lesson in gross simplification.\"<ref>Cavendish, Dominic (9 November 2009). [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/6530381/Is-Our-Class-at-the-National-Theatre-really-such-a-reliable-history-lesson.html \"Is Our Class at the National Theatre really such a reliable history lesson?\"]. ''The Daily Telegraph''.</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2011 Poland's President [[Bronis\u0142aw Komorowski]] asked for forgiveness at a ceremony marking the 70th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/news/poland-asks-jews-for-forgiveness-on-70th-anniversary-of-yedvabne-massacre-1.372579 | work=Haaretz| title=Poland asks Jews for forgiveness on 70th anniversary of Yedvabne massacre  | date=11 July 2011 | accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"jta\">{{cite news| url=http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/07/11/3088484/polands-president-asks-jewish-forgiveness-at-memorial-ceremony| work=JTA| title=Poland's president asks for forgiveness at Jedwabne memorial| date=11 July 2011| accessdate=11 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713104934/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/07/11/3088484/polands-president-asks-jewish-forgiveness-at-memorial-ceremony| archive-date=13 July 2011| url-status=dead}}</ref> It was reported on 1 September 2011 that the Jedwabne memorial had been defaced with a swastika and graffiti that read \"They were flammable\" and \"I don't apologize for Jedwabne.\"<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news|last=Andrusz |first=Katya |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-02/polish-president-condemns-vandalism-of-jewish-massacre-memorial.html |title=Polish President Condemns Vandalism of Jewish Massacre Memorial |publisher=Bloomberg |date= 2 September 2011|accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/09/01/3089197/memorial-to-jedwabne-pogrom-vandalized-in-poland \"Memorial to Jedwabne pogrom vandalized\"]. ''Jewish Telegraphic Agency'', 1 September 2011. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929223813/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/09/01/3089197/memorial-to-jedwabne-pogrom-vandalized-in-poland |date=29 September 2012 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/world/article/memorial_to_jedwabne_pogrom_vandalized_in_poland_20110901/|title=Vandal defaced monument|date=1 September 2011|publisher=JewishJournal.com|location=Los Angeles|access-date=1 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150404050511/http://www.jewishjournal.com/world/article/memorial_to_jedwabne_pogrom_vandalized_in_poland_20110901/|archive-date=4 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Poland launched an anti-hate crime investigation involving the country's domestic [[intelligence agency]], the [[Agencja Bezpiecze\u0144stwa Wewn\u0119trznego|ABW]].<ref name=\"www8\">{{cite web|author=Rp.pl |url=http://www.rp.pl/artykul/17,710609-ABW-szuka-wandali--ktorzy-zniszczyli-pomnik-w-Jedwabnem.html |title=ABW szuka wandali, kt\u00f3rzy zniszczyli pomnik w Jedwabnem |publisher=rp.pl |date= |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"PAP\">{{cite web | url=http://www.deon.pl/wiadomosci/polska/art,9442,pomnik-w-jedwabnem-i-usuwanie-zniszczen.html | title=Pomnik w Jedwabnem i usuwanie zniszcze\u0144 (''Memorial in Jedwabne, cleaning of damage'') | publisher=DEON.pl after [[Polska Agencja Prasowa]] | date=1 September 2011 | accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 television interview, Polish education minister [[Anna Zalewska]] expressed doubt regarding whether Poles had participated in the pogrom.<ref name=Aderet>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/1.731391 |title=Two Senior Polish Ministers Deny Poles' Involvement in Massacres of Jews |work=[[Haaretz]] |first=Ofer |last=Aderet |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=30 December 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/polish-education-minister-says-massacres-of-jews-an-opinion/ |title=Polish education minister says massacres of Jews an 'opinion' |work= [[The Times of Israel]] |first=Vanessa |last=Gera |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name=Wprost/> When the interviewer asked whether Poles had killed their Jewish neighbors, Zalewska described that as one viewpoint and said other researchers had reached other conclusions.<ref name=Aderet/><ref name=Wprost/> In a radio interview two months later, she said that Poles shared responsibility for the massacre, while adding that the country was under [[German occupation of Poland|Nazi German occupation]] and that the [[Polish Underground State|continuity Polish resistance state]] punished the murder of Jews.<ref name=Wprost>{{cite web |url=https://www.wprost.pl/kraj/10022256/Minister-zmienila-zdanie-Polacy-wspolodpowiedzialni-za-pogrom-w-Jedwabnem.html |title=Minister zmieni\u0142a zdanie. 'Polacy wsp\u00f3\u0142odpowiedzialni za pogrom w Jedwabnem' |trans-title=The minister changed her mind. 'Poles are jointly responsible for the pogrom in Jedwabne' |work=[[Wprost]] |date=7 September 2017 |accessdate=1 January 2018 }}</ref>-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Aftermath (2012 film)|''Aftermath'' (2012 film)]]\n* [[Anti-Jewish violence in Poland, 1944\u20131946]]\n* [[The Holocaust in Poland]]\n* [[Kielce pogrom]]\n* [[List of anti-Jewish pogroms in Poland during World War II]]\n* [[Polish Righteous Among the Nations]]\n* [[Kaunas pogrom]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|26em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|26em|refs=\n<!--<ref name=\"Ignatiew-1\"> These are the official findings of the Institute of National Remembrance, \"confirmed by the number of victims in the two graves, according to the estimate of the archeological and anthropological team participating in the exhumation,\" wrote prosecutor Rados\u0142aw J. Ignatiew in [https://books.google.com/books?id=AfeGB5yz0ooC&pg=PA134 ''The neighbors respond: the controversy over the Jedwabne Massacre in Poland'' By Antony Polonsky, Joanna B. Michlic. Page 134] [[Princeton University Press]], 2004. {{ISBN|0-691-11306-8}}</ref>-->\n<!-- <ref name=\"JS\">El\u017cbieta Po\u0142udnik, Andrzej Kaczy\u0144ski, [http://www.polish-jewish-heritage.org/Pol/jednak_sasiedzi.htm Wyniki \u015bledztwa w sprawie Jedwabnego - Jednak s\u0105siedzi], ''[[Rzeczpospolita]]'', 10 June 2002</ref> -->\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n{{refbegin|26em}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Baker |first1=Julius |last2=Tzinovitz |first2=Moshe |title=Yedwabne: History and Memorial Book |date=1980 |editor1-last=Baker |editor1-first=Julius| editor2-last=Baker |editor2-first=Jacob |publisher=The Yedwabner Societies in Israel and the United States of America |location=Jerusalem and New York |url=https://www.jewishgen.org/Yizkor/Jedwabne/yed001.html#5 |ref=harv |chapter=My Hometown Yedwabne, Province of Lomza, Poland}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bikont |first1=Anna |author-link=Anna Bikont |translator = Alissa Valles |title=The Crime and the Silence: Confronting the Massacre of Jews in Wartime Jedwabne |date=2015 |orig-year=2004 |publisher=Farrar, Strauss and Giroux |location=New York |isbn=978-0-374-17879-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Browning | first = Christopher R. | authorlink = Christopher Browning | title = The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939 \u2013 March 1942 | year = 2004 | publisher = University of Nebraska Press and Yad Vashem| location = Lincoln and Jerusalem | isbn = 0-8032-1327-1 | ref = harv | url = https://archive.org/details/originsoffinalso00brow}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cesarani |first1=David |authorlink1=David Cesarani |title=Final Solution: The Fate of the Jews 1933\u20131949 |date=2016 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Chodakiewicz |first1=Marek Jan |authorlink = Marek Jan Chodakiewicz |title=Research Before Conclusion: The Problems of Shock Therapy in Jedwabne |journal=Glaukopis |location= |date=2001 |volume= |issue=|pages= |doi= |url=https://www.iwp.edu/wp-content/uploads/2002/01/MJ-Chodakiewicz-Shock-Therapy-Jedwabne-Feb-2001.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| first = Marek Jan | last = Chodakiewicz | authorlink = | title=The Massacre in Jedwabne, July 10, 1941: Before, During, After | publisher=East European Monographs, distributed by Columbia University Press |location=Boulder, CO| year=2005 | isbn=978-0-88033-554-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Crago |first1=Laura |editor1-last=Megargee | editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=Dean |editor2-first=Martin |title=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945 |title-link=Encyclope